a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.tq8owr91hbb0">7.3 &ldquo;Brave New World&rdquo;</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.dmdcunyua7dv">8 Not a valueless pile of words (uncommitted)</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.mrp2a2w0cv6">The process and depth of spiritual growth</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.x0p8a49v9lqk">Your state</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.uostdmhfc8e4">10.2 Distractions</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.ozqkhr6j19ol">Charisepignosis and Legalism</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.i6ojdzrhwwok">11.2 A facebook communication with a legalist</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.lmvezps5fwol">Rest-oration and Re-velation</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.pr68ba8lg3">The Church</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.jj4kbjebc7gv">Two Gods</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.49phi3qxvkgm">The Fast Track</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.7ihhu3kw9i5l">The new revelation</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.k78mko84k8vi">Grace discovered and received</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.mbg4dyjp9k43">A mini gospel in itself</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.rrns6viv4ug7">Charis: The active hub &nbsp;(related Greek words)</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.lvj2bkkwdjj">Core Word Group Table</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.5ne8caadtcgx">{Aspects/facets - love, joy etc? (purpose, direction, discernment, clarity) or Grace at work?}</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.ggtm8d2kh84r">Grace that grows</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.pm3me43cnt1">Grace is not license</a></span></p><p class="c36"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.1vb1zkurksar">Part 2: Grace in your life</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.fznt05jmnkar">19.2 My anxiety in writing this</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.wuocp1rbhxjx">Humility</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.2n0ea5hc2qoi">The journey</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.61cta79iluhh">21.12 The urge - god starting the journey</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.k6wrekq80e0n">21.13 The commitment</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.8s5pa4e0n24u">21.16 The change, the transformation, also deserves expansion.</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.m2vjtl6mjlbl">21.17 Expect the unexpected</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.lkvgh8j5l6ra">21.18 The Wow factor (Boom)</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.3bvsrrv84is3">22 That nudge inside</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.mq44ob5sdkgb">22.3 The holding factor</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.j5wkbwuhu0xs">22.5 Holding and perseverance</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.klbyrojwx4h6">Decision Matrix</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.sdw2rq2xhtot">How we position ourselves.</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.qqyu35qmsxeg">The power and importance of prayer</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.lgiz76oe0nvs">No Disruption</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.t001kq2xtht">25.3 Don&rsquo;t fall</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.fagf781bbwc4">Prayer - constant *requirements, opportunity for God&#39;s glory *massive, etc</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.w6mli845p5zo">Sell all to buy the field - what you value is in your heart</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.bqc8qwfg9e9y">27.2 Are you spiritually and emotionally healthy?</a></span></p><p class="c36"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.a3q4jpn7ivji">33 &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.v7eeiev0u9jg">Notes</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.dzhjcosbnkpb">Etymology</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.jpw4qd5e810n">Scriptures of good things from God</a></span></p><p class="c36 c59"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.jc4gw2b8schp">Xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.4sz1xuekdovr">5 minute conversion technique</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.jfir7pr7n1h">D. Charis and the fruit of the Spirit</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.o0x457klmn34">3. Practical next step</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.h51cmqzf19o">1. Opening: Redefining God&rsquo;s &ldquo;R &amp; R&rdquo;</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.irzf8dg2y8m4">2. Restoration: Grace rebuilding relationship</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.ey48kgknp6af">3. Revelation: Grace opening eyes and ears</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.63s74zx5lnzy">4. How R &amp; R fits the charis flow</a></span></p><p class="c23"><span class="c16"><a class="c19" href="#h.rcvpzitf3zrl">5. Possible closing angle</a></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1 </span></p><h1 class="c54" id="h.3dj9qhv1adrp"><span class="c26 c51">What is grace - introduction</span></h1><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.1 &nbsp;Purpose of the book. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This book will focus on explaining Grace and, more so, explaining charis, the word translated into Grace (What grace/charis is, Understanding it). &nbsp;Then it will focus on positioning your life to receive Grace / Charis (How to get it). The greater you are, the less value this book will have for you, if you know it all, stop reading; I have nothing for you. After all &ldquo;...God resists the proud, but He gives grace to the humble;&rdquo; 1 Peter 5:5b</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.udcphw4krbe6"><span class="c29 c26">Prelude</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.2 Yeshua / Jesus naming note. </span></p><p class="c2"><span>First things first, the name Jesus only came into existence 600 to 800 years ago, as the Letter J did not exist before that; it was Iesus, and that too was a transliteration of the original Yeshua. Please note that the only reliable person to write about him during his life here on Earth from that region was Josephus, who wrote &ldquo;Yeshua&rdquo;, so I can be 99.99% confident his name was Yeshua. I&#39;ll quite happily use Jesus when speaking to those who don&#39;t know this, though, for </span><span class="c88">this book</span><span class="c1">, as you now know, I&#39;ll use Yeshua.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.3 The power of impotence -God using weak vessels </span></p><p class="c2"><span>We tend to respect and sometimes honour those who claim to be nothing, as that is an ideal of the Bible. So sometimes the claim to be nothing may even come from pride in the Biblical sense. God has moved through proud people who express their importance, whose names and photos are magnified on the cover of their books. Sometimes they reveal wondrous aspects of God or keys to Christian living. If God can use the proud and egotistical in light of verses like {find verses</span><span>&nbsp;&gt;&rdquo;resists the proud&rdquo; and &ldquo;servant of all&rdquo;&lt;}.</span><span>&nbsp;Then I pray these words inspire you, as I don&#39;t have the power, knowledge or business connections to deliver revelation. This is not about me or what I have discovered; I&#39;m just the conduit. I merely express</span><span>&nbsp;(quite poorly)</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;what God wants you to perceive. It&#39;s the dawn of a new era. I perceive people coming to a new understanding of God and a new structure of discipleship.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.4 Why the understanding is being renewed.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Stop right there... Some people are thinking &ldquo;Are you saying the way people are discipled is changing? If so, could that be against the Bible? Besides, the Bible doesn&#39;t change, so our understanding of God won&#39;t change&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">OK, OK, let me answer discipleship first. The concept of evangelism and harvesting go hand in hand, and discipleship is the process of training new Christians, so it&#39;s the last stage of evangelism. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Yeshua said in Mat {XXX} The fields are white for harvest, and the workers are few. He, of course, was using that parable for Evangelism. They used to cut the grain (by hand), thrash it and grind it to flour... Do we no longer turn grain into flour? We do, yet in the natural, the methods have changed with technology. We use machines now to process a lot more quickly. To a degree, evangelism happens more through the technology of TV. Though it stops there. For far too long, evangelists have not discipled (and in many cases are not called to). They&#39;re harvesting and leaving the grain to rot.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&#39;s time to wake up, it&#39;s a modern world and technology has changed everything... though evangelism and especially discipleship have not really changed. So I&#39;m not talking about the goal (flour), it hasn&#39;t changed. We can now look at the process and improve it so none of the grain rots (or very little). We still want people to discover God as he is in the Bible and build a strong relationship with God, then for them to find their call, train in it, launch it and surround them with a community of like-minded believers. Yet in this modern world of KPIs, we don&#39;t have discipleship KPIs... Why not? Are KPIs not effective? Do they not sponsor improvement? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I now present that we don&#39;t even know what the KPIs of Christianity should be! It&#39;s time to write the manual, the training programs and set those KPIs so we can see what needs to be improved. The church could see that TV worked as a mass media, so many ministers went on TV. Since then, companies have introduced training and KPIs as they could see the benefit. We, the church, haven&#39;t even considered them. It&#39;s time to modernise that, like the early (and modern) TV evangelists. Evangelism and discipleship go hand in hand, yet we have neglected that fact for millennia. It&#39;s time to go back to the initial church (in many ways) and start producing &quot;Timothys&rsquo;&#39;&#39; (saved, trained and launched into ministry). All new Christians should be led all the way to their own ministry, rather than left to rot.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">All I&#39;m saying is let&#39;s go back to the original process of complete discipleship, but use modern systems that have not yet been trialled by the Church. If the message I&#39;m getting is wrong and not an illumination (from darkness rather than light). Then cut it out when it can be seen to be in error.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A new understanding of God. Well, that is a far bigger question to answer. First, it&#39;s not new, as what I&#39;ll express is merely the understanding of God that first-century Christians knew but has been lost in linguistics. We no longer speak Greek, especially the Biblical Greek, as Greek has changed (like English, we no longer say thee, thou and many words that no one would understand today). In this book, we will look at just a few simple Greek words that seem to have been lost in translation... The meaning hasn&#39;t changed, but we no longer teach the meaning or importance of these words... Our teachers don&#39;t even know what was written about them in even our standard Bible concordances/dictionaries (Strongs&#39; and Thayer&#39;s). We no longer understand the base words for Grace and Servant. They are extremely important, and I feel it&#39;ll take 3 books to explain them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.5 Why this book, burden, revelation, and the need to grow.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So who is Joe Average, and why this book? OK, If you guessed Joe Average is an alias. You&#39;re right. The person typing this is merely a secretary taking a message and delivering it, yet whose name goes on this work? I&#39;m not taking this dictation from a human; I&#39;m just writing what I feel God wants said. So, I can&#39;t take credit, nor do I have anyone to credit but God. It simply must be an alias. Also, the glory is God&#39;s, and there is no glory in being &quot;The average Joe&quot;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&#39;ll go back to the start, this next part 1.6 is what I&#39;d written upon the first inspiration, and take it from there, (it includes all self-wrestling, and maybe paradoxes)...</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.6</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Wow, what a week, many things getting in the way, disrupting the work I needed to get done, culminating in the ultimate disruption that changed me. Sure, I was heading on a narrow path before the events of this week, yet due to it, I&rsquo;m not only behind schedule, but now my path is narrower, and I have even more clarity of that which I only see dimly. Sure, things got in the way, yet I know they were meant to be. I believe in God (expand here?)? I see God took me from the work he has laid on my heart, in which so strongly that I feel at a loss when I&rsquo;m taken from it. Yet God did exactly that, with a chain of events that opened my mind. Not that my mind was not open to him or to new things, in fact, the opposite. Because my mind is open to being influenced by God to reveal new things, I am in a position to learn.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This brings me to a dilemma, I guess you can see I seek to now reveal this to you, yet beyond that opening, I wonder how. That may seem a strange way to begin an exposure, yet there is an urge within me that I am very clear here. I&rsquo;m going to speak of x x x in ways you likely have not heard before. And as I type these very words, I&rsquo;m still wondering what I&rsquo;m going to say next, as I know what I wish to express, but have no idea how to start. In fact, I just took a break after that last sentence to do some of the regular ministry activities and gather thoughts. I just said to someone, &ldquo;It looks like I have more work to do now, two books,&rdquo; as I can see there may be two aspects of this, yet as I walked away, there was a nudge inside me saying three&hellip; I instantly considered the testimony side of this, which may be one of those two, but my testimony as a whole&hellip; Maybe. I&rsquo;m not sure. Though what I am sure of and what is relevant here is the nudge itself. As that nudge inside, one of the ways God communicates with you is the very purpose of this book. Again, I need to expand, and again, I am not sure how, but God will bring that too. I feel this will be a lot of pausing to &ldquo;wait on God&rdquo;, not that God is slow to act, I think we are slow to listen. Which brings me to another aspect of this. How we position ourselves. Before all that, though, what I&rsquo;m now writing and why has just come to my mind&hellip; I feel God saying here, &ldquo;Expect the unexpected&rdquo; Sure, I know a corny use of an old saying. Maybe God is saying through me just now, that he&rsquo;ll make it familiar to you, so this is a little easier to understand. I say &ldquo;maybe&rdquo; there with less confidence, as I feel that explanation is more my words. I don&rsquo;t know what outcome God plans, but I know that nudge, I&rsquo;m getting to know it at least. It&rsquo;s a compulsion within that can be so strong you can even feel a&hellip; (no words here explain a spiritual feeling that has what seems to be a physical feeling as well). &hellip;feel a pressure, maybe ever so slight, maybe pressure is not the right word, yet a sensation nonetheless, around or on the heart.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Expect the unexpected&rdquo;, I wonder why I&rsquo;m even writing much of this, as I&rsquo;m confident I could write a message that gets to the point in a compelling way. So, even this message is unexpected for me. I have a great sense of amazement and anticipation merely to put these things into words. And I look at the words I&rsquo;m using and think &ldquo;I could do so much better&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ll simply have to trust God, and trust that he doesn&rsquo;t want depth here (or just yet), he wants simplicity. I would have stopped reading this by now; it&rsquo;s disjointed in my mind and not even leading to the point. So, more than express to you those three simple corny words. &ldquo;Expect the unexpected&rdquo;, I&rsquo;m having to go through the unexpected to get them out. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This whole week expanded my comprehension of charis even more. Maybe I&rsquo;m getting overexcited about this, but I&rsquo;m constantly learning so much more about one simple (or maybe not so simple) Greek word. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I reflect now on the many revelations I&rsquo;ve had that came at times when I could not record them, and those that were quickly disrupted by the issues of life. I&rsquo;m led to add that from them, I know this text/work/book falls awfully short of what I&rsquo;d like to express. God will inspire us, yet it&rsquo;s then up to us to find the value, importance and words (which can often be found when you know the word and how God uses charis to teach). We are to discover the depths of God and Godliness, by first putting our old life aside and then choosing to grow in love for the things of God. Do you love the things of God so much that they are all that&rsquo;s on your mind most of the time? &nbsp;You just want more of every aspect of God and Godliness, so it&rsquo;s your obvious compulsion?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I feel these words will suffice for some. Yet I wish I had the words that would move everyone to a deeper understanding and growth in God, ultimately producing a fruitful, plentiful harvest of Godliness (in action beyond mere thought). I believe most people have no real idea of where they truly are in their actual relationship with God and where they stand between God and humanity, or the fullness of the call on their lives. I pray these words help.</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.4s5bvwswyigh"><span class="c29 c26">Chapter 1: What is grace</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.7 Ephesians 2:8,9 and the starting point.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Ephesians 2:8,9 &nbsp;for by grace you are saved, through faith, and this is not of yourselves - it is the gift of God, not of works, that no one may boast; (LSV)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How important is this verse? It explains the foundation of salvation&hellip; sort of&hellip; You see, all too much has been lost in translation, and the insufficient modern concept of its meaning. It does explain salvation, not sort of, not partially, but totally; given you have a good understanding of the word grace. And I have not found one person, including well-known ministers, who can explain it beyond &ldquo;Unmerited favour&rdquo;, which you, I pray, will come to see it is far more.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll start with the definitions of &quot; grace &quot; in Strong&#39;s Concordance and Thayer&rsquo;s Lexicon. To lead you in the Greek word translated into Grace is &ldquo;Charis&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ve highlighted the most significant parts with bold lettering. Also, a concordance is an index of words with a basic meaning where a lexicon gives full definitions, senses and examples; so I&rsquo;ll focus on Thayer&rsquo;s definitions</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.fmfqaa239ftr"><span class="c26 c33">1.9 Strong&rsquo;s</span></h3><p class="c2"><span class="c1">G5485</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&#769;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">charis</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">khar&#39;-ece</span></p><p class="c2"><span>From G5463; graciousness (as gratifying), of manner or act (abstract or concrete; literal, figurative or spiritual; </span><span class="c17">especially the divine influence upon the heart, and its reflection in the life</span><span class="c1">; including gratitude): - acceptable, benefit, favour, gift, grace (-ious), joy liberality, pleasure, thank (-s, -worthy).</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Total KJV occurrences: 156</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll focus on the bold words - &ldquo;especially the divine influence upon the heart, and its reflection in the life&hellip;&rdquo; &ldquo;ESPECIALLY&rdquo;. He is saying here that the most important aspect is God influencing our hearts to such a degree that it is evident in our lives.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1.10</span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.mvshopg0rzrz"><span class="c33 c26">Thayers&rsquo;s</span></h3><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-0 start" start="1"><li class="c20 c11 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">grace</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-1 start" start="1"><li class="c37 c66 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">that which affords joy, pleasure, delight, sweetness, charm, loveliness: grace of speech</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-0" start="2"><li class="c20 c11 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">good will, loving-kindness, favour</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-1 start" start="1"><li class="c37 c66 li-bullet-0"><span>of</span><span class="c7">&nbsp;the merciful kindness by which God, exerting his holy influence upon souls, turns them to Christ, keeps, strengthens, increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection, and kindles them to the exercise of the Christian virtues</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-0" start="3"><li class="c11 c20 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">what is due to grace</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-1 start" start="1"><li class="c37 c66 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">the spiritual condition of one governed by the power of divine grace</span></li><li class="c37 c66 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">the token or proof of grace, benefit</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-2 start" start="1"><li class="c37 c68 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">a gift of grace</span></li><li class="c37 c68 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">benefit, bounty</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_b6lhtnozxrzg-0" start="4"><li class="c20 c11 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">thanks, (for benefits, services, favours), recompense, reward</span></li></ol><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Being written in the 1800s, this book have been faithfully updated to modern language to preserve their original meaning; though we are more likely to say &ldquo;gives&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;affords&rdquo; and maybe &ldquo;forceing&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;exerting&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, let&#39;s look at Thayer&#39;s definitions - I&rsquo;ll start with II. &ldquo;the merciful kindness by which God, exerting his holy influence upon souls, turns them to Christ, keeps, strengthens, increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection, and kindles them to the exercise of the Christian virtues&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.11 Grace as more than unmerited favour.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Unmerited favour can be summed up in &ldquo;merciful kindness&rdquo;, the rest takes us far beyond that simple, partial understanding; as here we find the framework of Christianity. If the sacrifice of Christ on the cross is the Foundation of Christianity, then that which sits on the foundation and holds the rest in place is grace (charis); the frame to hold the walls and roof in place.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.12 Grace and predestination / what it does.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&hellip;by which God, exerting (forcing) his holy influence upon souls&hellip; Here&rsquo;s my first revelation. As I had not read the Bible in many years (I was backslidden for decades), I&rsquo;d either forgotten or never really knew of the predestined factor of the Bible. Let&#39;s go there to start</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Ephesians 1:4&ndash;6 &ndash; God &ldquo;chose us in him before the foundation of the world&hellip; In love, he predestined us for adoption to himself as sons through Jesus Christ, according to the purpose of his will.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Ephesians 1:11 &ndash; &ldquo;In him we have obtained an inheritance, having been predestined according to the purpose of him who works all things according to the counsel of his will.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Romans 8:29&ndash;30 &ndash; &ldquo;For those whom he foreknew he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son&hellip; And those whom he predestined he also called, and those whom he called he also justified, and those whom he justified he also glorified.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Romans 9:11&ndash;13, 15&ndash;16, 21&ndash;23 &ndash; About God&rsquo;s purpose of election before Jacob and Esau were born; mercy and hardening grounded in God&rsquo;s will, with the potter/clay imagery.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Our destiny is set in clay, not stone, so we have the free will to struggle against God, yet like a horse being broken in, sooner or later, if you are appointed, you will turn to Christ</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Acts 13:48 &ndash; &ldquo;As many as were appointed to eternal life believed.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">John 6:37, 39 &ndash; Those whom the Father &ldquo;gives&rdquo; to the Son will come to him, and he will lose none of them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">John 10:26&ndash;29 &ndash; Jesus speaks of his sheep, given to him, who hear his voice and cannot be snatched from his hand.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1 Peter 1:1&ndash;2 &ndash; Believers are &ldquo;elect&hellip; according to the foreknowledge of God the Father.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1 Peter 2:8&ndash;9 &ndash; Some &ldquo;stumble because they disobey the word, as they were destined to do,&rdquo; contrasted with believers as &ldquo;a chosen race.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2 Timothy 1:9 &ndash; God &ldquo;saved us and called us&hellip; not because of our works but because of his own purpose and grace, which he gave us in Christ Jesus before the ages began.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2 Thessalonians 2:13 &ndash; &ldquo;God chose you as the firstfruits to be saved, through sanctification by the Spirit and belief in the truth.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Romans 8:28 &ndash; Those who love God are &ldquo;called according to his purpose,&rdquo; leading into the predestination chain in verses 29&ndash;30.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Romans 11:2&ndash;7 &ndash; &ldquo;God has not rejected his people whom he foreknew&hellip; a remnant, chosen by grace.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I Grace</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1 &nbsp;that which affords joy, pleasure, delight, sweetness, charm, loveliness: grace of speech. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Far beyond &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, it gives good things (attributes rather than physical items). </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.13 Backronym, prodigal son, relationship, riches.</span></p><p class="c2"><span>The common backronym for Grace is God&#39;s Riches At Christ&#39;s Expense. When you deconstruct that, we see unmerited favour in &ldquo;Christ&#39;s Expense&rdquo;, and in &ldquo;Riches&rdquo; somewhat, but what are God&rsquo;s Riches? An afterlife in paradise, then the new earth? Does it really convey all the </span><span class="c48">richness</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;of the descriptions given by Thayer and Strong? I consider &ldquo;Riches&rdquo; to be too vague. It seems to imply we are merely blessed by unmerited favour. Sure, we are, though that falls short of the concept by a long way. It&rsquo;s God&rsquo;s &ldquo;prodigal return&rdquo; at Christ&#39;s expense. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Picture that return of the prodigal Son (from Christ&rsquo;s parable), The father sees him and runs to embrace him, to reward him for his return, to meet his needs&hellip; as a restored relationship&hellip; to be valued by the father. The father was not concerned by what may or may not have been given to the son previously, only that the relationship was restored, and his first action was rewarding the son for that. Not &ldquo;I told you so&rdquo; or &ldquo;don&rsquo;t do it again&rdquo; or any other thing, just (in my words) &ldquo;Give him good things and feed him, in fact, let&#39;s celebrate together&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, what were those good things? He clothed him and put rings on his fingers. Firstly, what kind of clothes did he put on his son? The clothing of a worker? No, the robes of a wealthy person, he gave his son the best. Anyone who looked at his son would instantly, visually be able to identify that he was a wealthy person or the son of a wealthy person. Also, here, remember this point, when this son was born, he was not adorned with robes, he wore nappies like any other baby, so a new Christian will look more like a baby than a well-adorned son of aristocracy, though as we grow, how appearance changes, and we&#39;re adorned with the symbols of aristocracy, our relationship with him who is in power. &nbsp;Now, what I&#39;m talking about here is not natural physical clothing; it is the outward appearance, the countenance of your being. When people look at a wealthy aristocrat, they can tell at first glance. When people look at you, do they see God coming through your life and your relationship with God as a Christian, the wealth of God being exposed rather than the wealth of the world? Remember here also that it is not the sons&#39; wealth that is seen at that moment, but the Father&#39;s wealth is seen on the Son. Do people see the (internal) wealth of God exuding from you?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c11 c37"><span>III</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;What is due to grace</span></p><ol class="c45 lst-kix_2psz0ho1k74p-1 start" start="1"><li class="c37 c66 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">the spiritual condition of one governed by the power of divine grace</span></li><li class="c37 c66 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">the token or proof of grace, benefit</span></li></ol><ol class="c45 lst-kix_2psz0ho1k74p-2 start" start="1"><li class="c37 c68 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">a gift of grace</span></li><li class="c37 c68 li-bullet-0"><span class="c7">benefit, bounty</span></li></ol><p class="c2"><span class="c17">III</span><span class="c17">. 1. The spiritual condition of one governed by the power of divine grace i</span><span>s the fruits of the spirit, which should primarily be seen in you, as well as wisdom and </span><span class="c17">XXXABC</span><span>, rather than worldly things. Note here in </span><span>III.</span><span class="c1">1. a/ it is a condition, a state of being (far more than a mere pardon), and b/ that state is one governed by God&#39;s power. Our will, our desires, our plans, thoughts, and every other &ldquo;our&rdquo; or &ldquo;my&rdquo;, including pride and ego, etc., are all now to be set aside, and God&#39;s desires for us are to be taken up in their place.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Also, due to grace, we have </span><span>III</span><span>. 2. </span><span class="c17">the token or proof of grace, benefit</span><span>. A token is a representation; it represents something, which proves grace is there. Yet as the state of Christianity has been explained already (the life which has changed from being sinful to being Godly in an obvious and evident way). This proof is the other benefits beyond those fruits, such as wisdom </span><span class="c7">XXXABC</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&#39;d like to create a backronym for CHARIS, maybe; Christ (Handcrafting or Hinging?) A Relationship In Sacrifice. I simply can&#39;t decide which h is better, handcrafting or hinging. I guess at some stage I&#39;ll put it to a vote. That&#39;s one thing the grace backronym is missing it probably should be relationship rather than riches, but innocence both need to be conveyed because a relationship with god is one that brings you to the Riches of understanding with wisdom, personal life value, fruits of the spirit and more, far more. &nbsp;It&#39;s the relationship that brings those riches, so personally, I&#39;d prefer to focus on the relationship, yet I also want people to see the rich value of that relationship. Even as I write this, my mind is leaning towards hinging because, like the prodigal son, the relationship was once there god used to walk with Adam in the Garden of Eden, but that relationship was broken by sin. It is the relationship that God longs to restore. The sacrifice of Yeshua on the cross was the action to implement this. So I am leaning away from handcrafting and towards hinging because, like hinging a door, the door was already there, the hinge was already there. The door frame was already there; they were merely not connected, and the hinge being put in place created that connection. In fact, as I read back what I just wrote, I see more similarities with Christ&#39;s sacrifice on the cross. To hinge a door is to hang a door. Jesus hung on the cross, and it is a door or Gate that is hung. There are other references to adore or gate that Jesus spoke of. He said he was the door. He said if anyone should knock on the door, he would open the door, and that was a door to eternal life. Also, he spoke of the wide gate or door and the narrow gate door in Matthew 7 and described those as a path to Heaven. Hence, the imagery in my mind right now is Yeshua being the door hung on the cross, the Access to the narrow path, and the narrow path leads to Paradise.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">1.14 Short summary definition.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Lastly, here I&rsquo;ll give another shorter definition based on both Strong and Thayers</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Evident Unmerited Divine Transcending Influence</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I originally tried for three words of this divine transcendence or influence. Divine needed to stay, as it&rsquo;s all but all an action of God. The action is both unmerited and evident, and both of those are important; then I couldn&rsquo;t decide between transcendence, which means (to rise up) and influence (to be changed by). So a short explanation of that reduction</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Evident (from Strong&#39;s &ldquo;it&rsquo;s reflection in the life&rdquo; and Thayer&#39;s &ldquo;the exercise of the Christian virtues&rdquo;)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Unmerited (from Thayer&#39;s &ldquo;merciful kindness&rdquo;)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Divine (from Strong&#39;s &ldquo;the divine influence&rdquo; and Thayer&#39;s &ldquo;by which God&rdquo;)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Transcending ( from Thayer&rsquo;s &nbsp;&ldquo;increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection&rdquo;)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">and </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Influence (from Strong&#39;s &ldquo;the divine influence&rdquo; and Thayer&rsquo;s &ldquo;turns them to Christ&rdquo; and &ldquo;kindles them&hellip;&rdquo;)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, a quick summary on this part - God obviously lifts us to a higher lifestyle and spiritual mindset if you accept that growth which you can&rsquo;t buy through work, merely accept Christ&#39;s sacrifice and allow that change. Of course I will expand in the coming chapters.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.vfom6typvt46"><span class="c29 c26">Charis Discovery</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">2.1 the Facebook conversation and how it exposed a legalistic view and a shallow understanding of grace.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I have cut and pasted the following directly from my Facebook messages (correcting just a couple of typos). I think it&rsquo;s worth including as it is, so I removed the person&#39;s name whom I was speaking with and replaced it with (blank). First, a paragraph to fill you in</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">(blank) and I had previously spoken about getting together for the purpose of evangelism. I&rsquo;d asked if this person would go with me, but due to the slow response, I decided to go and meet them in the place they evangelise. It was certainly a place of trouble for a Christian, a place filled with worldlyness. Before they got there, I discussed evangelism with a couple of other Christians out to evangelise (hand out tracts). They mentioned negative things about my approach, which, upon further research into the person who promotes their style of evangelism, I found out what this person (Mr X) has taught them and these are the messages I and (blank)sent to each other after that research into (Mr X). And lastly, before you read the messages, I had fallen away from God for 23-24 years till about 7-8 months before this, and (blank) was aware of that&hellip; The Black Highlights are (blank)&#39;s words, The entire internet conversation is recorded as &ldquo;2.2&rdquo; &gt;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><ul class="c45 lst-kix_gdd6mdmrrvcd-0 start"><li class="c40 c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c44">&ldquo;The following is an </span><span class="c44 c42">unedited</span><span class="c32 c26">&nbsp;Facebook conversation; I&rsquo;ve left it raw so you can see my own wrestling.&rdquo;</span></li></ul><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c3">&nbsp;Hi (blank), I thank you for your slow response, as from that, the decision to go on Friday night was placed on my heart. It was the right decision. I discovered more from the others there without even knowing what I&#39;d discovered. They told me things that (from my research on MrX yesterday), had come from him. Like, for example, they said my method was &quot;not the Gospel&quot; which threw me (and you had not gone that far, except for a mention of &quot;prosperity doctrine&quot;), but when I checked MrX out, I found it had come from him, that he says leading with the goodness of God is a &quot;false gospel&quot;. I was shocked </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c3">I discovered that he teaches: No &quot;Life Enhancement&quot;: He strictly avoids telling people Jesus will improve their lives (better marriage, peace, etc.). He views this as a &quot;false gospel&quot; that leads to &quot;false converts&quot; or lukewarm Christians who fall away because they weren&#39;t seeking &quot;righteousness,&quot; only &quot;happiness.&quot; when trials come. He says to avoid &quot;Easy Believism&quot; and warns against reducing the gospel to self-improvement or life-enhancement. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c3">Wow, I can&#39;t reduce the gospel to life-enhancement, but that is a definite aspect of it. After all, can he reduce the gospel to sin and ignore redemption? He starts with sin then moves to redemption. I start with charis and move to redemption (again study the word, it is the basis of salvation so you should know it better than me)! (I&#39;ve only had 7-8 months to discover it, you&#39;ve had years). The &quot;Goodness&quot; side of charis is the &quot;keeps, strengthens, increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection, and kindles them to the exercise of CHRISTIAN VIRTUES&quot; part... increases them in &quot;love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self control. The fruits of the spirit. These are the things I lead with - The better life that is promised, no, demanded by God! We are to walk from sin to become fruitful (fruits of the spirit) To know love even amidst hate, joy amidst despair, peace amidst disruption, etc. When you have a real