d all along?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c42 c26 c74"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">***That is the end of the online chat***</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I think it was during this banter, I realised the point about heaven and hell, and more so their irrelevance, as it&rsquo;s the relationship God wants, that&rsquo;s what man was created for&hellip; Relationship. &ldquo;Relationship with God&rdquo; is the Bible&rsquo;s story&#8209;line. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Since then (that was about 6 months ago) I have also come to realise this even more, as now I look at scriptures like &nbsp;Mat 11:12 &nbsp;And from the days of John the Immerser until now, the kingdom of the heavens suffers violence, and violent men seize it by force, (LSV). (I now look at that differently in a new light as well *as of this week)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Yes, we are able to take heaven now, as heaven is available since Jesus was baptised by John (the holy spirit came down and his ministry began). We take heaven and with force... It is not passive; we force ourselves into it (cram in). By charis (grace). But how can we force ourselves into a place above? It&#39;s a higher spiritual plain (happiness, power, etc.), not physically higher, mentally higher! Which he made available through a relationship with him? We go there now, not after life.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A quick breakdown on this (and I won&rsquo;t use every possible translation of each word, just the most likely, for the sake of reducing another 1, 000+ words:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Kingdom is: &beta;&alpha;&sigma;&iota;&lambda;&epsilon;&iota;&#769;&alpha; &ldquo;basileia&rdquo; bas-il-i&#39;-ah - meaning &ldquo;realm&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Heaven is: &omicron;&upsilon;&#787;&rho;&alpha;&nu;&omicron;&#769;&sigmaf; &ldquo;ouranos&rdquo; oo-ran-os&#39; - meaning &ldquo;higher plane; including happiness, power etc.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Suffers violence is: &beta;&iota;&alpha;&#769;&zeta;&omega; &ldquo;biazo&#772;&rdquo; bee-ad&#39;-zo - meaning &ldquo;to force (to crowd oneself into)&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Violent men is: &beta;&iota;&alpha;&sigma;&tau;&eta;&#769;&sigmaf; &ldquo;biaste&#772;s&rdquo; bee-as-tace&#39; - meaning &ldquo;a forcer&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And, Seize it by force is: &alpha;&#788;&rho;&pi;&alpha;&#769;&zeta;&omega; &ldquo;harpazo&#772;&rdquo; har-pad&#39;-zo - meaning &ldquo;to seize, take&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In short, Heaven is a current higher (spiritual/mental) realm we forcefully push into by Godly action. It&rsquo;s all about changing your current hell-like life to a current heavenly one! LITERALLY.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">3</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.jcusb5cxui6k"><span class="c29 c26">A personal burden most Christians &ldquo;don&rsquo;t comprehend&rdquo;</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.1 Why you &ldquo;can&rsquo;t stop talking about charis&rdquo; and why most Christians don&rsquo;t comprehend it.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I have something from giving my life to God that seems all but impossible to understand. Even most people who call themselves Christians have no comprehension of this. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It is the subject I seem to talk about often: Charis and Galatians 5:22,23 (the fruits of the Spirit). Is that because I like the subject? No, I&rsquo;m compelled to it, I keep discovering more, and I keep wondering why no one seems to be teaching these things. I seem to find myself pushed in this direction, which, when you understand it, the pushing is a major factor of it. It is the force that pushes you from sin to Godliness, from ignorance to understanding.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I seek to expand your comprehension of this one word significantly, both in meaning and its extreme importance. If I succeed, it will be like a person who can barely swim a lap of a normal pool to now be able to confidently swim the English Channel.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I live in Australia; those of us non-Aboriginals live here due to Captain Cook&#39;s discovery of it. His discovery gave Europeans the ability to come here, as they then knew it existed. After the British used it as a prison colony, as it was considered a harsh and hostile land, other settlers came, and they considered it a good place for one reason or another. We are here because of his discovery, but we were not brought here in his discovery.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.2 Cook&rsquo;s discovery and how grace is like a journey</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Cook&#39;s voyage of discovery was not our transit, but made our latter transit possible. Similarly, our salvation is by grace, which the cross made possible. I&rsquo;ve been told, after a reading by another, that this next sentence should be changed due to potential controversy. I will not change the sentence; it is correct. Just remember to focus on its clarifying second half. We are not saved by the cross; we are saved by Grace because of it. Much like my family&#39;s latter transit did not happen by Cook&#39;s discovery, but by their transit because of the discovery of Australia. So I&rsquo;ll stick by my statement staunchly; as the cross is the key that opens the door, it unlocks the door, but grace is turning the handle and pushing or pulling the door to open it. Grace (charis) gets you eternal life on the new earth (not in heaven, and yes, also controversial but true), the cross was the key to unlock, but not open that door to eternal blessing.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This will take some time for me to explain. Firstly, a minor explanation before the (proper/accurate/better/main/primary???) explanation. When Cook sailed from New Zealand to find the as-yet-undiscovered east Coast of &ldquo;Van Diemen&#39;s Land&rdquo; (the inhospitable west coast had already been discovered), he discovered it the moment it was sighted. An instant in time, not during the voyage there nor while continuing towards it. A single moment. When Jesus was nailed to the cross, salvation was not possible, as his death had not happened. The instant he died, it was possible, nor after while he still hung there, nor when his body was carried away. In the one instant, and not the resurrection either, as that wasn&rsquo;t his sacrifice, his resurrection gave us the ability of resurrection to the afterlife on the new earth. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now that&#39;s also a whole different deal, if you think you&rsquo;re going to heaven, which I&rsquo;ll reveal more on that later. In the sacrifice of his life, our sins were washed away (for those who earnestly repent and commit to him due to it). A single instant. Now that instant was like Cook&rsquo;s single instant of discovering the East Coast of Australia. His discovery never put anyone here, nor did it bring them here, though we are all here because of it. It is important to know the difference. The Endeavour (his ship) did not bring my ancestors here. Which also does not make Cook&rsquo;s discovery unimportant; in fact, it is paramount.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Charis&hellip; You may not comprehend it, but if you don&rsquo;t have it, you quite simply are not saved. Charis is the word translated into &ldquo;Grace&rdquo; and is the action of salvation. Before we get too far, I&rsquo;d better explain its pronunciation, as even the (very few) Pastors (who even know it) usually mispronounce it. And I&rsquo;ll give an example of the lack of Pastoral knowledge in a couple of paragraphs. The H is silent - &ldquo;Car-is&rdquo;, after all, it is the same word which is the foundation of the word charisma, a charismatic person, etc., we don&rsquo;t pronounce the H. I&rsquo;ll have to expand on charisma later, too, due to its relationship.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.3 Charis as the action that brings us to God; the lack of pastoral understanding; the backronym &ldquo;God&rsquo;s Riches At Christ&rsquo;s Expense&rdquo; and its limits.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Charis is not a word for the sacrifice of Jesus (like Cook&#39;s discovery), it&rsquo;s the action that brings us to god, as we can now do so because of his sacrifice. Charis is in this analogy; the discovery that my ancestors made, that there was a place discovered by Cook that had value in travelling to and their journey here. Charis (grace) is their whole discovery and journey process, got that? Jesus died to free us from sin, Charis is our life journey to discover, accept and take hold of that. (like my ancestors&#39; journey&hellip; to the promised land, in their case, Australia).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You will see what I mean from the concordances and dictionaries of Joseph Henry Thayer 1885 and Dr James Strong 1890. As Thayer came first and laid the groundwork, I&rsquo;ll use his First. He gave four explanations, which I&rsquo;ll get into more detail later, but 2/ is very important and I&rsquo;ll give that now; &ldquo;The merciful kindness by which God, exerting his holy influence upon souls, turns them to Christ, keeps, strengthens, increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection, and kindles them to the exercise of the Christian virtues&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You may have heard Pastors, Evangelists or other preachers speak on Grace and &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, though I have never heard a message about Grace that goes beyond &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; and delves into the second meaning even in the slightest. It&rsquo;s like they just don&rsquo;t know, or maybe find it too difficult to teach on. In many cases, I can say they actually don&rsquo;t know. Besides, no definition mentions &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;; they only imply it by words such as &ldquo;merciful kindness&rdquo;!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">An example, as mentioned, before we come back to Charis. I went to a Church service with the intention of meeting the head pastor and asking for permission to get testimonies from people in their congregation. This, by the way, was the largest church in my city. I asked a person at the front door welcoming people to their service who could point out the head pastor so I could introduce myself to make this request. He said this is our head Pastor right beside me, I began talking with the head Pastor. Soon he asked what I do in ministry. I began to explain, and in doing so, I mentioned the messages I give and happened to mention, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been teaching on Charis a lot lately&rdquo;. His head went back as his body language was saying, &ldquo;What are you talking about?&rdquo; I noticed and said, &ldquo;You know what I&rsquo;m talking about, Charis, right?&rdquo; I don&rsquo;t recall his exact words, &ldquo;NO&rdquo; or &ldquo;What?&rdquo; or similar. I said, &ldquo;Charis, the word translated into Grace&rdquo; I don&rsquo;t recall if he said something at that point. If so, it would have been only a single word reiteration of his first indication of his lack of knowledge. Whatever his response, I realised I had to explain Charis, the word for Grace, which meant he didn&rsquo;t even understand grace.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Do you think I was shocked? No, not at all, as I had never had one person explain it to me (well, not in dictionary terms anyway, as someone reminded me of a backronym of Grace very recently, &ldquo;God&rsquo;s Riches At Christ&rsquo;s Expense&rdquo;, so some people have some vague knowledge of it). I explained Strong&#39;s description to him, as I didn&rsquo;t even know of Thayers at that point. There are many other interesting points to the full story, but I&rsquo;ll leave it there and get back to the point. But on the way back to the point, I&rsquo;ll expand on that backronym first, it may convey Grace better than any non-concordance/dictionary, but doesn&rsquo;t do justice to the depth of meaning. Gaining God&#39;s riches could be considered as an instant thing too, as there is no mention in that as to even the slightest mention of time. My ancestors didn&rsquo;t think of Australia and instantly arrive. Charis is a long process, like that journey. The unmerited favour/merciful kindness part (like Yeshua&#39;s death) is an instant in time as well. The instant you touch that ticket and drag it towards yourself to pick it up, the instant you begin controlling your part of the journey. Yes, you have things to do too; the ticket doesn&rsquo;t instantly transport you here either. They probably didn&rsquo;t even have tickets in that day anyway, just a registration on the ship&#39;s passenger log. Still, whatever the action, they then needed to pack (if they hadn&rsquo;t yet) and board. Also note here, even upon boarding doesn&rsquo;t mean they will make it, as they may have chosen to get off at another port on the journey and never got back on board.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">3</span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.r06b8536unyn"><span class="c33 c26">Unmerited favour - the ticket</span></h3><p class="c2"><span class="c1">and how charis is the process that moves us from sin into the fruits of the Spirit, even in turmoil.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.1</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c56">His/this description and strong&#39;s description and the Christian virtues that I have talks</span><span class="c92">(ed</span><span class="c56">) about other fruits of the spirit in Galatians</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;and the reflection in the life is the reflection of God working in your heart coming out to your life as strong described. which again is the same thing, it is the fruits of the spirit, and this is also backed up by much of what Jesus said. He said look at the fields to harvest is ripe. He was talking about people being a harvest of fruit or grain; it doesn&#39;t matter. A harvest of good things to consume now. Jesus also said we will know them by their fruit, so we know people that don&#39;t have God by the sin in their life, the anger, the disruption, the disquieted people, we can see they don&#39;t have God. The Christian who is truly Christian has the fruits of the Spirit. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, having said that, I must include that it seems impossible for many people to comprehend the wonderful, good things that I see purely from the fruits of the spirit, purely from the result of the grace which is the thing that saves us. So the result of Salvation again not the thing that causes it in first case, that&#39;s the sacrifice of Jesus on the cross. That charis is the action that happens in your life when you first discover, then accept Jesus as lord and savior and then as you continue to grow in him to produce fruit (the fruits of the spirit).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So when you accept Jesus as Lord and Saviour, you begin the process to gain love, joy, peace, patience, etc. It might not be there straight away, and the sin might not disappear straight away, but Charis is god turning you towards Christ; it is the action by which those sins are disappearing and being replaced by those fruits. You are gaining love, joy, peace, patience, etc., even if you&#39;re in a world of turmoil and here&#39;s the bit that most people don&#39;t understand. Even Christians tell me that you cannot have peace if you&#39;re in a world of trouble, you cannot have Joy if you&#39;re in a world of turmoil, you cannot have these things.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But many verses in the Bible show us that we can have peace amongst the turmoil, we can have happiness amongst the trouble, we can have love among or amidst the hate. We can have tons of people hating us, and we just have compassion for them; those poor souls just don&#39;t understand. If we have become Christians earnestly, then we are learning to love those who hate us, etc. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.2 Christians may not understand peace and joy in trouble; critique the &ldquo;good things&rdquo; gospel.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Why is it that extremely few understand this? because they don&#39;t have God in their life! If you have God in your life, then you are walking towards a loving environment, not that the environment around you suddenly changes. You become the love within the environment of pain; you are walking towards producing those fruits of the spirit. Therefore, you have a wonderful joy and happiness because of them (God in you). The wisdom and everything else that God brings is such a comforting thing that even in the middle of troubles and trials and tribulations and whatever else, you have still personally got (not environmentally or circumstantially) that God-given love, joy, peace, patience, etc. It is unlikely to be instant, but the more you walk toward God, the more those fruits will grow.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now I find that it is incredibly difficult even amongst Christians to find somebody who both knows and embodies this. God is a God of goodness, not a God trying to bring trouble into your life. Some very famous evangelists preach that life is going to be difficult as a Christian, that you should not preach the message to people; that they can have the fruits of the spirit, love, joy, peace, patience, etc., because their circumstances may control them, and therefore they might be in a circumstance where they can&#39;t have love because of the hate around them etc. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Well, what I say is </span><span class="c1 c46">whether you&#39;re not you obviously a person </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And this particular person is a very well-known evangelist, and he certainly has said that preaching that &ldquo;god gives you those good things&rdquo; is a false gospel. Sure, one of us is preaching false gospel! Is it me, by saying that the promise of Christianity is to gain the spirit through charis, which not instantly but eventually, leads to gain and not gain of worldly things but those fruits (you become the; love, joy, peace and patience, etc., in your environment). Or is it him saying that my message is a &ldquo;false gospel&rdquo;? And one of the many ironies of this is the word &lsquo;gospel&rsquo; literally means &ldquo;good news&rdquo;. Are we to believe that there is nothing to gain through Christianity except to gain heaven and avoid hell?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Now my concern about that is, you don&#39;t know God if you think God is only about your environment or heaven/hell status, that God is unconcerned about how you live now and won&#39;t bring you that peace amongst turmoil etc., that I mentioned </span><span class="c46">from it is enveloped by God&#39;s goodness</span><span>. I have a relatively easy life that my life is something else again right through the roof having this connection with god within me I have empathy for people where I used to have anger with them it is a godly thing that makes my life better and having that is good for me but certainly not selfish because it is me having God&#39;s goodness in me </span><span class="c56">not being god godly in myself as in you</span><span>&nbsp;k</span><span class="c56">now</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class="c1 c88">I am the good thing now</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.3 God makes you the &ldquo;good thing&rdquo; in your environment</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&#39;s God&#39;s goodness in me that makes the world around me a little better from the effect of God in me. His message, on the other hand, is just harsh, and it might be a message of heaven and hell, and it is very selfish, to only be concerned about getting yourself out of hell and into heaven and not care about anything else. That&#39;s far more selfish than wanting the good things of love, joy, peace, patience, etc., because those good things developing in your life right now are actually good things for the other people around you as well; not just for yourself. You become the blessing to others by having God in your life. You are doing more for the people around you than you are doing for yourself. It is more selfless, less selfish to want to be the embodiment of that love, joy, peace, patience etc.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>I had explained this word &lsquo;charis&rsquo; many times in many different ways, yet again, I explain it another way, thanks to the revelation of this evangelist. When I heard about him, I was told to check him out because he&#39;s such an appropriate, effective evangelist. What I found tore at my spirit, he tells people to avoid giving a message of love, joy, peace, patience, etc. He says the people who give that message are trying to attract people by appealing to their selfishness. </span><span class="c1 c56">What is being loving in hypo environment selfish is having Joy internal or peace in trouble so fish is having patients so fish or is the impatients true selfishness in fact you are walking away from selfishness when you get God in your life and take on the fruits of the spirit. So I would like to actually meet this man because on it tell him about the loving god that Jesus </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">God makes you the good thing. You bring goodness to the world around you and therefore even though the external troubles, etc., don&#39;t change by themselves, they may change from your goodness you then exhude, by having God in you. and should not without relying on that just what god does for you is an amazing, wonderful thing that you gain in your life right now by having God in your life. Yet this man says that preaching any kind of gain is a false gospel. Again, I need to introduce him to Jesus; he has probably spent more time than me reading the bible. I expect he has spent more time than me in evangelism, yet he doesn&#39;t seem to know the heart of God. The heart of God that wants to turn you into the; love Joy peace, and patience, etc. To make you patient instead of impatient, to give you self-control when you had no self-control. Those changes in you that make life better and those changes are good things. You will be happier with those things in your life, rather than the opposite, being the sins of hate and anger etc., derived by putting yourself first. Let&rsquo;s not forget, trying to avoid hell is the ultimate selfishness. If all you seek is to avoid hell, then your commitment is certainly based on flimsy ground. As the prime thought behind that decision is, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s all about me&rdquo;, that same source of sin.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What is the Bible about in three words? Relationship with God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">3.4 people fail Ephesians 2:8</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I used to interview people about God, and a question I&rsquo;d ask if they declared themselves as Christian was &ldquo;Please fill in the blanks&hellip; We are saved by (blank) through (blank). On occasion, I&rsquo;d get the correct answer, Ephesians 2:8 &ldquo;For we are saved by grace through faith, and this is not of yourselves, it is the gift of God&rdquo;. most of the time I&rsquo;d get a quizical tone of voice saying something like &ldquo;We are saved by Jesus, though his death?&rdquo; of course they answer in a tone of implying the question of &ldquo;am I right in this answer?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Ephesians 2:5,8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;...made us alive with Christ even when we were dead in transgressions&mdash;it is by grace you have been saved... For it is by grace you have been saved, through faith...&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Grace explicitly saves in the same paragraph.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Ephesians 2:8-9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;For it is by grace you have been saved, through faith&mdash;and this is not from yourselves, it is the gift of God&mdash;not by works...&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Both terms in one verse.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Titus 2:11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;For the grace of God has appeared that offers salvation to all people.&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Grace brings salvation in one verse.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Acts 15:11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;No! We believe it is through the grace of the Lord Jesus that we shall be saved, just as they were.&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Grace saves in one verse.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Titus 3:5-7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;He saved us, not because of righteous things we had done, but because of his mercy... so that, having been justified by his grace, we might become heirs...&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Salvation by mercy/grace in a paragraph.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In my journey to where God wants me like a journey to Australia I know where God wants me and let&#39;s say that is the state of Queensland but I don&#39;t know which city in Queensland he wants me in or which house in that city so what I&#39;m saying here is I know what God calls me to &nbsp;and I can see the future of it but only a general view of this future I do not know the specifics </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Grace is not self-improvement with religious language. It is God&rsquo;s holy influence turning the soul toward Christ, strengthening faith, and producing the fruit of a changed life. That means grace does not merely pardon the self; it displaces the self. It does not just forgive sin; it reorders the heart. It makes dependence on God more natural than dependence on personal strength.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So grace is not the opposite of obedience; it is the opposite of self-salvation. Grace does not tell the believer to do nothing. It tells the believer to stop trying to become righteous by the power of the old self. Grace creates a new centre, a new appetite, and a new direction. The result is not religious performance, but a life that increasingly bears the marks of God: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">4</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.kg9050u3xf5z"><span class="c29 c26">Common Misunderstanding</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">4.1 What my interviews show</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It seems from my conversations and interviews that few people understand anything about Grace at all. I used to interview Christians, and a question I asked was &ldquo;Please fill in the blanks&hellip; We are saved by (blank) through (blank)?&rdquo; This I took from Ephesians 2:8. Only a few would say &ldquo;we are saved by Grace through Faith&rdquo;. If the Bible says, we are saved by&hellip; &nbsp;wouldn&rsquo;t it be important to know the following point? After all, the following concept must be the basis of salvation.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I see it quite prudent to not only know the word but also the meaning of that word. When I say &lsquo;the meaning of that word&rsquo;, not its simplest base meaning either, but its full meaning. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">As mentioned, a few have given me the correct words, though I have never met any person, including ministers, who know any more about Grace beyond two words &ldquo;Unmerited favour&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">4.2 Even the most knowledgable</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I have even watched the person referred to as the most popular preacher of this decade. Yes, he&rsquo;s rather good. But to me, in another way, not that much different. Preaching the cream; a little thicker than milk, but not much. Yes, he goes into some depth. What I&rsquo;m saying here is that he explains words in their original Greek; not that his messages are about things I haven&rsquo;t heard often before, but still cream rather than milk. Again, I&rsquo;ll reiterate, I do think he does a better job than most.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now I heard him mention Grace once, I&rsquo;d hoped now I&rsquo;ll hear someone say something beyond &ldquo;Unmerited favour&rdquo;, to my displeasure, that&rsquo;s all he said too.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Why does no one understand even the base meaning? The best concordance we have, certainly the most trusted, as it&rsquo;s the only one I hear of constantly, is Strong&#39;s, and just to remind you, He highlighted this sentence with the word &ldquo;</span><span class="c17">especially&rdquo;!</span><span>&nbsp;&ldquo;</span><span class="c17">Especially the divine influence upon the heart, and its reflection in the life</span><span class="c1">, including gratitude&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c2"><span>Now the semicolon means the &ldquo;; including gratitude&rdquo; is more of an afterthought, reinforced with the use of &ldquo;Including&rdquo;. <br><br>Nowhere does </span><span class="c11 c62">Dr James Strong</span><span>&nbsp;in his concordance mention unmerited favour, nor does </span><span class="c12 c11">Joseph Henry Thayer in his four even more accurate descriptions of charis. And Thayer&#39;s work was a Lexicon, which by nature is more exhaustive. However, Thayer does expand to include &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; amongst many other later references. Which, in my mind, does not therefore overrule the four definitions he gave, as it then seems like a drop in the ocean.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c11 c14">4.3 True, but woefully incomplete</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c11 c12">Now, I must agree there is an unmerited favour aspect to it. But as I will mention in the chapter &ldquo;A mini gospel in itself&rdquo; {get chapter number for &gt;A mini gospel in itself&lt;}, given a natural expansion of &ldquo;Virtues&rdquo; as that&rsquo;s required. After all, what virtues? Expansion is thus required. If we then expand not extensively but moderately, we have the whole basis of salvation. I&rsquo;ll save that for the aforementioned chapter.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Yet here I&rsquo;ll offer a mini expansion: Thayer&#39;s second description carries the most weight. His opening three words are &ldquo;The merciful kindness&hellip;&rdquo; Well, sure, loosely here, mercy is usually unmerited, and favour is kindness. But as you saw earlier, he then follows with a massive sentence. If you think about it, that sentence carries a compelling gravity. Far more than mere &ldquo;Unmerited favour&rdquo;. I am actually in awe of it. Do I give it far more credit than it deserves? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">I express the thoughts that I&rsquo;ll present to you in this/these book/s to people and get almost blank looks. It seems to mean little to them:</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Do they negate it from Christian tedium? (The &ldquo;yes, I&rsquo;ve heard stuff about the Bible so many times before that I know it all&rdquo; - thoughts in their head, so they discount it beforehand and don&rsquo;t even listen)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Is it that my explanation to them fails to hit the mark because I haven&rsquo;t simplified it enough for them to understand?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Is my understanding giving it far more credibility and value than it really has?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Maybe I&rsquo;m not as intelligent as I thought I was, and as mind-blowing as this whole journey of mental growth was to me, it&rsquo;s nothing to these geniuses?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">These are Christians I&rsquo;ve been expressing these thoughts to. If it were the unsaved, I&rsquo;d expect those responses. So, yes, I find it compelling; understand a little, and you just want to research more, which keeps building to an expectation of a crescendo which never comes, as when I think I&#39;ve learnt it, God keep teaching me more.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Personally, I think they fail to see the gravity it holds. I do it a disservice in some way, and I wonder about my delivery mostly. I really think I&rsquo;m either wording it too simply for its due significance or I&rsquo;m not simplifying it enough.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Let me put it this way</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">If 1/ &ldquo;We are saved by Grace&hellip;&rdquo; then we should know what it means.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">If 2/ the meaning we are taught (given we have even been taught), falls short of reality by a gross margin.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Then 3/ We should be extremely interested in its real definition and not just the simple definition, but the extrapolated value</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">And 4/ If that extrapolated value carries sufficient weight, we should respect any new illumination it provides.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">Especially if 5/ That illumination then refocuses our heritage and more so our path<br></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c14 c11">4.4 if grace saves, and our definition is inadequate; the problem of indifference</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">If I haven&rsquo;t yet, in some way, please bear with me, as that is exactly what I intend to do: Show what grace, the crux of salvation, actually means, its gross undervaluation, its real value, weight, illumination and alteration to our path.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c11 c62">This is where I&rsquo;m blown away, as I discovered the little I know, it has altered my path immensely. It is far more than what I thought and hope to show you enough for you to seek so much more godliness too. Yes, I&rsquo;m on a far more Godly path. But was my path </span><span class="c44 c11">askew</span><span class="c12 c11">? Certainly not. In fact, I&rsquo;m let down by these very same Christians as they want to discuss the same things the average person in the world does, when all those things hold no appeal to me at all. If it&rsquo;s not God, godly or something of value to the Christian walk in general, I&rsquo;m not interested. These people also happen to be people who are very regular church attendees and the like. They would not be considered in the churchian group by many. They&rsquo;d generally be considered authentic Christians. Yet what are the &ldquo;authentic Christians&rdquo;? I also know they may watch an hour of Christian TV each week, amidst the 18 to 20 hours of regular worldly programs. By worldly programs, I don&rsquo;t even mean news and documentaries, that which may at least educate. No, these are soaps dateing/marriage and Big Brother type programs. Trash in my mind. Though each to their own.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">My point being If I&rsquo;m not lacking intelligence and &ldquo;seem&rdquo; to have a less worldly focus, and this blows my mind, why does it not seem to even shift theirs a little? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">I believe there is a dual misunderstanding: the initial misunderstanding of &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; combined with what seems to me to be a misunderstanding of exactly what it is I&rsquo;m trying to communicate. So I sincerely pray you can see what I see. I believe it will move you if you do.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">One last thought on &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; before the next chapter:</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c11 c62">The second half of </span><span>Ephesians 2:8</span><span class="c12 c11">&nbsp;describes unmerited favour. How often do we use the second half of a sentence in repetition to define the 1st half? Rarely, I believe the 2nd half &nbsp;&ldquo;...This does not come from you; it is the gift of God&quot; (an explanation of unmerited favour) is nuts if Grace also means the same thing! as it would then read like this if &quot;Grace&quot; was meant as &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, which is also the gift of God.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c12 c11">It would therefore read like this: &gt; &quot;For by the gift of God, which does not come from you, you have been saved through faith. This does not come from you; it is the gift of God. Come on, that simply doesn&#39;t make sense; it becomes an irrational sentence. But we know &quot;grace&quot; is actually far more; it is an obvious divine influence on your heart.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c12 c11"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">5</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.kspg6vjp309f"><span class="c29 c26">Definition - lack of understanding</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">5.1 More is unknown or misunderstood than known; the danger of thinking we &ldquo;know&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I find more is unknown or worse, misunderstood than is known. Yes, it is worse to think you have the answer and know a subject or concept and then shut down to reality. So I&rsquo;d wish it were mostly unknown, and that seems to me to be the case.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">My biggest problem is with those who know. Pastors, ministers and long-time Christians who have &ldquo;heard it all&rdquo; and to whom &ldquo;there is nothing new under the Sun&rdquo;. Yet I present something new under the Son&rdquo;. Note the spelling if you missed it. Not that this is new, again, it&rsquo;s been in plain sight the whole time.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Even a revelation of the definition seems to entrap them. &ldquo;Oh, OK, so now I understand &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; fell short and I now have heard the correct definition&hellip; let&#39;s move on. But when they say lets move on they mean, I don&rsquo;t want to know more, let&#39;s change the subject.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It should mean, let&#39;s now delve into it. &nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">5.2 Cognitive dissonance</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">People just want a simple thing that won&rsquo;t cause a paradigm shift. A little more information, OK, but if it&rsquo;s to follow with a requirement to then rework that thinking&hellip; Oh no, I don&rsquo;t want to do that, so the cognitive dissonance will cause a comprehension shutdown.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The mind, in a sense, says, &ldquo;I heard the definition, so now let&#39;s get away from that, and if you try to expand and show any need for me to change, those words just won&rsquo;t affect me; I&rsquo;ll hear but not listen.&rdquo; Are we not moved from a fear of change, or if not fear, the discomfort of change?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What happens when we are given a more accurate definition that now requires change? After all, &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; is wonderful as it&rsquo;s all about getting things you don&rsquo;t deserve!</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&ldquo;The merciful kindness&hellip;&rdquo; OK, that&rsquo;s pretty much the same, but it is already beginning to cause discomfort. Mercy? Unmerited is one thing, but mercy implies guilt and fault beyond me, simply having not worked for it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>We are already starting to put our backs up. I believe people are already beginning to shut out what is coming. &ldquo;... by which God&hellip;&rdquo; Ok, not too bad. &ldquo;&hellip;turns us to Christ&hellip;&rdquo; they think &ldquo;actually that part&#39;s good, God will do the work and we don&rsquo;t have to put any effort in towards that Godliness&rdquo;. &ldquo;... keeps, strengthens, increases us to Christian faith, knowledge, affection&hellip;&rdquo; Ouch, that one hurt a little. All good till that last word. We have to have affection (love). We have to love the unlovable? I remember that in the Bible, but do we really do that? Well, we like to think we do. The brain then justifies its&rsquo; position, &ldquo;sure, I forgive everyone&rdquo;, whether you do or not. But still, even self-justified, we shut out the words a little more, not liking what we are hearing. &ldquo;...kindles them to then exercise of the Christian virtues.&rdquo; Whoa, Brian shut down, hear the words but don&rsquo;t listen, don&rsquo;t process the meaning. After all, this means to have the fruit of the spirit right, which are a major part of Christian Virtues. Love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control.<br><br></span><span class="c7">5.3 {Discomfort}?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How to read Eph 2:8 is faith also the gift of God? If so, should it read &ldquo;they are&rdquo; the gift of God? Is faith the human contribution? Yet (to each is given a measure of faith), so yes the faith itself is part of that gift. I consider the implication to be the unproven choice will be made by those who God has not merely called but enabled with the response of faith. the response of faith as awakened and granted by grace, while still being authentically our own act. A strange, paradoxical, balancing act that boggles the mind; where is the line? There is no line, as it is two independent actions that are solely dependent on God. All Gods influence alone yet requiring human contribution, a mystery in itself Phil. 2:13, &quot;it is God who works in you, both to will and to work&quot;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">grace isn&rsquo;t merely an enablement to choose, but as a divine action that effectively creates new life. This is more than coaching; it is resurrection (Eph. 2:5-6). In this view, the &quot;choice&quot; to follow is the fruit of a prior, supernatural regeneration (John 1:13, 3:3-8; 1 John 5:1). The new birth is not merely contingent on human cooperation, as these texts present it as the sovereign, causative work of the Spirit that ironically enables the very faith it demands.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Salvation begins with God&#39;s drawing: &quot;No one can come to Me unless the Father Who sent Me draws him&quot; (John 6:44, NLV). This drawing is the first movement of grace&mdash;an enabling influence that makes response possible. Yet this divine influence respects human freedom. Like a coach who trains, encourages, and empowers an athlete but cannot run the race for them, God&#39;s grace enables our response without forcing it. Jesus himself described this dynamic: &quot;Listen! I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears My voice and opens the door, I will come in&quot; (Revelation 3:20, NLV). The knocking is for everyone; the opening remains a human act made possible by that very knock.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A fully comprehensive NT viewpoint holds the mystery of both divine sovereignty and human responsibility in tension. As Peter writes, believers are &quot;chosen by what God the Father had planned. This happened through the Holy Spirit&rsquo;s work. He wanted you to be made holy as you obey Jesus Christ&quot; (1 Peter 1:2, NLV)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sure, I like the idea of joy, and the others, well, they&rsquo;re great to have inbound&hellip; people giving them to me; people loving me and showing peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control towards me. But hey, I have some issues in presenting them to others or having patience and or maybe self-control in my life&hellip; So they think.<br></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">5.4 {subtitle?}</span><span class="c1"><br>People get caught up in the definition, let alone the expansion. They don&rsquo;t want to hear about the repentance required. Hang on, I repented when I said a sinner&#39;s prayer, some think and of course, more shut out happens here. Sorry, but 1/ it&rsquo;s very unlikely they even understood the word. (It doesn&rsquo;t simply mean a turnaround, a change of lifestyle; from sin to well&hellip; looking sinless). It means to change your mind, which in salvation is to have God and Godliness in your mind so much that you don&rsquo;t even think of sin. Here, however, there is a need for mental renewal again. Yes, I said need, that means you need to comprehend the difference if you did not already know this, as the real foundation of salvation. I think you probably didn&rsquo;t, as not even Pastors I have spoken to have gone beyond &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, including one of the world&#39;s most famous.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So God is making that change happen; God has the figurative river you are in flowing in the direction of Godliness. Well, we have free will; we can swim against the flow. If you are called, you will realise sooner or later you&rsquo;re just putting in a lot of effort to basically go nowhere. Give up and go with God&#39;s flow, even better, put in the effort to swim downstream.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you are called, God is turning you to Christ, don&rsquo;t fight it, run with it and seek that fruit. More so, seek the greater change as it is selflessness that is the tree from which the fruit grows. Planted in the earth that is God, Yeshua and the word. Sure, you said a sinner&#39;s prayer and are making an effort to be a nicer person&hellip; fail. The sinner&#39;s prayer registered you on the voyage, and now you are standing behind the sail, blowing into it. What?<br><br>If you missed it, read the second line of that last paragraph again. &hellip;it is, selflessness. Now, if you haven&rsquo;t been moved, either you don&rsquo;t understand, or you are in that cognitive dissonance, wishing I&rsquo;d get on to the nice God does all the work and you do nothing from &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;; or you&rsquo;re on the &ldquo;I said a sinner&#39;s prayer and now have to work on being good as I have to change myself&rdquo; trip. Both are what the Church teaches (depending on which church you attend). But again, even pastors only answer with &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, or I&rsquo;ll add that backronym Gods Riches At Christs Expense, still grossly missing the mark.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Either way, you would be holding on to yourself by doing those. Maybe to such a degree that would be considered pride or ego, but you&rsquo;d still be holding on to your own strength to deal with those sins at the least, and that is sin in itself. Very important, I&rsquo;ll say that again. Whatever you do in your strength is placing yourself above God. Why? In case you don&rsquo;t know, and I don&rsquo;t blame you if not, as it seems no one teaches this, as it seems they don&rsquo;t know. God is so big that if you have God in your heart, there is no room for you - there is no &ldquo;me&rdquo; in life. Your desires, needs, ego, pride, ID, everything becomes nothing of no value and can&rsquo;t fit in your heart with God. So if you are in your heart, then you haven&rsquo;t let God in. If you are doing things in your strength, then you are not trusting God; you, by default, are the God of your life. Whether you&rsquo;ve said a sinner&#39;s prayer or not, whether you go to church or not, whether you are living a good, Godly life or not. The heart is what matters</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sometimes it can be hard to tell if a person is in control of their life or God is; sometimes it can be very easy. One way is the mouth ( XXX verse). &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been trying to stop smoking&rdquo; Who&rsquo;s trying? Where&rsquo;s that focus? Themselves! Where, on the other hand, a person is constantly going to church, &nbsp;praising God, doing Godly things, and it&rsquo;s all an effort they are making to work their way to heaven (their work, themselves), whose God is there? They are even if they claim to be Christian.<br><br>Most people in those cases really think the religion they follow will save them. And yes, it&rsquo;s just religious activity, which they are unaware is not what God seeks at all. Being religious does nothing for you but entrap you.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So this is not about religion. This may look like religion to some, but if it does, they simply don&rsquo;t know what religion is or the difference here.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I haven&rsquo;t led a person through a sinner&#39;s prayer in about 6 months, and I think I&rsquo;ll make an inclusion for the future. &ldquo;God, push me out of my heart and fill it with you, it&rsquo;s not about me, my pride, ego, desires, needs or myself anymore, teach me to seek what you want, not what I want. After all, I pray this regularly over my own life. It&rsquo;s something to keep reminding ourselves of. Don&rsquo;t try to get yourself out of your heart, again you&rsquo;d fail before you begin, as straight up you&rsquo;d be seeking to do it in your own strength. OK, got that? I hope so</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.tlmtdvrtontb"><span class="c29 c26">Religion opposes relationship </span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Relationship supersedes religion and makes it useless (especially in the sense of religious rites and acts)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">6.1 What are the differences</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">1/ Religion doesn&rsquo;t even comprehend relationship: Example (as poor as it may be); A person may know something you don&rsquo;t are they happy indifferent or sad about it? First there is no middle ground between them there is no indifference. Religion is happy as that secret gives them power (to be the middle-man between you and God). They know what you don&rsquo;t thus you must rely on their superior status between you and God. Relationship is a direct connection so there is no need of religion and therefore relationship is superior and powerful in itself in which there is only sadness for those who don&rsquo;t know or have a strong relationship with God. When someone isn&rsquo;t connecting with God (and wants Godliness or eternal life etc.) then Religion is happy to (pretend to) represent them while hiding the fact that it&rsquo;s actually relationship God seeks. And yes, God is seeking that relationship before you even consider it (we were made for that relationship, did God ask Adam to do any religious actions before the fall?). They simply don&rsquo;t understand, as if they did, they&rsquo;d drop the religious acts immediately and seek relationship themselves. Where relationship looks at others in the knowledge of what God wants (as when you know God, you know what he wants&hellip; and that is&hellip; of course&hellip; RELATIONSHIP). Which only leaves one option Sadness for anyone who doesn&rsquo;t have it and therefore a great desire to connect them to God too.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">2/ Religion seeks power over you, Relationship is empowering you</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">3/ Religion wants things from you (observance, their numerical growth and money); Relationship seeks only to give (understanding, compassion and help)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">4/ Religion oppresses in the guise of helping you, relationship frees with no hidden agenda (of course, discipleship comes with that freedom, so you will help God!)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">5/ Religion hides as much as it can, Relationship reveals as much as you&rsquo;re willing to see</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">There may be more, though I&rsquo;ll leave it there now and ask AI to add</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">If you can&rsquo;t see these simple points, solidly backed by the Bible (or more so I should say solidly backing the Bible), then I wonder if Religion is clouding that vision?</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.tuyyswao4qk2"><span>6.2 </span><span>No Godly excusess! </span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Don&rsquo;t be The Monk in the monastery or nun in the convent, where you are so busy tending to God and Godliness that you have no time and no connection with the outer world. That&rsquo;s like a person learing to be a lifesaver who spends all their time in training and reading the &ldquo;Lifesaving handbook&rdquo; that they never look out at the sea full of drowning people!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">We can be so busy in what we think is our call that we don&rsquo;t tell people about God!</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">I have watched workers in Christian Charities spending all their time on the process of assisting the natural needs of people that they never create opportunities to express their ability to help them meet God and therefore meeting their greater needs. It seems to come across to me as the religious. They seem to be people trying to work their way to heaven by taking care of the needy. They are definitely neglecting the greatest need. They don&rsquo;t seem to understand Gods priorities and/or they seem to be &lsquo;too busy to express the needs of the soul that God wants to meet above the needs of the flesh&rsquo;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">It seems to me to be an avoidance technique to simply make themselves look like they are doing something good for God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Don&rsquo;t make evangelism your duty to work your way to heaven either! Sure it is definitely the superior action of Christianity. Though it is not a ticket to heaven either! </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">6.3 Religious busyness and real Godliness</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Two people go to a rich man; one asks what they can do to be paid $2000 a week. The other says I hear you have $2000 a week for me, and there&rsquo;s nothing I can do to earn it. I accept it and would like to know what I can do to say thank you?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Sure my example lacks in so many ways, yet if I could think of a better one right now I&rsquo;d give it. The point is one seeks reward for what they do (their effort) and the other knows there is nothing they can do, yet still needs to show appreciation for it will not be given to those who won&rsquo;t show appreciation. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">A few scriptures on this:</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Rom 3:28 &nbsp;Then we conclude a man to be justified by faith without works of Law.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Rom 9:32 &nbsp;Why? Because it was not of faith, but as of works of Law. For they stumbled at the Stone-of-stumbling,</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Gal 2:16 &nbsp;knowing that a man is not justified by works of Law, but that it is through faith in Jesus Christ (we also believed into Christ Jesus, that we may be justified by faith in Christ and not by works of Law, because all flesh will not be justified by works of Law).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Now these like many mention works &ldquo;of the law&rdquo; as yes works are mentioned in the law, but more than that; works by themself are legalistic (considered a payment for sin), certainly no more than penance as per Catholicism. So we need faith in God (commitment to God), rather than works &ldquo;of the law&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">But, then due to that faith, work is not negated, but expected; to show appreciation and to glorify God. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Mat 5:14 &nbsp;You are the light of the world. A city situated on a mountain cannot be hidden.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Mat 5:15 &nbsp;Nor do they light a lamp and put it under the grain measure, but on the lampstand; and it shines for all those in the house.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Mat 5:16 &nbsp;So let your light shine before men, so that they may see your good works, and may glorify your Father in Heaven.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">See your what? Evangelistic message? No. &ldquo;Good works&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">6.4 Don&rsquo;t claim Godliness and ignore duty</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">This one takes a little more to understand:</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Mat 10:38 &nbsp;And who does not take up his cross and follow after Me is not worthy of Me.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">A cross was a burden and sacrifice (being sacrificed for your own sins), but it was also very public and the &ldquo;follow after me&rdquo; is crucial. Be like him, act as him, willing to was the feet of others (serve in humility), prayerful, teaching, expressing God and constantly promoting God and Godliness in every circustance. There&rsquo;s more, though I may think of that later. To follow Jesus isn&rsquo;t easy, it&rsquo;s a burden and you will have to sacrifice your old life, to take on his new life (living his way, in his strength not yours). And follow him in his ways, not his actual physical footsteps! Do you do what he did? That constant, prayerful, promotion of God and Godliness in every circumstance and maybe even teaching (at least discipleing if you&rsquo;re not able to teach)?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">James wrote a whole chapter on it, which I&rsquo;ll pick up from the second half:</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:14 &nbsp;My brothers, what is the gain if anyone says he has faith, but he does not have works? Is the faith able to save him? </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:15 &nbsp;But if a brother or a sister is naked and may be lacking in daily food, </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:16 &nbsp;and any one of you say to them, Go in peace, be warmed and filled, but does not give them the things the body needs, what gain is it? </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:17 &nbsp;So also faith, if it does not have works, is dead being by itself. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:18 &nbsp;But someone will say, You have faith, and I have works. Show me your faith apart from your works, and I will show you my faith out of my works. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:19 &nbsp;You believe that God is One. You do well; even the demons believe and shudder. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:20 &nbsp;But are you willing to know, O vain man, that faith apart from works is dead? </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:21 &nbsp;Was not our father Abraham justified by works offering up his son Isaac on the altar?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:22 &nbsp;You see that faith worked with his works; and out of the works the faith was made perfected. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:23 &nbsp;And the Scripture was fulfilled, saying, &quot;And Abraham believed God, and it was counted for righteousness to him;&quot; and he was called, Friend of God.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:24 &nbsp;You see, then, that a man is justified out of works, and not out of faith only. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:25 &nbsp;But in the same way Rahab the harlot was also justified out of works, having received the messengers, and sending them out by another way. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Jas 2:26 &nbsp;For as the body is dead apart from the spirit, so also faith is dead apart from works.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">James, presented faith show by works. And notice he didn&rsquo;t say works &ldquo;of the law&rdquo;. No, the works are different here. They may have been the same actions like the $2000 and it&rsquo;s reward or thanks but differing attitudes (to earn or to respect). Also I consider those works in respect of Yeshua&rsquo;s sacrifice to pay for our sins as works of the Holy Spirit, rather than works of the law. Another way to look at it is a Soldier fights for duty (even though they are paid), where a mercenary fights purely for money. They both fight the same battle, but for different reasons</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Another passage to look at here. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">1Pe 3:13 &nbsp;And who is the one harming you if you become imitators of the good? </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">1Pe 3:14 &nbsp;But if you truly suffer because of righteousness, blessed are you. &quot;But do not fear their fear, nor be disturbed. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">1Pe 3:15 &nbsp;But sanctify&quot; Isa. 8:12, 13 the Lord God in your hearts, and always be ready to give an answer to everyone asking you a reason concerning the hope in you, with meekness and fear, </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">1Pe 3:16 &nbsp;having a good conscience, that while they speak against you as evildoers, they may be shamed, those falsely accusing your good behavior in Christ. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">1Pe 3:17 &nbsp;For it is better, if the will of God wills it, to suffer for doing good than for doing evil. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Peter is saying if you have committed your life to God, you will do good and if you suffer while doing good, people will want to know why, ask; and then you have a fantastic opportunity to evangelise. The benefit of what you do for God isn&rsquo;t just to &ldquo;be good&rdquo;, but to express God and use that opportunity to bring them to the same salvation. To tell them of the Good things God does. Like, in this case, help you deal with trouble.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">6.5 Beyond excuses</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c22">Also Jesus gave the parable of the evil servant </span><span class="c22">Matthew 18:21-35 </span><span class="c9">(the short version).</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">A servant owes a king a massive amount (worth millions today); he begs mercy, and the king forgives the entire debt. The servant then meets a fellow servant owing a tiny fraction (about a few months&#39; wages); who pleas for patience, he bashes him and imprisons him until repayment. The king revokes his mercy, calls the man &quot;evil,&quot; and hands him to torturers until he pays his original debt. Jesus concludes: &quot; So also My heavenly Father will do to you unless each of you from your hearts forgive his brother their deviations.&quot; &nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Sure this is about God&#39;s forgiveness of our sin and our duty to then forgive others offenses. However my point is that; because you were forgiven, act for God. Did the servant decide that he would forgive the other debtor then he could go to the King and demand forgiveness as a just reward for what he&rsquo;d done? No. The difference is commitment and attitude. I could write another whole book on this alone. I hope however you get a good idea of the difference from these few words.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><ol class="c45 lst-kix_nrtmt6xg6exs-0 start" start="1"><li class="c2 c59 c83 li-bullet-0"><span class="c9">The king had an unspoken expectation for the forgiven person to act accordingly.</span></li><li class="c2 c83 c59 li-bullet-0"><span class="c9">Even though we have forgiveness, and therefore &ldquo;faith&rdquo; in God, we do not neglect showing thanks and respect of that forgiveness. As per </span></li></ol><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">If you still don&rsquo;t quite see the point; The first person is like a poor person going into major debt to buy an expensive car to LOOK RICH, The second is a child of a billionaire who simply asks their father for the same make and model of car, who after the father gives it to them also knows (from their upbringing) that their father wants them to show appreciation (do something) for the gift. They ARE in a RICH FAMILY. But they also know they can be cast out of the family for being unappreciative. The same car; the difference is who has it and how they got it. One has a real inheritance, the other is just faking it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Simply; You can&rsquo;t work your way to heaven, but you must show appreciation for the gift. Not that we go to heaven anyway, the Bible says &ldquo;Paradise&rdquo;. And what is it your RICH FATHER asks you to do? Sure take care of the widows and hungry etc. But far beyond that, Mat 28:19 &nbsp;Therefore, as you go, disciple people in all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father, and the Son, and the Holy Spirit, </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Mat 28:20 &nbsp;teaching them to obey everything that I&#39;ve commanded you. And remember, I am with you each and every day until the end of the age.&quot;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c22">This takes precedence, especially as caring for the widows and hungry is leading to evangelism. When doing those things we are constantly looking for opportunities to express God and salvation. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.s35f3coz1v2k"><span class="c29 c26">7 False Christianity and church systems</span></h2><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c17">7.1 Rome</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Rome cemented and centralised everything, including the church. Cement is a blended Mix of elements that goes hard a conglomerate. Rome centralised the </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c44">&ldquo;Early Rome exemplified </span><span class="c44 c17">syncretism</span><span class="c32 c26">&nbsp;in religion, blending indigenous Italic, Etruscan, Greek, and later provincial deities into a tolerant polytheistic system. Romans absorbed foreign gods rather than eradicating them, promoting social stability through this religious fusion.&rdquo;- Wikipedia</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">This also happened with early Christianity, as they maintained their statues and idols, merely renaming them to fit a new persona, as had been the replication of statues. For example, a new emperor would have the heads removed from statues to be replaced with his head. Rome adapted things, and the church no less. Rome introduced priests and garments for them, ceremony and mystical rituals which did not exist in Christianity beforehand. &nbsp;They also introduced a mediator or intercessor capacity for their priests to maintain power&hellip; To gain power over all.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c44">These are not the only Roman introductions. Even festivities such as Christmas </span><span class="c44 c42">Solis Invicti</span><span class="c32 c26">&nbsp;(Birth of the Unconquerable Sun) on December 25, a time of gifts, goodwill and tree decoration. Pope Julius I, around 336 AD, timed Christmas to Christianise pagan rituals, tying The Birth of the Son to the birth of the Sun.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c17">7.2 The shape of things to come</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Fraud entered the Church early in its history, so be willing to stand on the word alone and question all that is not directly recorded, challenge the system and more the status quo.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Is church akin to a marketplace&hellip; A bit of this and a bit of that? Its leadership can seek to appeal to many needs and many types of people in a desire for growth. Are we going to get those things? Is there something we want from it other than God? Beware, here, even many things we think are Godly may merely be religion, not God.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Are we a congregation or customers? I can&rsquo;t justify you, don&rsquo;t seek it through church ritual either, as it&rsquo;s an uncomfortable process of God, not a simple &lsquo;confession&rsquo; or the like.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><h3 class="c81" id="h.tq8owr91hbb0"><span>7.3 </span><span class="c33 c26">&ldquo;Brave New World&rdquo;</span></h3><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">Aldous Huxley wrote Brave New World. If you don&rsquo;t know the story, please do a quick search for a synopsis, as I&rsquo;ll assume a basic understanding of it to go on.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">It seems to me that almost all churches have an Alpha &ldquo;T&rdquo; and a network down through Alphas to Epsilons. The Alphas pander to the masses who scream for SOMA, a direct play on the Greek word, as social control through complacency.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">Are they offering verbal DOPE to entice the complacent majority, the Epsilons? Passion for God&mdash;especially through Godliness and vitality through suitable action&mdash;is often lacking. Do they know what they are doing, or has the modern church become its own &ldquo;Brave New World&rdquo;? In Huxley&rsquo;s story, both religion and alcohol are forgotten, and society is controlled by mind&#8209;numbing SOMA which placates the masses, with notably higher use among those of less intellect.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">Rome used &ldquo;Bread and Games&rdquo;. Today many churches say, &ldquo;Come to church,&rdquo; and may go as far as to seek a sinner&rsquo;s prayer and a &ldquo;commitment&rdquo;. Yet it can feel like they want commitment to themselves above and beyond commitment to God. They seem to want their congregations to obey what they preach. I can&rsquo;t think of many that focus on urging their congregations to read the Bible and research for themselves, to think for themselves within God&rsquo;s standard (with a Biblical foundation).</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">I&rsquo;m going into this a little deeper now, though please remember this is simply a common pattern; it is certainly not all ministers or all churches.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c17">7.4 Consumer Christianity; the lullaby</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">They may not say, &ldquo;Come to church, and you are therefore saved,&rdquo; but it can feel that way. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t forsake the gathering of the saints&rdquo; is heavily leaned on. I am not underplaying that; we must gather, encourage each other, spur each other on to good works and to learn. But we should learn far more than &ldquo;obey me as your leader, pay tithes and bring others&rdquo; (so they too can obey me and bring tithes). Soft messages of &ldquo;maybe consider repenting and certainly commit (to me and this church)&rdquo; are then paraded as being &ldquo;strong&rdquo; on commitment. Yes&mdash;but to what?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">My heart says, avoid trashing here, but make sure the understanding of the need for Godliness comes through. My mind says a big issue is that many of those leaders don&rsquo;t understand themselves. A good, Godly message is paramount, yet sadly lacking. I&rsquo;ll minimise and say some are selfish, yet many simply don&rsquo;t understand themselves.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">Why SOMA? Why placate? Why do we avoid those harder messages of the major need to comprehend, repent (change), and act correctly and earnestly under a proper understanding? Even the selfish don&rsquo;t understand themselves. If they grasped the imperative nature of insight, then transformation, scholarship and its continuous demand of action, they would preach very different messages. The soft messages would be reserved for the napios (babies), those new Christians in their first months of discovery, delivered in &ldquo;new life classes&rdquo;. There may be a moderate middle ground, though the focus should be to drive people to the in&#8209;your&#8209;face reality so often missed.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c26 c31"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">I don&rsquo;t desire the &ldquo;Brave New World&rdquo; as per Aldous Huxley. I will constantly push for metanoeo (&mu;&epsilon;&tau;&alpha;&nu;&omicron;&#941;&omega;), translated as &ldquo;repent&rdquo;, yet like charis, doulos and others, it is far deeper than a simple word gives light on. Yes, I want them to repent&mdash;turn around and toward God. But I also want them to repent&mdash;think differently. That is more literal for metanoeo, the word most often translated &ldquo;repent&rdquo;. Come to a new understanding, a deeper understanding. Not a superficial &ldquo;repent&rdquo; = &ldquo;oh, OK, I think that means be sorry for sin&rdquo; mentality and leave it there without further research. I have too often been told repent means to be sorry for sin, which it doesn&rsquo;t, and worse, does &ldquo;sorry for sin&rdquo; imply change? No. It may be a selfish &ldquo;Oh, I&rsquo;m sorry you were hurt but I&rsquo;ll do it again.&rdquo; There is often no change accompanying many who say they repent. Often it becomes &ldquo;confess your sins to a priest so you can go back out into the world and do it again&rdquo;. Wrong!</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">No, we need metanoeo, a real change of understanding. My understanding changes often, towards a more Godly perception. So by common translation, I am constantly repenting to a greater observance (in both meanings of observance). Maybe metanoeo should in this case be &ldquo;revelation&rdquo;, as this different thought by a change of understanding is not a mere turn but an advancement.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c17">7.5 Awaken</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">The word epistreph&#333; (&#7952;&pi;&iota;&sigma;&tau;&rho;&#941;&phi;&omega;) means &ldquo;to turn&rdquo; or &ldquo;to turn around/back.&rdquo; It is far less common than metanoeo and often translated as &ldquo;convert&rdquo; instead of repent. We find both words in Acts 3:19: &ldquo;Repent ye therefore, and be converted, that your sins may be blotted out&hellip;&rdquo;. &ldquo;Repent therefore and repent&hellip;&rdquo; would be nonsense. Now the King James translates poorly in many ways, though it is still far more reliable than many versions. As another example, it usually translates doulos, the word for &ldquo;slave&rdquo;, as &ldquo;servant&rdquo;, underplaying the cards dealt.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">Personally, I would have it the other way around&mdash;that metanoeo was translated as &ldquo;think differently&rdquo; or &ldquo;have a revelation&rdquo; and epistreph&#333; as &ldquo;repent&rdquo;. I hope you see my reasoning, so I won&rsquo;t delve further into this.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">I passionately seek a brave new world of both awareness and determined action, full of people expressing God in both word and action, spurring each other on to bring every conversation to God and Godliness. Yeshua turned a conversation of acquisition (the woman at the well) into one of Godliness and salvation. What would it be like if we discussed salvation with everyone at the checkout in the supermarket? I certainly don&rsquo;t know, as I have never seen it. But this was illuminated for me about a week ago, so I intend to express God to anyone who can hear, at any time, like He seems to have done. After all, what is a Christian but a disciple of Christ, and a disciple does what their Master does or did.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c26">I will also put both in a sentence to sum this section: I seek that ministers metanoeo and epistreph&#333; their stance. I hope they will &ldquo;see what they haven&rsquo;t&rdquo; and &ldquo;turn&rdquo; from holding the church back&mdash;from change and action&mdash;by promoting consumer Christianity; churchianity.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.dmdcunyua7dv"><span>8 </span><span class="c29 c26">Not a valueless pile of words (uncommitted)</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">8.1 Ticket, not journey</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So you said a sinner&#39;s prayer and are going to heaven&hellip;? OK, let&#39;s go back, a sinner&#39;s prayer is just the ticket, not the journey. Sure, you are going to heaven, but if I&rsquo;m on board a ship going to Australia, there are ports on the way, where if I get off and think this is nice, I&rsquo;ll just live here. Then you were going to heaven (paradise really), but you can&rsquo;t get there till you are back on board and actually land. &ldquo;Going to&rdquo; is not an assurance of arrival.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A sinner&#39;s prayer can be a useless pile of words if you don&rsquo;t take that journey. Travel that narrow path. Let God rule. There it is, who rules your life, who makes those decisions? God or you? Please understand, many of us kid ourselves, many will say Oh no, God is in control, then talk about their nasty neighbour. A lack of love? Maybe&hellip; maybe God isn&rsquo;t in control there, but they have made an immutable decision about their neighbour. Maybe their neighbour is a bit of a problem&hellip; and they, of course, were an innocent angel being attacked with no justification by a hostile neighbour who is simply wrong. This may be the case, but chances are they forget any influence they may have had that the neighbour didn&rsquo;t like. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">8.2 Self-rule exposed</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">We tend to see ourselves as just and righteous, nice people who never cause problems, who are always the innocent ones in any issue&hellip; Grow up! Chances are, you are half the problem. I don&rsquo;t have research for this coming statement, it is merely a presumption of mine, but I&rsquo;ll state - People who have fewer social issues incite fewer social issues. It&rsquo;s not fate, luck or the world against you, that would simply be blame. As guess what, we don&rsquo;t like to see ourselves in a negative light. Hey, we are all the victims here!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I know this principle is true in other areas, as I&rsquo;ve seen in life - People with fewer financial issues cause fewer financial issues. Let&rsquo;s just simplify it totally,- People who cause fewer issues have fewer issues. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">8.3 Commitment matters</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;d like to go on for those still with me. I know many have tossed this book aside in a tizzy, and some are still reading, but maintain disbelief. For God to act in your life, you must be committed; it must be a Life Style, not a Lip-Service. Yet it can&rsquo;t be a forced Lifestyle, the Christian act gets you nowhere fast. The irony is that you need to be committed, but not rely on your commitment.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Is your mind expanding? If not, then either you really know all this, which would surprise me, as I&rsquo;ve never met anyone who knows this, or your cognitive dissonance rules and won&#39;t let you accept it. OK, there is that third option, maybe I&rsquo;m the one kidding myself and wasting my time writing something I think is a paradigm shift, when it&rsquo;s only a basic thing. I think not. If the shift hasn&rsquo;t begun, then I&rsquo;m left to say, pray for it, and if it hasn&rsquo;t happened by the time you have read all this, then please be open to reading it again. I can&rsquo;t say this in the middle of writing it, but if people are recommending this (of course, I don&rsquo;t know yet), then I was right, there&rsquo;s something here. So please, as I said, finish and if it hasn&rsquo;t hit, read it again; if it still hasn&rsquo;t hit, seek out someone for whom it made a difference.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Jesus presented the Christian life as a path requiring continual choice: &quot;Go in through the narrow door. The door is wide and the road is easy that leads to hell. Many people are going through that door. But the door is narrow and the road is hard that leads to life that lasts forever. Few people are finding it&quot; (Matthew 7:13-14, NLV). This &quot;hard road&quot; is walked not by human strength but by grace-enabled perseverance. The apostle Paul expressed this partnership: &quot;Work out your own salvation with fear and trembling. God is working in you. He helps you want to do what pleases Him, and He gives you the power to do it&quot; (Philippians 2:12-13, NLV). The working out is ours; the working in is God&#39;s.</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.mrp2a2w0cv6"><span class="c29 c26">The process and depth of spiritual growth</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c22 c17">9.1 From novice to craftsman</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">There are many kinds of relationships with God, like those who create furniture. From the two-bit hack through to the master craftsman. A two-bit hack uses cheap materials like plywood or particle board and cheap tools; they don&rsquo;t measure and seek to quickly attach pieces with nails and glue. Resulting in items that look and feel rough and will certainly fall apart quickly. Note here, they claim to do excellent work and may not be cheap. At the other extreme, we have the master craftsmen. They use quality wood like redwood and mahogany, quality tools; they measure twice and cut once and use mortise and tenon joints and dovetail joints that hold even more securely than glue or nails. They take the time to produce quality pieces that look and feel good, which will last centuries. Actually doing supreme work, they are not cheap, yet considering the many years their products will last, they are very good value.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9"><br>We are all somewhere between the ignorant novice and the master craftsman or disciplined, effective, Godly &ldquo;Royal priest&rdquo;. Unlike carpenters, the knowledge and experience to master the craft of Christianity doesn&rsquo;t need years of training. There are those of us who are still on the milk who haven&rsquo;t learnt to walk with God and seem like baby Christians after many years. Conversely, some reach heights of maturity in less than a year on the meat of Christian teaching and are ready to deliver their own revelation, delivered to them by the Holy Spirit in line with the word of God. The difference is in their initial understanding in realising the need to let God change you and their willingness for those changes. Those who remain baby Christians hold on to their desires and don&rsquo;t submit very much to God. They maintain a minimal prayer and study life while giving almost nothing of value in physical or mental substance. These people seek to receive; it&rsquo;s all about what they get. Don&rsquo;t stay there, as a Christian who doesn&rsquo;t grow is like the parable of the sower (ref) they are not going to produce the crop that God seeks. What happens to the seed that doesn&rsquo;t come to maturity? It dies. Don&rsquo;t suffer that spiritual death, as God becomes merely an idea, and your destiny would be the same as those who never received God in the first place (Hell).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Now of those who come to maturity (some 40 fold, some 60 fold and some 100 fold). Lets look at those like a percentage of relationship with both God and your neighbour. As Yeshua asked a lawyer about the greatest commandment (love) </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">And the lawyer followed with a question, &ldquo;Who is my neighbour?&rdquo; The parable of the robed man, Luke 10:28? Any person in need who is open to receive and not an opponent is your neighbour. A word of warning here; don&rsquo;t take pleasure in argument and therefore constantly fighting with those seeking a contest (we wrestle not with flesh and blood&hellip;); many love contention (as it gives them abc). We are to be (abc) </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Yeshua said the Greatest commandment is (love). So, what do you do when you love someone? You think about them a lot, you communicate with them and are interested in them and their passions. Do you think of God and pray often? Are you interested in what God wants? Do you even know what God wants? There are things God wants from you specifically and from all of us generally. Generally to pray, to read the word, to commune with our brethren and grow to bear the fruits of the spirit while expressing God to the world. Do you have a strong relationship with God? Then &ldquo;the second is like it&hellip;&rdquo; Are you thinking of others and communicating with them (and of course the things to communicate are not the pleasures and distractions of the world, but God and how to gain God in their lives). Are you showing interest in them before you hit them over the head with your Bible (figuratively)? Are you seeking their best interest (by meeting their needs and carefully expressing God 1peter?, their greatest need)?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Again, some 40, 60 and 100 fold&hellip; As I mentioned, it may help to look at those like percentages. Some of us have got 40% of our relationship with God and the world right, others 60% and a very few have a 100/% strong relationship with God and the world. In my life I have met &nbsp;1 person whom I&rsquo;m confident had a 100% strong relationship with God and man. He knew the heart of God and shared this with people in a way that you could be sure it was the Holy Spirit speaking through him. Then maybe a dozen or two dozen who I&rsquo;d think were in the 90% range. Those who have a strong relationship with God and wisely approach man. Yet these people can have a slight influence of themselves, affecting their relationship with God and man. A touch of personal opinion creeps in. I have met maybe 30 to 100 80% strong Christians, with good relationships, but still some growth needed. Maybe 200 to 300 60-70%ers who basically have it right, but a few issues that really need attention. Then we have the low range, those 40 to 50%ers&hellip; The baby Christians, those are either new to Christianity or those who have never really grown. Maybe around a thousand. Yes, the great majority. For you it&rsquo;s time to step up, to realise it&rsquo;s about growing in all those things and focusing on God first, others second, and ignoring yourself almost entirely (at your expense, just not to your detriment).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">9.2 Mostly religious</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">All up I&rsquo;ll say one to two thousand Christians out of the tens of thousands whom I&rsquo;ve met that claim to be Christian. I&rsquo;ve spent time with many and interviewed a few. These are the people who believe they were born as Christians, but live as the world, or those who said a sinner&#39;s prayer once but never changed and those who have backslidden. The tares among the wheat, the goats among the sheep, the worldly people who go to church but are religious but have no relationship with God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">It seems to me this last group are 90% of the people who call themselves Christians, and then there are 9% who lack a lot who are not in a relatively secure position with God&hellip; Playing with fire&hellip; The fire of Hell!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Now I&rsquo;ll present the 90%. Those who call themselves Christians, but other than tagging themselves with that title, don&rsquo;t even comprehend what Christianity is. Who are they? Those who had a religious upbringing</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">They are more religious than Christians! After all it&rsquo;s about them trying to work their way to heaven! Religious! Let me explain the difference here. Religion is a belief system that ABC , yet there are other types of religion. There are those things we &ldquo;do religiously&rdquo;, those things we constantly do and probably in the same way each time. That is making a religion out of an aspect of life. And finally we have something I read in the world encyclopedic dictionary when I was young, but it impacted me so I&rsquo;d always remember it! &ldquo;That which we turn to in our time of need&rdquo;. &nbsp;Christianity has 2 sacraments (two things expected of us), Baptism and Holy Communion. Yet there are a few expectations beyond those sacraments - ABC worship, fellowship and community shepherding. What is community shepherding? I&rsquo;ve just put those words together to explain ABC</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">9.3 Worship</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c22">And while I&rsquo;m there, what is worship? </span><span class="c22 c17 c50">(to expand)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">9.4 Growth</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Now back to the process and depth of spiritual growth. The process or steps are: 1/ understand 2/ commit 3/ baptism 4/ learn 5/ strengthen relations 6/ discover and train in your call 7/ spread the love. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c50 c22 c17">9.5 Law as springboard</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17 c22">Ephesians 6:10&ndash;12 </span><span class="c9">&ldquo;Finally, be strong in the Lord and in the strength of his might&hellip; For we do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the authorities, against the cosmic powers over this present darkness, against the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly places.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Focus: Defines spiritual warfare as a conflict with organized spiritual powers, not merely human opposition.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">&ldquo;For though we walk in the flesh, we are not waging war according to the flesh&hellip; For the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh but have divine power to destroy strongholds. We destroy arguments and every lofty opinion raised against the knowledge of God&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">Focus: Shows the intellectual and ideological dimension of spiritual warfare and the power of God&rsquo;s truth. - these are opinion arguments like a lawyer, not fighting arguments as many consider the word to mean.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c9"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c9">I struggle with getting my desires for entertainment out of the way, as the things that entertain me can consume a great deal of time (like for example major poker tournaments can take entire days (I haven&rsquo;t played in many years, though I was a winning player with a consistent ROI of about 10 to 20% so if I was to play 100 $1 tournaments I&rsquo;d finish with about $110 to $120 It took years but I turned a few freerolls (no fee to enter promotional touries) into about $30 to $50 (I can&rsquo;t quite remember) then went to 10c tournaments, 20c to 50c then $1 tournaments reaching about $300 to $350 and then got bored and started playing more and more at the same time till I got to 12 games at once and playing so many I made many errors as there was not time to think. I slowly went down a little over a hundred dollars then the ability to play was restricted by my government, So I withdrew the last couple of hundred (or near $200). But how relevant was that? Poker would consume my entire day and all my thoughts. There is also another game I play which takes about 3 days play to complete and takes all my thought, when finished I always think of a few changes I&rsquo;d like to make to improve my play, sending me into a new game.. Games consume me, and if I alow them they will take days even weeks away from me. and my relationship with God suffers (in a multiplied fashion) a week out of having God on my mind sets me back in my spiritual journey up that narrow path by months. It seems to take me a month or two to get back to where I was before that week away. Even as I type this, I&rsquo;m thinking on continuing a game I&rsquo;ve been playing most of each day for the last couple of days (I&rsquo;ve been writing 4-5 pages in the mornings and playing after that. I feel uneasy about even playing a (long-term) game, yet my addiction is powerful and it&rsquo;s not a damaging addiction like drugs or alcohol etc. I haven&rsquo;t played in over 2 years so I&rsquo;m letting go a little. My point here is I know the cost of letting go. I&rsquo;m willing to pay that cost, but I also know I really shouldn&rsquo;t.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.x0p8a49v9lqk"><span class="c29 c26">Your state</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">10.1</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Be conscious of your state; where you stand in God, what may be between you and God and what may be holding you back as well as what God seeks from you as an individual, a worshiper, and what God seeks from you in your call. &nbsp;Seek god and his righteousness. you are righteous, yet your focus needs to be on god, so God can take you away from Sin etc. Being righteous does not mean you cannot sin, and sin disrupt that righteousness one John 3:7 plus - Yet don&#39;t just see yourself as a sinner or even more so, a person compelled to sin don&#39;t have in your mind we are all sinners and we will therefore all sin. It, in a sense, is excusing a hidden desire to sin. You are righteous, yet needing to deal with any known sin. Search the depths of your heart to discover any hidden sins and faults that can be fixed, but not to consider yourself as a sinner, but rather a righteous person who could slip and sin. Especially in the consideration of not being able to deal with sin. First don&rsquo;t even try in your strength to deal with sin, let God take it away. Because anything you do in your strength, you are denying Gods strength, you are then by default considering your strength above Gods and your ability to deal with things above God&hellip; You are putting yourself above God and therefore making yourself God [sin]. Choose to take hold of righteousness given by the cross and it is the choice of what you let rule your heart that matters.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&nbsp;What do you focus on: spirit, action, works, holiness, sin, Afterlife, Revelation, prophecy, etc attitude, guilt/righteousness?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The innocence lost in the Garden of Eden is like a child at about four years old who until that time has run around naked&hellip; innocent, and then begins to realise that they should wear clothes, having lost that innocence. Adam and Eve losing that innocence by partaking of the fruit were like those children coming to a different understanding of themselves, and others around them socially. a loss of innocence, a discovery of themselves [I am, I want&hellip; good in my mind], [you did, you don&#39;t, you hurt&hellip; evil in my mind] Note well, the result was discovery of nakedness, like a child of four or five losing that innocence of a baby and also putting on clothes. I can&rsquo;t say I know the thoughts of a baby, though I think first they don&rsquo;t think in words like us as they don&rsquo;t know them and I second I think their thoughts are so basic that they have not yet even considered themselves their needs or the like intellectually, merely the basics of life (what&rsquo;s this?, eat and sleep *much like that of a rather intelligent animal). However around 3 to 5 most of us reach a basic realisation of self and society (we then begin to wear clothes and are not happy to run around naked). you can&#39;t reclaim that innocence as the knowledge of good and evil remains. you can however choose to ignore the opinion you have or had that; what I like is good and what I do not like is evil. If what you like is good and what you don&rsquo;t like is evil, then you are placing your desires, your will above that of God. Who is to choose what is good and what is evil? You? No God. Forget what you like or don&rsquo;t like, just get into the word of God and learn his heart. Make it your own. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Spend your time chasing after God and his counsel through the word and prayer, discuss Godly things with others, take counsel from them when their position lines up with the word (yet they may help to have you understand it a little more). When their position isn&rsquo;t in line with the Bible softly let them know and guide them, yet don&rsquo;t become entangled with them. As after 2-3 attempts to show them Gods way, if they have not come to a life that seeks Godlyness then spend time with those who will either teach you Godly things or who are willing to learn. We are not to fight (+++)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&#39;d rather call myself yeshuan than Christian as &nbsp;people paint you with their idea of Christianity when you call your self a Christian. they assume that you are like the Christians that they know, and the majority of them are likely to be religious people who do not have a real relationship with god</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Remember you Worship yourself when you carry a load when you carry your burdens when you carry your shame when you carry your needs when you carry your call when you do anything in your strength you are not giving god the opportunity to carry these things and that is because you do not trust God in carrying those things and if you trust yourself more than you trust God you are putting yourself above god you are making yourself god</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Do you take personal responsibility or do you blame Responsibility carries both guilt and honour if you are responsible for something negative or bad you are guilty if you are responsible for something good you are honorable we should all be responsible yet not carry any burden including guilt as we should be giving that up to God. always think should be given up to God </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If we battle not with Flesh and Blood maybe that can even go so far as that our thoughts are also not wholly our own, but inspired first spiritually then developed in our minds, to produce a final thought which we think of as ours. So wrestle with the issues in prayer and any negative thoughts let God take care of them and replace them with godly useful thoughts. &nbsp;If you are busily chasing God especially on the mental front, you won&rsquo;t be thinking on sin, if you are busy thinking of doing good to others you won&rsquo;t be sinning against them etc.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">XXX</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">People preach - prosperity, prophesy, revelation, the law &gt; grace says</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">People dont matter not even your family (expand) (so what really matters?)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Peace fear etc .. the negative in your life </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Are you ready</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.uostdmhfc8e4"><span class="c29 c26">10.2 Distractions</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I earnestly want to write this book, yet today I&rsquo;m finding it difficult to concentrate with the TV blaring in the background, and a ridiculous annoying show (goggle box) distracting me taking my attention from this work. Here is an example of how the enemy seeks to disrupt us. I am now tossing up in my mind to put it aside and play a game on my computer. I am merely a guest at these premises, I choose for the moment to remain here for an undetermined amount of time, as I&rsquo;m encouraged to stay, yet not disrupt the lifestyle of my host who likes to watch these worldly shows. I am moved emotionally by this and wish I could reveal the full meaning and power of charis to them, and that they would take hold of it and become committed to God. Sure this person is a Christian, but that&rsquo;s like saying this person is a Democrat or a liberal or a Tory or whatever one of the political parties may be in your country. Christianity is no different when it comes to understanding their supporters. In politics like Christianity there are many level. There are those who run in seats as members of parliament or the senate etc (the leaders) right through to the lesser levels. The staff, then below them the (t-shirt wearing) promoters, then those who talk about a party a lot to those who support it but only vote for it and rarely talk about it, then those who only vote for it and never talk about it, and finally those who think well of it but don&rsquo;t even vote.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In the sphere of Christianity it&rsquo;s no different, we have ministers right down to those who never discus their views but merely think they&rsquo;re christian as they were christened as a baby and that in their mind is all christianity is, or all that&rsquo;s needed and they will go to heaven by default. I almost overwhelmed by sadness when I think about them. I&rsquo;d like to show them how wrong they are, what the Bible actually says. Yet people become set in their ways, maintaining a mindset that they are right and their view is what the intent of the Bible is. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">We all too easily use the Bible to sup