they deny it&rsquo;s purpose charis in it&rsquo;s entirety to feed the brain, and even though I&rsquo;m not sure what I mean by this it is in my heart to include, this information (from God), is a map of the cardiovascular system which is charis, it is charis that connects the flow of everything. Wow, again I&rsquo;m typing as this comes to me, so I&rsquo;m blown away with the thought and how much it seems to relate. Also take note, I have nothing but charis alone on which that last statement stands, I have not looked into the Bible to research this in any way, it&rsquo;s just that fresh, so I can&rsquo;t back it with scripture&hellip; Yet.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c39">It seem to me that those people are looking at a heart in a body, denying the brain entirely and are self motivated and in sin due to that unmoveable selfimportant stance, (</span><span class="c17 c39">I</span><span class="c39">&nbsp;think Law, So </span><span class="c17 c39">I</span><span class="c39">&nbsp;say law, and you must listen to </span><span class="c17 c39">ME</span><span class="c39">, as </span><span class="c17 c39">I</span><span class="c39">&nbsp;am right). After all they always back themselves with </span><span class="c17 c39">their</span><span class="c18 c26">&nbsp;adherence to the law. Even if they don&rsquo;t see it there seems to always be self importance and pride behind them and a very unloving demanding legalistic spirit. Try to help them see charis and if after a couple of attempts they remain the hard stony heart (legalist) ignoring the greater purpose of it supporting the body; us doing the dos, and producing the fruit of the spirit; assist them to go on their way&hellip; &ldquo;You ain&rsquo;t stopping here buddy&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Yes, reject the words they offer and stop it from continuing as it can only XXX disease the body, the church. Here&rsquo;s another fresh thought; if the heart is bigger than the body it can&rsquo;t support the body, the body would have not use in itself, and the body would be receiving more blood than it can handle, the lungs could not oxygenate it, and it would be braindead, and being braindead, the heart would then kill the body. Ouch. I guess that&rsquo;s backing Paul when he said &ldquo;if the law could justify us then Christ would have died in vain&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Seriously beware of legalists, also people who promote what they are extremely unlikely to adhere to are dangerous hypocrites, puting disease into that body. How many of them make sure they uphold the minor laws like non-duality of crop or garment? Can you assure me that two kinds of crop have not been grown in the field that produces the food you eat? Or there has never been cross breeding of any cattle from the meat you eat has come? Leviticus 19:19 <br><br>There are many other laws that they are likely &nbsp;breaking by partaking of non-kosher food etc. And to be sure, each and every one of these laws are kept. They&rsquo;d need to grow everything they eat themselves and still they&rsquo;d fail&hellip; What of the sacrifices they are not offering? No-one sacrifices in the non-existent temple today. &nbsp;FAIL. Never dare promote an unkeepable legalistic view, no-ne can keep the law, but hey some types of fat are good. I now understand Paul so much more when he wrote all those chapters about honouring Yeshua, The Holy Spirit and the Father, above the law, it presented the law as merely a part of the system that certainly should not be looked at legalistically, but as a spring board to spur you on to far better and higher things. Don&rsquo;t hold on to it as if is what matters above all, what is the use of holding on to a springboard? It&rsquo;s not attached to the side of a pool to hang on to. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Upon the second defence of Godliness, notify them of the scripture that says for you to give 2 chances and that you can therefore no longer discuss Godly matters with them and by default not speak with them. After all, if the conversation is not turning to charis (non-legalistic), godly matters, then why talk at all?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Commit to God, Godliness, growth in such and spreading that by word and deed, yet in a religious, legalistic fashion.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c17 c39">11.4 Grace Vs Legalism</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c44 c82">Christians are judged by grace, not by the law. Salvation comes through grace enabled by Christ&#39;s sacrifice, not human efforts to keep the Mosaic Law, which only reveals sin and points to our need for a Savior.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">The law was given through Moses, but grace and truth came through Jesus Christ (John 1:17). Christ fulfilled the law in the ultimate sacrifice (Matthew 5:17), the final sacrifice that ends its role for those who accept his rule (Romans 10:4) </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">Gal 3:21 &nbsp;Is the law then against the promises of God? God forbid: for if there had been a law given which could have given life, verily righteousness should have been by the law. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c26 c32">Gal 3:22 &nbsp;But the scripture hath concluded all under sin, that the promise by faith of Jesus Christ might be given to them that believe. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">Gal 3:23 &nbsp;But before faith came, we were kept under the law, shut up unto the faith which should afterwards be revealed. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">Gal 3:24 &nbsp;Wherefore the law was our schoolmaster to bring us unto Christ, that we might be justified by faith. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">Gal 3:25 &nbsp;But after that faith is come, we are no longer under a schoolmaster. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">Gal 3:26 &nbsp;For ye are all the children of God by faith in Christ Jesus. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26">Gal 3:27 &nbsp;For as many of you as have been baptized into Christ have put on Christ.</span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26 c82">So by That passage: the law does not bring righteousness or life, faith could not be revealed till Christ, So the law like a schoolmaster ruled for as long as you remain in school. Grace through faith is active for those who have truely put on Christian lifestyle; who produce that fruit.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26 c82">as no one is justified by law-keeping (Romans 3:20).</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c44 c82">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26 c82">While unbelievers face judgment by works under the law (Revelation 20:12-13), Christians experience a judgment seat focused on rewards for faithful service, not salvation, which is secure by grace (2 Corinthians 5:10; 1 Corinthians 3:12-15). Grace empowers holy living without legalistic fear &nbsp;</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26 c82">Rom 6:14 &nbsp;For sin shall not have dominion over you: for ye are not under the law, but under grace.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c32 c26 c82">Gal 5:1 &nbsp;Stand fast therefore in the liberty wherewith Christ hath made us free, and be not entangled again with the yoke of bondage.</span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">Obviously, people don&#39;t understand the word &quot;grace&quot; &gt; Rom 6:14 &nbsp;For sin shall not have dominion over you: for ye are not under the law, but under grace. Eph 2:8 &nbsp;For by grace are ye saved through faith; and that not of yourselves: it is the gift of God: </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">Eph 2:9 &nbsp;Not of works, lest any man should boast. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">Eph 2:10 &nbsp;For we are his workmanship, created in Christ Jesus unto good works, which God hath before ordained that we should walk in them. </span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">So grace saves, not the law, and it produces good work in which we are to live a Christlike life, not a life under the law? Liberty from the law of sin and death (Mosaic), e.g. we are not compelled to grow our own food to assure differing produce was not grown in the same field (a vegi-garden), see Lev 19:19. I can&#39;t grow food, so I must buy food, which may be sinful under the law as I can&#39;t prove it came from fields producing singular produce. &nbsp;Yet does that permit sin? Certainly not! As grace is not licence, in fact the opposite it (overly simplified to save 50, 000 words here), it is a compulsion to be Christlike (Loving, and producing spiritual fruit as per Gal 5:22,23 - love, joy, peace, etc.).</span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">Sure, you can say liberalists are wrong, and they (if sinful) are, but so are legalists, who are proud of their (ignorant) stance. 1Pe 5:5 &nbsp;Likewise, ye younger, submit yourselves unto the elder. Yea, all of you be subject one to another, and be clothed with humility: for God resisteth the proud, and giveth grace to the humble. I am neither a liberalist nor a legalist, I am a Theist. </span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">Legalism is not simply a love of rules; it is self-righteousness in religious clothing. It is self-protection, self-comparison, and often self-exaltation. The legalist does not merely want obedience; he wants a system in which he can feel justified, measure others, and preserve his own standing. In that sense, legalism often uses the law to defend the self rather than to submit to God.</span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">That is why legalism and grace collide. Grace removes boasting. Grace destroys the ladder by which pride tries to climb into God&rsquo;s favour. A legalist may speak loudly about the law, but the deeper issue is often not zeal for God&rsquo;s holiness; it is the need to keep the self respectable, superior, or in control. When law becomes the thing a person leans on for identity, security, or acceptance, it has functionally replaced Christ.</span></p><p class="c15 c10"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c6">Not every person who emphasizes the law is a legalist. Some are sincere but confused. Some are reacting against lawlessness and think they are protecting God when they are really protecting a system. So the point is not to accuse every law-minded person, but to expose the spirit behind the stance when the law is used to exalt self over mercy.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">12</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.lmvezps5fwol"><span class="c29 c26">Rest-oration and Re-velation</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">12.1 </span><span class="c17">Gods R &amp; R</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">God seeks restoration and gives revelation. Before I even get into it, I&rsquo;ll reveal a Revelation coming to me. Firstly, the majority of revelation I get from God is through circumstance, and when I look into the BIble, it backs up what the Bible says.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">As I type this, it is a very new concept, I&rsquo;m not sure what to make of it just yet. Sometimes I get to rare thoughts that seem like a revelation, though, turns into something of no great use. This is the case here; I may be barking up the wrong tree. This is somewhat prophetic, so it&rsquo;s a little different to the majority of revelations I receive (which are usually revelations of Christian life, or at least what should be Christian life), which can then be confirmed in the Bible.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>So this is different. I see a coming change, when? Who knows. Yet this will be unlike the previous events. I&rsquo;m talking of Revival, yet I&rsquo;m not, as I&rsquo;m really talking of renewal. OK, immediately, many will think they are the same or very similar at least (so just call it revival). But it&rsquo;s not. I see revival as like a person&#39;s revival being brought back to life after a xxx to death. The church in revival is like that; the dwindling numbers are reversed in a quick turnaround from its fall as lives are changed by a revived fire. Like poking a campfire with a stick and turning all the wood so it burns better and the fire grows. It is revived but not changed, or if there is change, it is minimal, and the majority of that change is in dedication.</span></p><h3 class="c81" id="h.pr68ba8lg3"><span class="c33 c26">The Church</span></h3><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c17 c39">12.2 Two Gods</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">the church is spiritually having an affair. Maybe not all its members, yet the majority of those who identify as Christian may as well purr, meow and identify as cats. It&rsquo;s members in general are egocentric, which in itself is sin. Who comes first in your world? You or God? What about the majority of your church and what of the other so-called Christians you know; how many of them are not putting themselves first?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">7a.2</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Yeshua sumed sin and service by these statements:</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Mat 16:24 &nbsp;Then Jesus said to His disciples, &ldquo;If anyone wills to come after Me, let him disown himself, and take up his cross, and follow Me, </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">I&rsquo;ve used the LSV here as it very suitably uses the word disown, which is a clearer picture than those translations that use deny. After all, what is it to deny? Could you picture a person saying, oh I&rsquo;ll fast and deny myself food, which then qualifies me as a person who denies myself?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">To &ldquo;deny himself&rdquo; is open to far more interpretation than disown. Disown here means to let go of the &ldquo;Me&rdquo; in life, not to just deny yourself of a few pleasures. Who is in your heart? You or God? We may not have to have pride to be in sin, but we need the humility of disowning ourselves to be in a Godly place. The I want, I need, I&rsquo;m good, I do&hellip; I anything, outside of the humble I&rsquo;s, I submit, I seek Godliness and so on. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Please note this; sIn is not spelt with a capital S but a capital I. It is allowing the old man to rule in whatever way. It appears to me that all sIn comes from our desires, the &ldquo;me&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">So, the First step is to see the value in a true Christian life, then disown yourself (let your personal desires go). After that take up your cross, let&rsquo;s look at that for a moment.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">What is it to &ldquo;take up his cross&rdquo;? First a crucifixion was a death penalty, please allow me to take a little poetic licence as it were on this point. It was therefore a penalty for a crime; which I&rsquo;ll fairly expand to a sin and here&rsquo;s the conceptual part. A sacrifice was a penalty for sin, so it loosely implies sacrificing yourself. Now, poetic licence over, these are now actual implications. It certainly did humble the convict as their clothes were torn off in the process. Also it was a public process; no-one ever &ldquo;carried their cross&rdquo; from their bedroom to their loungeroom.<br><br>Lastly following is not walking on the same roads he walked on physically, but to follow his ways, his lifestyle and commands. So, take up your cross and follow him is to act like him; doing what he did, speaking like he spoke, loving like he loved, in the humility he displayed. No, pride, ego, or self at all. Just all we think say and do in Glory to God.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c17">12.3 No part-time disciples</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">How many of us live like he lived? It appears his every conversation or speech was directed to God. Individual conversations like the woman at the well, where he turned a request of water to a conversation of living water and Godliness, to mass speeches like the sermon on the mount. It seems to me that he shifted any opportunity to speak towards Godly things. We may not have the freedom he had to simply walk around from town to town, constantly expressing God in speech and action. Though we can constantly express God without a (gypsy like) life&hellip; Do we? We may not draw water from wells, but do we discuss God with those at the drinking fountain?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Or other places we may acquire water, like the supermarket? When was the last time you saw someone at a checkout creating a conversation to turn that conversation to God? We generally don&rsquo;t.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Do you have rivers of living water, so much, so that seems to be all that comes out of you?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">I have a massive appetite for God to be first in my life, yet I have only recently (less than two weeks ago) discovered what was always before my eyes. Yeshua constantly spoke of what seems to be only one thing. Divinity. We can&rsquo;t turn every conversation to God as most of us have roles that require role oriented communication. Never expect to hear an Air Trafic Controller get on the radio and say &ldquo;Flight VA205, has anyone expressed the wonders of God to you?&rsquo;&rdquo;. Or how about a judge committing someone to prison then saying to the court room &ldquo;for the rest of you I&rsquo;d like to commit you to a lifetime of service to God, but as I can&rsquo;t let me talk about him a while&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">What can we do? We can deny the carnal self and as Yeshua said in Gethsemani, &ldquo;not my will but yours&rdquo;. We too could choose to submit, not partially, but fully to God. Not I&rsquo;ll serve you God but still hold on to some of those personal desires. If those desires don&rsquo;t promote God, glorify God, express Godliness or the like, what value do they really have? After all what verses follow?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Mat 16:25 &nbsp;for whoever may will to save his life will lose it, and whoever may lose his life for My sake will find it; </span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Mat 16:26 &nbsp;for what is a man profited if he may gain the whole world, but of his life suffer loss? Or what will a man give as an exchange for his life? </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Verse 25 is not referring to loss of physical life, as it comes directly after vers 24 and is expanding on it; explaining it. To deny or disown yourself as per verse 24 is to lose your life as per verse 25. After all it says &ldquo;For whoever&hellip; it is therefore explaining that need of laying down your life mentally, emotionally and spiritually to God. We are to submit totally, not partially; our lives are no longer our own, we are giving them up as a bond service to God (to serve as a slave). In doing so we find a new life in God. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">This is not a part time service; we are deserting Satans Army of Hate and violence and Joining Gods army of Love and peace. Like soldiers, there is need od discipline and it&rsquo;s not a part time thing, you can&rsquo;t be a soldier on week days and a civilian on weekends. Even if you leave the base on weekends, you probably still wear your uniform; though if you don&rsquo;t it is merely &ldquo;leave&rdquo;, permission to be away and out of uniform doesn&rsquo;t make you a civilian during that period. It is not part time service; are we acting Godly and promoting God and Godliness constantly?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">The great majority of &ldquo;Christians&rdquo; are consumer Christians. In it merely for what they get out, which is totally opposite to what is required. It&rsquo;s not about what we get out but what we put in as the third verse there expresses. What gain is there in anything, even the slightest desire we may hold on to that takes our focus from God/Godliness, and what will we give including all of our natural desires in exchange for a life in God?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c17">12.4 Total surrender</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Give it all, everything about you outside Godliness needs to be given up, &ldquo;Not my will but thine&rdquo; Let your will go entirely 100% and seek his</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c39">How? Now we have a problem. But, it&rsquo;s solved easily. Removing yourself from your life is an extremely difficult thing to do&hellip; by the nature of it, how can you remove you? That concept may be easy to see, but if you ask it &ldquo;how can I remove me?&rdquo; then you&rsquo;re already in the wrong place. After all we now have an example of this whole section. By asking that question we would be doing exactly what we are to give up doing. In five words self appears twice &ldquo;how can </span><span class="c17 c39">I</span><span class="c39">&nbsp;remove </span><span class="c17 c39">me</span><span class="c18 c26">?&rdquo; The focus is on yourself in your strength doing the action yourself. Totally opposite to what we need to do. No, indeed, let God do.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c39">Whatever we do in our own strength, is relying on our strength, our ability, we are then relying on ourselves not God. It should be obvious by now that in doing so we are making ourselves the power factor of our lives, the director of our lives, the God of our lives. We are making ourselves God by even contemplating the effort </span><span class="c17 c39">WE</span><span class="c18 c26">&nbsp;would need to put in. I can&rsquo;t remove me from my life, but it is very simple to ask God to push himself in my heart and push me out (as I don&rsquo;t have the strength to do so). <br><br>I believe it must be total, what gain is there in holding on to the slightest personal desire, the smallest thing where what you want comes before what God wants? The progression of thought is that then it needs to be total surrender, in total service. No consumer Christianity at all. It would be wonderful if even 10% of the churchians came to this understanding and sought Gods action in their lives then through their lives. Forget watching a movie or favourite TV series, get out into society and express God to others.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">The church in general is having a spiritual affair, not in giving their love to another, but in giving their love to themselves. There is a difference in motivation which is the major aspect. Two people may change, one from their own effort in (actioning) that change and the other in humbly asking God. Both may do exactly the same thing in the process, for example giving a stranger a meal. The first does so to get to heaven; the second as they have submitted and Gods order to them as a slave was to feed the hungry.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">We can&rsquo;t do anything to get to heaven, if we think we can or if we do anything to try it is denying God, through Yeshua&#39;s sacrifice. Though once we accept that and commit to God we are to still do the very same Godly things. The difference is attitude, why we do what we do.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c17">12.5 Childlike humility</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Yeshua spoke of being as little children as theirs is the kingdom of heaven. It&rsquo;s the innocence of a small child under 5 that he was speaking of. It&rsquo;s innocence that was lost by Adam and Eve in the Garden of eden, partaking of the knowledge of good and evil, is a loss of innocence. Sure a small child of two or more will know about punishment and what may or may not get them in trouble. But do they mentally process it as good and evil or comprehend responsibility in relation to it? I remember a Scientific study of Children to discover this (have I explained this study &ldquo;blocks&rdquo; elsewhere?)</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">It&rsquo;s a knowledge of responsibility and a choice therefore of three things; to be responsible, to be irresponsible, or to submit to God. God only values the submission. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Those who have not already thrown this book out as it stands against their unmoveable belief that &rdquo;Jesus came to forgive and save sinners, so as a sinner Jesus came to save them and therefore they are saved while still being a sinner (and of course having a desire to maintain those sins).&rdquo; That&rsquo;s true, but the second half is (often &nbsp;intentionally) predicated on the first and certainly unBiblical in itself. That&rsquo;s like saying soldiers wear green, so they are greenies and therefore care for the environment. Sure soldiers wear green, but they are destructive to the environment by blowing it up with their explosives, not therefore aligned to nature. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">All too many take one truth to support their beliefs while ignoring the foundation of that truth which opposes those very beliefs. We cling to cognitive dissonance. In the majority of minds either they are right and will stand on anything that supports them while presenting anything that doesn&rsquo;t as an unjust attack from an ignorant enemy.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Now I&rsquo;m compelled to look further into what I read in the Bible. In my teens I was shown the linguistic variation and why it mattered through this following example: </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">&ldquo;In english we have the word &ldquo;love&rsquo; and we need other words to explain what kind of love, where the Greek has four different words for love that convey those aspects. Storgie The love for family and maybe friends, Philia brotherly love, or that for associates, eros sexual love, natural attraction or desires (maybe it&rsquo;s eros chocolate if I say I love chocolate), and Agape total sacrificial love, a love so deep you would die for them.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">So the English word often pales in significance, when attempting to understand what was really trying to be conveyed by those who originally wrote the new testament as it was written in Greek. We face a massive problem if we take the english translation at face value, as it falls far short of the mark, which ironically a meaning of the word sin is &ldquo;to miss the mark&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">I remember someone leaving a message that finished in &ldquo;&hellip;my Bible is in English, so why do I need to know the Greek?&rdquo; I found that too somewhat ironic, as again the simple fact is The Bible was written in Greek not English, so we don&rsquo;t truly understand it in English without expanding it by many words. Most translators have done so in preference to the message they sought to present. They were preferential to one word or another dependant on what they wanted to say.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c17">12.6 Forgotten firewood</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c39">As an example Peter, Paul and James opened their letters saying things like (eg. Romans 1:1) &ldquo;Paul a servant of Christ Jesus&hellip;&rdquo; as per The king James. Now the Literal version says &ldquo;Paul, a </span><span class="c17 c39">slave</span><span class="c18 c26">&nbsp;of Jesus Christ&hellip;&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Why? The King James translators wanted to present it that way. I can only guess as I can&rsquo;t know exactly why, but they may have wanted it to be less demanding of the readers, softer and easier to accept</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">That is a very simple difference, yet there is quite a difference between servant and slave. Now look again at one word &ldquo;grace&rdquo;, it can take an entire book to expose, and still maybe insufficiently.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c18 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c18 c26">Why do I need to know the Greek? One English word often can&rsquo;t replace one Greek word and therefore the English Bibles can&rsquo;t convey what the original &nbsp;greek language intended. Especially when understanding Charis!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Even in typing these words, I&rsquo;m seeing it more clearly. The renewal will be different as this fire, and yes, it&#39;s the same fire (the fire of the Holy Spirit is behind all of these). Isn&rsquo;t being churned and turned for more flame from the same source. This time it will be extra wood being placed on the top. Now this is also not new green wood; it&rsquo;s not fresh wood. It&rsquo;s been there the whole time, but it&rsquo;s just been hidden away in the back of the camping area, and everyone has forgotten about it. OK, let&#39;s drop the analogy </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are things in the Bible that seem to have been forgotten long ago. Powerful life-changing things, like this whole message on charis/grace. Those verses have been there all along, but how many have revealed their meaning? Not the &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; message that those who have never bothered to look embrace. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are probably many more, like doulos, poorly translated as servant when its meaning is quite different, being a slave. Do I know of these forgotten lumps of figurative wood, that are real-life changing gems of understanding? I have been so caught up in charis alone that I&rsquo;ve only looked into doulos a little and the fruits of the spirit, of course. I know there will be many more. Someone just needs to ask &ldquo;What does this really mean?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I am throwing Charis and the char family on the fire and shouting (figuratively), &ldquo;Hey, look at this&rdquo;. I beg others to start seeking those hidden gems of the Bible to also throw on the fire of the spirit.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">12.7 Upward spiral</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You see, what I conceive is a renewal of understanding; this fire isn&rsquo;t just being turned to give more opportunity for flame, it&rsquo;s being refuelled with a better comprehension of the relationship with God. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">OK, so here&#39;s the first kicker. We are being restored to a new understanding that has been there all along, just forgotten. It&rsquo;s a personal restoration of your relationship with God and a restoration of understanding in the church. It&rsquo;s a revelation to a few, which is the initial lead to this restoration, yet as we are restored in relationship individually and as a church as a whole, revelation itself grows. Many people will begin to have new revelations about old things that were in the Bible all along, merely forgotten.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&rsquo;s an upward spiral, which, right now as I type this, makes me think of a tornado, pulling things from the ground into the sky. We are being drawn up, but not directly; it&rsquo;s circular, a spiral. As something is revealed to us we restore it, or God restores it in our life; individually and as a church as a whole, a part of our relationship with God is restored, we are drawn up a little in our spiritual walk with God, and from that new height, we gain a new perspective, which inturn brings another revelation which is then a further restoration in that relationship. We are then a little higher again, and the process continues. Around and around, higher and higher. Yet we are never so high that ego comes in as ego, pride and self, all those me things are firmly on the ground, we are being taken away from them and growing in height here is growing in humility, as &ldquo;God resists the proud, but He gives grace to the humble&rdquo;. In this process, we are also learning humility, which attracts grace</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I believe restoration and revelation are so tied that one will bring the other. Primarily, a minor revelation will bring the desire of restoration, and once applied, it brings greater revelation, in which we draw closer again to God. As we draw closer in restoration, the revelations grow in number and immensity. {the upward spiral}</span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.jj4kbjebc7gv"><span class="c33 c26">Two Gods</span></h3><p class="c2"><span class="c17">12.8 Self on the throne</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are two Gods; you worship one or the other. Either YHWH God on high, or yourself, your own ego, pride, ID, needs, desires, even if you have some humility (and some people who let others walk all over them think it&rsquo;s humility), you still focus on one of two things you or God (even when you may be driven by other thoughts like the pursuit of wealth, that pursuit is about you not the wealth).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&rsquo;s all about the focus. Not the status or level of ego, etc. Two people can do exactly the same thing, like give a meal to a stranger. One is doing it to be noticed, admired, loved, or to work their way to heaven; whatever it may be, the catalyst is self, what they want. The other is doing it because they realised that their old God &ldquo;themself&rdquo; did nothing &ldquo;truly&rdquo; good for their life, there were always issues in one way or another, then when they discovered they could have A NEW LIFE! Not LIVING FOR THEMSELVES, but in repentance living for God. Forget the heaven-hell situation; salvation is more about now than then. When they discovered they gain those wonderful fruits of the spirit, and it is those fruits by which they shall be known. They gave their life to God, and now are also giving out a meal; no difference there, but it&rsquo;s in the heart. They are doing so not for any of those previously selfish reasons, but purely because their LORD requested them to, and they Love both God and what God is doing for them so much that thaey just want eveyone to have what they have, so they start by blessing others, and earnestly seek opportunity to rev eal the greater blessing that recipiant can have which is to also gian those wonders of God. Which, by the way, all Christians have, as God turning you from sin to Godliness and therefore gaining those fruits of the spirit is the evidence.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Two Gods, YHWH Lord, or You! Not convinced, what&rsquo;s in your heart? I want&hellip; OK, you want what to get [whatever], to be [whatever, ego building], or to give [to strangers and God directly] or to be [a blessing]? If those things you want are for you, a new car, a new friend, to be loved, etc., then you are your </span><span>g</span><span class="c1">od (yes, a very small g on that one). If your focus is God, Godliness and others for their benefit and to help them find God, then YHWH is likely your God. Still, there is that hidden side that few see through. Many people do Godly things like feeding poor strangers merely to work their way to heaven; as they don&rsquo;t truly understand, nothing you do (other than a real commitment to God) will get you to heaven&hellip; only keep you out (again, not that we go to heaven anyway). It&rsquo;s all in the attitude.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Still not sure? OK, try this one. Two people go to church; one as it is expected of them to get to heaven, the other as they just want to praise God and express to others to discover a real relationship with God, because they know that there are tares amongst the wheat, goats amongst the sheep and those &ldquo;cast out demons and healed the sick, in you name&rdquo; yet he said go away I never knew you.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sin is not merely breaking a rule; it is self-rule over God-rule. It is the self deciding that it will be its own authority, its own standard, and its own judge. In Eden, humanity did not simply commit an act of disobedience. It chose autonomy. It chose to define good and evil on its own terms. That is why sin is so deeply rooted in pride, desire, and self-exaltation: the self wants the throne. In that sense, sin is the self trying to take God&rsquo;s place.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This is why temptation so often begins with &ldquo;I want.&rdquo; The problem is not merely the outward act, but the inward posture. When the mind is bent toward self, the flesh becomes louder, desire becomes ruler, and God is pushed aside. Believers do face temptation, but they resist it by turning the mind toward God, not by trusting the strength of the self. The moment self becomes the centre, sin is already at work.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">12.9 Fruit and revelation </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This is serious, everyone is in jeopardy here, as those who cast out demons and heal the sick are almost always ministers! Many of the ministers don&rsquo;t have that charis relationship and are in great need of this revelation. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">7c.6</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Here&rsquo;s a tip&hellip; get this, no new revelation here, you will know them by their fruits! No, not the exorcisms, not the healing, as they were cast out, remember. It&rsquo;s the fruit, the love, joy, peace (etc.). There are a few ministers that I have noticed lacked in areas like this. But this is how you &ldquo;know them&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In fact (this is a personal opinion), I think restoration and revelation are so tied that they can be another evidence. The more a person grows in the walk up that narrow path, the more personal revelations they will have and the more focus they will have on God. Which I think will be evident. In fact, now that I&rsquo;m typing this, and I&rsquo;m still just typing the things the Holy </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Spirit is putting in my heart, fresh revelation, so I haven&rsquo;t put them to the test yet. So, I think you will be able to tell how far a person has travelled that path by 1/ how obsessed in their conversation about God and Godliness with everyone they meet (You know a person is likely full on for God if all they want to do is turn every conversation to him in some way). And 2/ The level of insight and depth they have in those conversations. Of course, that will vary with who they are talking with. You won&rsquo;t talk of the deep, meaty subjects with an unsaved person, but they would be talking of the blessings of god, those fruits and the value of having God in your life. And they may not talk about the meat with those who are not far along the journey, either. Yet when they meet someone who shows knowledge or at least understanding, their conversation will be on substantial revelations which can easily be verified by the Bible. Yet they will be encapsulating. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">We will see mind-blowing stuff coming from the average person that was always in the Bible, just forgotten for millennia. </span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.49phi3qxvkgm"><span>The Fast Track</span></h3><p class="c2"><span class="c7">12.10 fast-track grace</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This took many years in one way or another. Again, I&rsquo;ll avoid the testimony. I&rsquo;ll just go back about a year, then 8 months. About a year ago, I came back from decades of a backslidden state. So, quite simply, I had little recollection of a vague Christian life. About 8 months ago, I discovered Strong&#39;s definition of charis, and its importance, after all, again, it is that which saves us. Since that time, it&rsquo;s been revelation upon revelation; there have been dozens of revelations in my upward spiral.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I am now at a stage where I simply must write this and express it to as many people as I can. So I urge you to pass it on. However, over the last few days (less than a week), there has been another. I&rsquo;ll explain that as soon as I deal with the fast track.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, you don&rsquo;t need a year to discover this and implement it. I&rsquo;m giving you as much of the information of what I have learnt as practical. Some things are not so practical, and others are beyond my comprehension of explanation and vocabulary. I simply can&rsquo;t come up with the words. Besides, I think there will be a ton of information here anyway.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How to fast-track.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Read everything carefully &gt; understand the commitment (it&rsquo;s not hard, but it&rsquo;s intense) &gt; decide ( if yes go on, if no, then just put the book down once you have finished and go on living for yourself) &gt; If you want to truly commit to God, do so and not partially; earnestly seek for your every thought to start with God, your every action (god above all, ask he push the you out of your heart and fill it with himself look to study constantly at every chance, to grow constantly, including in prayer etc. &gt; seek to express God everywhere to everyone.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>People in ministry spend years learning before they even go to Bible college, then 2,3, 4 years later, enter ministry and still may know little. Under the anointing by choosing to seek God, fill your heart and</span><span class="c46">&nbsp;push you out </span><span class="c1">(Because it&rsquo;s very hard to get yourself out of your heart - ask God), you may reach a similar level of understanding and relationship with God as them in less than a year.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And remember when you read the Bible, it&rsquo;s not about trying to get what you want it to say out of it (you are god in that case). Seek real revelation, even when it hurts (in my experience, at some stages it will hurt).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.7ihhu3kw9i5l"><span class="c33 c26">The new revelation</span></h3><p class="c2"><span class="c17">12.11 Talk like your Master</span></p><p class="c2"><span>This is quite simple and obvious, yet obviously ignored. Before I get into it, please understand this is merely an observation, and I&rsquo;m quite </span><span>convicted</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;on this coming point. I stand before God guilty on this point, so I&rsquo;m not having a go at you. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Over the last week. I have been looking at: &ldquo;What is a Christian?&rdquo; I&rsquo;d asked a few people, and it jumped out at me, something people seem to miss that I think now should be glaringly obvious. Simply a disciple, and what is a disciple? One who does what their master did and taught. OK, what did our master do and teach, that we can do&hellip; after all, we are not going to get crucified, and many will have issues with casting out demons and healing with faith circumstances. But what are the things he constantly did and said that we can do&hellip; and say. First repent was the first thing he said in ministry; second, he spoke of love a lot. But here is the kicker. Everything else he said and did. Well, we can include feeding everyone around, including and especially strangers. But then what did speak on</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It seems all he ever spoke on was God and Godliness. Every recorded conversation with groups or individuals had some aspect of God about them. He was only interested in turning conversations to things of Godly value.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Wow. I&rsquo;m not saying Wow, this is a massive revelation, it&rsquo;s actually quite small. But WOW, how many people constantly converse of God? I&rsquo;d never thought of that. If we are disciplined in the way of Yeshua, then what did he do at what seems every chance&hellip; Talk of Godly things. Do you? I certainly haven&rsquo;t, yet now I want to, I earnestly want to be the person who emulates him by turning every conversation to Godly things.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Think about it, when was the last time a stranger started a conversation with you, was it to draw you to a Godly conversation? No? It&rsquo;s extremely unlikely. Have you sat on a bench outside a supermarket and if another was to sit beside you, you began a conversation to turn it to God? Ever sat in a doctor&#39;s waiting room to hear a person start talking to the person beside them and turn that conversation to God? To be a disciple we do what our master did and said&hellip; Well that&rsquo;s what he did!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you feel convicted that&rsquo;s OK, as I said, so do I welcome to reality. I&rsquo;d only just discovered it myself, so I need to change. Again, I ask God to change me here, as this too won&rsquo;t be easy. Now there are people who go out a few hours a week specifically to tell others about God. Am I letting them off the hook? No. As they too keep to themselves in those waiting rooms or benches outside supermarkets. Come on, have you ever seen one of them waiting at a checkout, turn to the person behind them and say, &quot; How&rsquo;s life? Mine&#39;s wonderful, would you like to hear about something that&rsquo;ll set your life ablaze? Or some other intro that will lead the conversation to God? No. After a night in the city centre handing out tracts and shouting out &ldquo;You need Jesus to save you from Hell&rdquo; or similar, they go home to live a rather normal life like just about everyone else. Most of the time anyway. Yet still outside those busy pedestrian areas where people go specifically to evangelise, I can&rsquo;t recall at any time a person turning a conversation to god&hellip; unless I was wearing a T-shirt with a Christian innuendo (which I do on occasion) and the come up to ask &ldquo;Are you a Christian?&rdquo; which has happened. Though I set that up. Note here, it didn&rsquo;t say Jesus or have a cross; it was innuendo. If you are blantant eg it says, Jesus. They know straight up and have no need to come up and ask, and therefore create a godly conversation opportunity. I&rsquo;ve worn shirts like that before, too, and people seem to want to avoid you when wearing them!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Fish don&rsquo;t bite hooks; they bite the worm on the hook! (In case you&rsquo;re missing this one, Jesus is the hook, the worm is some other message that the hidden hook of Jesus is in, and I&#39;m not saying be deceptive, just attractive; the worm attracts the fish to the hook.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">12.12 Door, lock, and key</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It is a restoration to God from revelation that produces further revelation. The law doesn&rsquo;t offer either, so it is separate and greater, as yes, God does seek obedience, yet for a purpose. The obedience is a key to gain relationship with God. it doesn&rsquo;t open the door, nor is it the action of you walking through. God cares less about you unlocking the door as to his desire that you walk through it. What is the value of unlocking that which you can&rsquo;t enter, as you have never learnt to walk?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In this picture, sin is the door, the law is the lock, and the presence of God is on the other side. Locking or unlocking the door is not nearly as relevant as opening it. The law is not the focus, but the sin that needs to be taken away, like opening that door, that which is between God and us. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The law requires sacrifice for sin, the key in the lock. Christ&rsquo;s sacrifice unlocked the door permanently. We can now enter at any time as long as we don&rsquo;t hold onto that sin. If we keep sinning what sacrifice is left? The lock is still in the door, the law still exists, but it is unlocked by Christ. Why focus on a lock that no longer does anything? Just open the door (walk away from sin). Is the lock greater than the key in it? Are we not to enter and go beyond the door (sin)? If we open the door and won&rsquo;t let go of that handle (of sin), can we enter to reach God?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sure, we can somewhat enter, but not to fullness as there is no freedom to walk in a room while holding that handle! The law will bind you as it both reveals and imputes guilt; it is no more Godly than the sin it reveals, remember the law is not the sacrifice it demands.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Now, on the subject of sin and guilt. I don&#39;t know a guilty person; they all tell me they&#39;re innocent! It is extremely rare to find a person who admits their guilt. It has been said, &ldquo;prisons are full of innocent people&rdquo;. The tendency for people is to uphold self-righteousness. We do what we do because it was our right, even when wrong. People tend to believe that if there is a conflict of interest in any way that they are the innocent, righteous party. We act as our own lawyer - a lawyer does not seek to deliver the truth but a convincing argument to present a possible innocence and win a case even if their client is guilty, and even if they know of that guilt.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Don&#39;t let your mind get contaminated w/ any ungodly thing</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Has grace diminished (almost left the church) it certainly is being forgotten</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Perfectionism brings legalism, is? Moralism is legalism</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>13</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.k78mko84k8vi"><span>Grace discovered and received</span></h2><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c7">13.1 Amazing Grace: A Song That Almost Says It All</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Amazing Grace&rdquo; is probably the best&#8209;known Christian song about grace. Its words show a surprisingly deep grasp of what grace does, yet even here I think there is more to see if we read it in the light of charis and Thayer&rsquo;s definition.</span></p><p class="c0 c11"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">Amazing grace! how sweet the sound,</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">That saved a wretch like me!</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">I once was lost, but now am found,</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">Was blind, but now I see.</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">&rsquo;</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">Twas grace that taught my heart to fear,</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">And grace my fears relieved;</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">How precious did that grace appear</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">The hour I first believed!</span></p><p class="c0 c11"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">The Lord hath promised good to me,</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">His word my hope secures;</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">He will my shield and portion be</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">As long as life endures.</span></p><p class="c0 c11"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">When we&rsquo;ve been there ten thousand years,</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">Bright shining as the sun,</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">We&rsquo;ve no less days to sing God&rsquo;s praise</span></p><p class="c2 c11"><span class="c1">Than when we first begun.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Beautiful words that have a good understanding of Grace. In my mind they still fall short, though lets look at some of Amazing Grace. </span><span>&ldquo;I once was lost, but now am found.&rdquo; That is already a clue. We do not so much </span><span class="c42">find</span><span>&nbsp;grace as grace </span><span class="c42">finds us</span><span>. Lost sheep don&rsquo;t locate the shepherd; the shepherd locates them.</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>&ldquo;Was blind, but now I see&rdquo; goes far beyond &ldquo;unmerited favour.&rdquo; Grace doesn&rsquo;t just change our legal status; it opens our eyes to realities we could not even conceive </span><span class="c1">without it. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>&ldquo;&rsquo;Twas grace that taught my heart to fear, and grace my fears relieved.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s a line many people sing without any thought. But &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; by itself does not teach your heart to fear God, nor at the same time relieve your fears. This is much closer to what Thayer describes: &ldquo;the merciful kindness by which God, exerting his holy influence upon souls, turns them to Christ&hellip;&rdquo;&mdash;there is teaching and turning going on.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>In my Australia analogy, my ancestors did not discover the continent; the news about the discovery came to them.</span><span>,</span><span>In the same way, </span><span class="c42">charis</span><span>&nbsp;&ldquo;finds&rdquo; us. </span><span>&nbsp;where Thayer says &ldquo;exerting his holy influence&rdquo; God </span><span>moves us to the point of &ldquo;passenger registration,&rdquo; and continues the work.</span><span>&nbsp;&rsquo;Twas grace that taught my heart to fear,&rdquo; is a statement of how Grace reveals the awe of God, the &ldquo;Wow factor&rdquo;, the </span><span>recognition </span><span>&nbsp;of his power and therefore the fear (and danger) of living without that</span><span>&nbsp;relationship with Him</span><span class="c1">. This line is a reverent fear, a recognition of his power. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c55"><span class="c17">13.2</span><span class="c7">&nbsp;Grace now, not just then</span></p><p class="c55"><span>At the very same time, &ldquo;grace my fears relieved.&rdquo; As we learn God&rsquo;s character, our fears are being taken away. We start seeing the smallness of our own bodies and possessions compared to eternity, and the meaninglessness of so much we used to cling to. Little by little, as we learn more of God and give our lives to Him more, many fears lose their grip. Yes, I do say </span><span class="c42">more</span><span class="c1">. You make one real commitment to God, but do you become sin&#8209;free in that instant, never to sin again? No. It&rsquo;s a process. You begin to trust Him then, but do you not learn to trust Him more day by day? We are constantly letting go of the world and our personal status (the self, the ego, the selfishness) as grace keeps working.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>&ldquo;The Lord hath promised good to me&rdquo; is often misunderstood. Some hear only &ldquo;I get good things in heaven,&rdquo; as if the good is almost entirely future. But the hymn</span><span>&nbsp;doesn&rsquo;t stop there &nbsp; </span><span>&ldquo;His word my hope secures; He will my shield and portion be as long as life endures.&rdquo; </span><span>The good promised </span><span>&nbsp;here is not only future reward;</span><span>&nbsp;&ldquo;AS long as life endures&rdquo;, </span><span>God Himself as shield and portion now, all through this life.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>The author John Newton knew the prime form of Gods goodness is &ldquo;shield and portion&rdquo;. - </span><span>protection and daily sustenance. Yet, I believe that goes deeper than food or money. God sustains us emotionally and mentally as well. He promises to meet needs</span><span>, occasionally there may have been some specific instances in the Bible where God promises certain individuals more, but he meets needs especially in the fruits of the spirit, </span><span>Those are the things our happiness </span><span class="c42">should</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;be based on: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, and so on, rather than possessions, power, or physical attraction.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">(In fact/remember) Those fruits are not an addition to your life as a Christian - they are the result of every Christian life and the evidence itself that you have become a Christian</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Not that God can&rsquo;t meet those desires; He can, however he seeks for us to lay our desires at his feet and take up his (those inner fruits rather than worldly things).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Take attraction as an example: God may not make you physically better&#8209;looking, but the fruit of the Spirit are very attractive things. If you have them, people will be drawn to that, and to you as you display them. And remember: </span><span class="c42">charis</span><span>&nbsp;is the process of gaining and displaying them. Grace is not only the ticket; it is the journey in which God makes you into a living evidence of His goodness.</span></p><p class="c69"><span>Newton finishes amazed at the enormity of eternity: &ldquo;when we&rsquo;ve been there ten thousand years&hellip;&rdquo; Personally, I don&rsquo;t even need to get that far before I&rsquo;m overwhelmed. I&rsquo;m already bursting at the seams from the &ldquo;living water&rdquo; of God&rsquo;s word within, from the way He constantly reveals understanding and gives fantastic things inside us in the form of the fruit of the Spirit. Eternity will be wonderful, but grace is already wonderful now.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Editing notes<br><br>Show how the hymn points beyond &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; toward charis as:</span></p><ul class="c45 lst-kix_2e0t64m3xtv4-1 start"><li class="c28 c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">God&rsquo;s initiative (grace finds you).</span></li><li class="c28 c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">God&rsquo;s inner work (teaching fear and relieving fear).</span></li><li class="c2 c28 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">God&rsquo;s present goodness (&ldquo;as long as life endures&rdquo;).</span></li></ul><ol class="c45 lst-kix_2e0t64m3xtv4-0 start" start="1"><li class="c40 c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">Finish with your contrast: many sing this with tears, but do not actually believe grace gives real, present fruit.</span></li></ol><p class="c71"><span>That makes this section a bridge between lexical work (Thayer, Strong) and the pastoral/theological argument you&rsquo;re making.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">14</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.mbg4dyjp9k43"><span class="c26 c29">A mini gospel in itself</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">14.1 Grace in one word</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">At the heart of the Christian message stands a singular, transformative reality: &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; (charis)&mdash;the unmerited divine influence that initiates, sustains, and completes our salvation. This grace is not merely a feeling or idea; it is God&#39;s active, empowering favour extended to those deserving the opposite. As Scripture declares, &quot;For by grace you have been saved through faith. And this is not your own doing; it is the gift of God, not a result of your own works. So no one can be proud of himself&quot; (Ephesians 2:8-9, NLV). This gift originates entirely from God&#39;s loving nature, not human worthiness.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&Chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; (charis) is the gift that contains within itself the power to be received. It is God knocking, drawing, and empowering. It makes faith possible, change real, and perseverance achievable. It marks the narrow path, supplies the strength to walk it, and guarantees the finish for those who continue. This grace is completely God&#39;s gift yet requires our continual receiving&mdash;not as a condition for earning favour, but as the very way unearned favour changes us. In this divine-human partnership, we find both the profound mystery of God&#39;s control and the serious responsibility of human freedom, held together in the boundless generosity of unmerited divine love. Truly the gift that keeps on giving.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Indeed, it is a gospel in a single word. Gospel means &ldquo;good news&rdquo; and if &ldquo;the merciful kindness by which God, exerting his holy influence upon souls, turns them to Christ, keeps, strengthens, increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection, and kindles them to the exercise of the Christian virtues,&rdquo; isn&rsquo;t good news, I&rsquo;m lost as to what is. It is the very message of salvation and Christian growth wrapped up in a single word.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let&rsquo;s look at a few other scriptures that contain it. I&rsquo;m due to also deliver variations of grace (not charis) as grace is found in both the Old and New Testaments, which were written in different languages (Hebrew and Greek). Now, due to major linguistic differences, &ldquo;grace&rdquo; in the Old Testament (&#1495;&#1461;&#1503; &ldquo;che&#770;n&rdquo;) actually does mean favour with secondary meanings of beauty and preciousness.<br></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">14.2 Grace comes to the humble</span><span class="c1"><br>Yet even che&#770;n does not hold the &ldquo;unmerited&rdquo; implication, as it was the pre-Christ era where favour usually required merit by act or sacrifice. So, I&rsquo;ll skip the Old Testament in this book, only to keep this book from becoming too excessive and needlessly traversing another universal rabbit hole to what could include another hundred pages.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So here&rsquo;s a short expos&eacute; of other scriptures revealing more:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1Peter 5:5 &nbsp;&ldquo;In like manner, you young ones, be subject to elders, and all subjecting yourselves to one another; clothe yourselves with humble-mindedness, because God resists the proud, but He gives grace to the humble;&rdquo; So, an important fact first, grace comes to the humble.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, I&rsquo;ll present a few more in Biblical order (mostly) again most section and paragraph references will be skiped here due to scripture references being suitable:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Act_11:23 &nbsp;who, having come, and having seen the grace of God, was glad, and was exhorting all with purpose of heart to cleave to the LORD, - It is more than received, it is seen (a comprehension factor)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Act_13:43 &nbsp;and the synagogue having been dismissed, many of the Jews and of the devout proselytes followed Paul and Barnabas, who, speaking to them, were persuading them to remain in the grace of God. - To remain in grace brings the conclusion that we can also lose it (Unlike &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Act_18:27 &nbsp;and he resolving to go through into Achaia, the brothers wrote to the disciples, having exhorted them to receive him, who having come, helped them much who have believed through grace, - It will deliver belief, can &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; bring belief. Much like a law is written but police bring it&rsquo;s affects (the law itself can do nothing, only the enforcers).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Act_20:32 &nbsp;and now, I commend you, brothers, to God, and to the word of His grace, that is able to build up, and to give you an inheritance among all those sanctified. - Grace builds you up, and by Strongs&#39; or Thayer&#39;s definitions, that is true, but &nbsp;&ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; can&rsquo;t build.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom_1:7 &nbsp;to all who are in Rome, beloved of God, called holy ones: Grace to you and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ! If they are beloved and holy ones, they already have &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, can you wish something to a person who has it? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">14.3 Grace in motion</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Here, before I go on, it was commonly wished upon people as it is the most desirable thing to have. Please treat it with the same respect and desire it, not merely for your salvation&#39;s sake in which it embodies, but for the many things it delivers far beyond salvation as &nbsp;&ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom_5:17 &nbsp;for if by the offence of the one death reigned through the one, much more those who are receiving the abundance of grace and of the free gift of righteousness, in life will reign through the one; Jesus Christ. - You can have an abundance of grace, which then means you can have meagre grace. Seek a lot of it, not just a little. Here it also separates &ldquo;the free gift&rdquo;, differentiating with &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; again.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom_11:5 &nbsp;So then also in the present time there has been a remnant according to the divine selection of grace; - There is a selective part of grace, where &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; is self-evidently open to all.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom_12:3 &nbsp;For I say, through the grace that was given to me, to everyone who is among you, not to think above what it ought to think; but to think so as to think wisely, as to each God dealt a measure of faith. - Here grace is directing his words. It certainly is an influence.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom_12:6 &nbsp;And having gifts, different according to the grace that was given to us: whether prophecy, according to the proportion of faith; - So grace presents gifts differently to people. Grace brings those spiritual gifts of healing, administration, prophecy, interpretation, helps and others.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom 15:15 &nbsp;However, on some points I have written to you rather boldly, both as a reminder to you and because of the grace given me by God - God gives grace that makes a person act or talk in a particular way, which can vary. It must then be acting upon his mind through his soul to tell him what to say and how to say it. An influence, not a pardon.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2Co_1:12 &nbsp;For our glorying is this: the testimony of our conscience, that in simplicity and sincerity of God, not in fleshly wisdom, but in the grace of God, we conducted ourselves in the world, and more abundantly toward you; - This verse is on conscience, wisdom and conduct shows grace as God&#39;s production of those things, far more than forgiveness but a causeation.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2Co_4:15 &nbsp;for all things are because of you, that the grace having been multiplied, because of the thanksgiving of the more, may abound to the glory of God; - Again, like abundance, here it can be multiplied. Then there must be great value in seeking to have more of it. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2Co_8:7 &nbsp;but even as in everything you abound, in faith, and word, and knowledge, and all diligence, and in your love to us, that also in this grace you may abound; - Like the other attributes here, seek to abound in it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Jhn_1:16 &nbsp;And we all received out of His fullness, and grace for grace; - Grace for grace? The exact implication here eludes me. Maybe, just maybe, the implication could be something like two various aspects of charis, and Godly influence for Godly knowledge? For God to influence us (charis) for the acquisition of Godly knowledge (charis). I certainly do not know, and my presumption probably falls far short of the intended meaning. Though the active component comes out here grace here seems to be doing something for grace.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Gal_1:6 &nbsp;I wonder that you are so quickly removed from Him who called you in the grace of Christ to another good news - &ldquo;Unmerited favour&rdquo; would require a different word than in, we can&rsquo;t be called &ldquo;in&rdquo; it, maybe from it? But another point here is if we can turn &ldquo;to another good news&rdquo;, it must certainly have a gospel-like aspect to it, &ldquo;A mini gospel in itself&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Gal_2:21 &nbsp;I do not make the grace of God void, for if righteousness is through law&mdash;then Christ died in vain. - You can make it void! You simply can&rsquo;t void &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;. You can refuse to accept &nbsp;&ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; but not void it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Gal_5:4 &nbsp;you were voided from the Christ, you who are declared righteous in law; you fell away from grace; - &nbsp;&ldquo;Unmerited favour&rdquo; is always there to be taken, it is as abundant as atoms. Try to fall from atoms; you just fall to where there are other atoms. You can fall from the powerful, knowledgeable influence of God. You can step away from the connection with him that brings manifold change.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Eph_3:2 &nbsp;if, indeed, you heard of the dispensation of the grace of God that was given to me in regard to you, - Here it is something given to Paul regarding the Ephesian Church, could this scripture not be more blatant? Charis brought him insight. God&#39;s influence that changes us and teaches us.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Eph_4:7 &nbsp;and to each one of you was given grace, according to the measure of the gift of Christ, - Another showing variation as to how much we have. I&rsquo;m confident in the charis he gives me, that it has some keys, of which the major keys are Repentance (of both kinds), Humility and an earnest desire (more so a hunger) to advance (grow) in God; not to a more important position, but to a deeper relationship and knowledge.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Col_1:6 &nbsp;which has come to you, as also in all the world, and is bearing fruit, as also in you, from the day in which you heard, and knew the grace of God in truth, - Its knowledge factor is reinforced here.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Col_4:6 &nbsp;your word always being seasoned with salt in grace, to know how it is necessary for you to answer each one. - By grace, we know how to speak on God&#39;s behalf, and salt makes things more tasty and therefore desirable. So use it to express God in a desirable way. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2Ti_2:1 &nbsp;You, therefore, my child, be strong in the grace that is in Christ Jesus, - it, unlike unmerited favour, is not merely received; we are to be strong in it, note &ldquo;in it&rdquo;, not because of it. Have it as a strong ability in your life.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Heb_2:9 &nbsp;and we see Him who was made a little less than messengers; Jesus, because of the suffering of death, having been crowned with glory and honour, that by the grace of God He might taste of death for everyone. This one blows &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; out of the water, as &nbsp;&ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; can&rsquo;t send him to his death, but knowledge of what God wants certainly can.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Heb_4:16 &nbsp;we may come near, then, with freedom, to the throne of grace, that we may receive kindness, and find grace, for seasonable help. - Then it helps in different ways depending on the season (and think of herbs and food seasons as there are many, rather than just four times of year). Pepper may help one meal, where curry may help another and salt another again.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Heb 12:14 &nbsp;Pursue peace with everyone, as well as holiness, without which no one will see the Lord. - Ka-Boom, is there anything unholy in your life? (That&rsquo;s just the lead-up scripture to the one containing grace)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Heb 12:15 &nbsp;See to it that no one fails to obtain the grace of God and that no bitter root grows up and causes you trouble, or many of you will become defiled. - So be peaceable, holy, and then obtain grace. Of course, 1/ repent, 2/ commit to that holiness, and 3/ grace will then flow. As mentioned its a constant learning and growing upward spiral.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Heb_13:9 &nbsp;Do not be carried away with strange and manifold teachings, for it is good that by grace the heart is confirmed, not with meats, in which they who were occupied were not profited; - Ignor the nonscriptural (more so antiscriptural) various teachings, and if you have a strong foundation in the word, he will confirm good teaching as such.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1Pe_1:13 &nbsp;For this reason, having girded up the loins of your mind, being sober, hope perfectly on the grace that is being brought to you in the revelation of Jesus Christ, - once you have gained a good Biblical grounding, it is grace that brings further revelation; aligned with the word.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1Pe_4:10 &nbsp;each one, according as he received a gift, ministering it to one another, as good stewards of the manifold grace of God; - &nbsp;manifold meaning a single source of many things or many things into a single thing, here we discover there are many results or illuminations from grace.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2Pe_3:18 &nbsp;and increase in grace, and in the knowledge of our Lord and Saviour Jesus Christ; to Him is the glory both now, and to the day of the age! Amen. - Increase in it, seek more of that productive connection with God</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll jump back to its first mention in the New Testament, then the last few.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Luk_2:40 &nbsp;and the Child grew and was strengthened in spirit, being filled with wisdom, and the grace of God was on Him. Yeshua didn&rsquo;t have all wisdom, etc. at birth, it grew, and he was not grace, nor would his action of sacrifice bring it, as it was already &ldquo;on him&rdquo;. He had a connection with the father from day one, yet he grew in wisdom from it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now the last 3 references:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Jude_1:4 &nbsp;for there came in certain men stealthily, having been written beforehand to this judgment long ago, impious, perverting the grace of our God to licentiousness, and denying our only Master and Lord, Jesus Christ. - Don&rsquo;t let it be made impure by impious teaching</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rev_1:4 &nbsp;John, to the seven assemblies that are in Asia: Grace to you, and peace, from Him who is, and who was, and who is coming, and from the Seven Spirits that are before His throne, - right to the end, the call for those who&rsquo;d made commitments to receive or grow in grace is emphasised.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rev_22:21 &nbsp;The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all. Amen. - The last few words of the Bible beg you to gain it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It is the very connection to God in your life; That which gives you awareness, helps you decide in the initial commitment, leads you from the milk to the meat of the word, brings knowledge, and passion for God and the world, producing fruit and insight.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>The Bible is the car, the attitude of your heart is the fuel, and Charis is the key. That 1/ gets you into the car 2/ starts the motor, but 3/also engages the Sat-nav, which helps you find where to go. <br><br></span><span class="c7">14.4 {name needed}</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Grace is not just something we have, but also a state to be in, a way to act, a lifestyle and as Colossians 4:5,6 tells us it is how to speak. So let&#39;s break them down:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Col 4:5 &nbsp;Behave wisely toward outsiders, making the best use of your time. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Col 4:6 &nbsp;Let your speech always be gracious, seasoned with salt, so that you may know how you ought to answer everyone.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">These verses are to the entire church at Colossae, not just ministers and directly talk of the lost, yet keeping them in mind when talking with Christians is of implied value too. So the best use of your time is to behave wisely toward outsiders, which is continued in the next verse, explaining how to be wise toward them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let your speech always be gracious, seasoned with salt. Grace, as we know, is charis; it is God working in you and through you (Paul&#39;s verses). So if your speech is gracious, you are speaking of God and Godly things. Now, it seems people miss these verses, but even if they don&rsquo;t, they certainly miss &ldquo;always&rdquo;. Wow, we are to turn every conversation to a divine focus. Ouch, I fall short there; even knowing this and earnestly desiring to do so, it is very hard. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">For many roles we have in the modern world, it is simply not suitable. Can you imagine an air traffic controller, who hears &ldquo;Pan, pan, pan&rdquo;, which is the international airline phrase for &ldquo;mayday&rdquo;, &ldquo;S.O.S.&rdquo; or &ldquo;Serious emergency&rdquo;, reply with &ldquo;What is your emergency, and have you heard about God&#39;s salvation?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, of course, we can&rsquo;t bring God into every conversation, though, do we bring God into every non-professional conversation? If an air traffic controller is on a break, can he not discuss God with his co-workers rather than what was on TV last night?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Here&rsquo;s where the implication overflows to Christian conversation. If Colossians 4:6 tells us that our speech should &ldquo;always&rdquo; be gracious, could we and should we then include conversations with Christians? Absolutely. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It finishes with &ldquo;&hellip;so that you may know how you ought to answer everyone.&rdquo; Again, an implication that should be conversations with Christians too, yet don&rsquo;t forget it has specified &ldquo;outsiders&rdquo;. So we are to deliver this message to &ldquo;everyone&rdquo; and note here, it says &ldquo;answer&rdquo;. If we are truly acting like Christians, giving and loving everyone. Prefering others before ourselves. It is very noticeable, they will ask of your nature in it&rsquo;s Godliness; even if they don&rsquo;t recognise it as Godliness, they will still ask &ldquo;What&rsquo;s different about you?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Here is then the point of the verses. When we act Godly, &ldquo;Behave wisely&rdquo;, especially by having gracious speech (Godly discussions), people will want to know more about you and God in you, so then ask you about it. If people are not noticing God in you, are you doing Godly things and discussing God at every chance? There is an evident factor as it&rsquo;s &ldquo;mirrored in the life&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Lastly, on these verses &ldquo;seasoned with salt&rdquo;. Salt was the prime seasoning of the time, the easiest to get and most flavoursome. The inference here is that it made food more appealing, more attractive. It is a figurative way of saying, &quot;Be attractive in your speech&rdquo;. Make it more desirable. Sure, there&#39;s a hell, but the emphasis by this is that we first offer what appeals before we turn to scaring them out of hell, as the last resort.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">14.5 &nbsp;Don&rsquo;t miss it</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The average &ldquo;Christian&rdquo; misses the mark by way too much. I have asked many who profess Christianity many questions; some questions I ask of everyone. I am joyful when I find the rare one who gives appropriate answers, yet it serves to remind me of how little I know as well. Now it&rsquo;s not how much I may have learned compared to what they may have learned, as we learn at different rates, for one. The difference here is a desire to 1/ Know more 2/Build that relationship with God, and 3/ Share God with the world. That&#39;s our 3-tier service. Too many don&rsquo;t seek to know more than a shallow understanding. Having an attitude of &ldquo;the scripture says this&hellip; next&rdquo; without the desire to even consider what it may mean or what that may require of them. Too many treat it impersonally or cherry-pick scripture to back what they believe staunchly, what they will not let go of, as they can find a scripture that somewhat supports their view. While denying the hundreds that categorically oppose it. XXX.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Most so-called Christians seem to hold on to their pride, ego, desires, needs, wants, ideas, their whatever is self, they refuse to lay the self down, to deny or disown the self (Matt 16:24?). It&rsquo;s just lip service. Unless we lay ourselves down humbly seeking God, that relationship will not be real. They may think they have a relationship, or say they have a relationship. But it will be like the third cousin twice removed that you speak to for a few minutes every ten or twenty years at a funeral or wedding, maybe. Sure, you know them, but how much do you really know them? Do you even know their favourite colour?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;m suggesting we stop assuming we know God from our ignorant stance of self-value. Limiting God to being somewhat like ourselves, as we have not dropped the self, the barrier between God and us. We think we are looking at God, but our lack of humility is merely looking in a mirror. God, then, to us is merely what we think </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">God is tainted by self-view. After all, if this hasn&rsquo;t clicked for you yet, do you have an urge to turn every conversation, even if a one-minute conversation with a person to God and Godly things? Simple&hellip; Charis will urge you to have such a focus on God that you become disinterested in anything else and just want to share God in every conversation. How many people do you really know like that?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Keep them in mind. The word Christian has come to mean any person who professes it. Any person who claims to be a Christian is considered to be one. Now, if I claim to be the leader of my country, that claim means nothing, as the claim doesn&rsquo;t make me the leader. Just as many people claim to be Christians, with no foundation, no real Christian attitude or actions. I will say here in my opinion, it is the absolute great majority. I&rsquo;ll use this as a figurative statement&hellip; &ldquo;Show me a Christian, and I&rsquo;ll show you 100 self-deceived so-called Christians.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, due to the extremely loose definition being someone who says they believe in Jesus (and that may be all). I now use a clarifying term, much like denominations separate beliefs, Catholic, Baptist, Pentecostal, etc. I will now call a person who has a good working knowledge of the Bible, especially the New Testament, can see its nature and builds a good relationship with God from that and seeks to be like Christ (including in expressing God in every communication), a Yeshuan. Now, this word is not a denomination nor a rank, it describes more an attitude of: &ldquo;God First In Everything&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Nothing else will seem to matter when you finally see and seek that level of relationship. I find myself disrupted by anything that is outside of God or sharing God with others in both word and deed. That&rsquo;s Tri-tier charisepignosis. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Titus 2:11-15 (ISV) Tit 2:11 &nbsp;For the grace of God has appeared, bringing salvation to all people. &nbsp;It trains us to renounce ungodly living and worldly passions so that we might live sensible, honest, and godly lives in the present age as we wait for the blessed hope and glorious appearance of our great God and Saviour, Jesus the Messiah. He gave himself for us to set us free from every wrong and to cleanse us so that we could be his special people who are enthusiastic about doing good deeds. These are the things you should teach. Encourage and refute with full authority. Do not let anyone look down on you. &nbsp;Simply, grace brings salvation, causes us to become pious (Godly) and actively express God in deed and word. Therefore, without that evident grace and change, you are not saved!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are legalists (keep the Law), Liberalists (act Godly), Hedonists (do what you want) and Theists (do as God says). Now, many people get these mixed up, thinking the traits of one is what another is. A legalist usually thinks they are doing as God says, when they are merely following the law and ignoring the higher demands of God. A liberalist often thinks doing religious things like going to church is being Godly, yet it is usually merely an act of pretension, as their hearts are often not in the right place. They may give to those they like, but avoid at all costs those they don&rsquo;t. I wonder if maybe they should give to those they don&rsquo;t like all the more, unless, of course, the issue is one of ungodliness, in which we are to cut ties. Then we have the hedonists who justify their desire to sin, saying we are no longer under the law and assume that freedom is freedom to sin. Which it certainly is not, it is freedom from the restrictive, menial aspects of the law; and those aspects alone, after all, love does not XXX. Finally, there are the rare few Theists who do not confuse the word or justify their lifestyle by their twist of it. They fully live a God-minded life, focusing on God rather than the law, liberty or hedonism. They seek to advance through the three tiers of charisepignosis: to first know the word, to then build a strong relationship with God and finally to expose God to the community through Godly action and communication. Not through keeping the Law, pretending to act godly or doing what they want.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">15</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.rrns6viv4ug7"><span class="c29 c26">Charis: The active hub &nbsp;(related Greek words)</span></h2><p class="c0 c35"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">15.1 Charis in the life (the word family)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Like English, or most other languages, Greek has foundation words creating family groups of words often having similar meanings or opposing meanings depending on suffixes and prefixes. Here I&rsquo;ll look at a few of the Greek Xap- &ldquo;Char-&rdquo; words to see the common characteristics and how their relationship reinforces Charis and its meaning, along with the nuances lost by the choice of it beyond the choice of similar words that would better convey concepts like &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This section most likely lacks, and I may not give the illumination it deserves, as I am in no way a linguist. I merely noticed there were other Greek words with similar meanings and or spelling. So, with my regular inquisitive nature delved into them a little. Not a great deal at all, as my (self-initiated) studies don&rsquo;t have the benefit of direction from teachers with trained minds&hellip; Alas, you will have to suffice with my poor effort. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The char family, and remember here the h is silent and c has more of a gritty k sound to it. My lack of depth in research was satisfied with only five words. Yes, my minimal study, this work may never leave the research phase, given that I limit it for the sake of production! With all my words, I&rsquo;m not likely to reveal more than a few facets of this highly faceted gem.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>I was satisfied in discovering </span><span>&chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega;</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>chair&#333;, &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940; chara, &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; charis,</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; charizomai </span><span>and </span><span>&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha;</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;charisma, as I knew of charisma, also with a silent h, and similarity in meaning and my intrigue expected more. I&rsquo;ll leave you to discover any others if you are intrigued.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Unlike a textbook would normally do, which (in my mind) would be to start with a core word group table. I&rsquo;ll add that last in the hope you read the prime meanings first and don&rsquo;t merely refer to it and think you know it from the few summary words within. Starting with a unifying relationship paragraph.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Grace (&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf;, </span><span>charis</span><span>) is God&#39;s transformation that brings joy (&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940;, </span><span>chara</span><span>) and is expressed through rejoicing (&chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega;, </span><span>chair&#333;</span><span>). It manifests as free gifts (&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha;, charisma) empowered by the Spirit (e.g., 1 Cor 12:4) and generous forgiveness (&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota;,</span><span>charizomai</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;e.g., Col 2:13 forgiving &quot;all our trespasses&quot;). </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>First, you may have noticed I used transformation for charis and generous forgiveness for </span><span>charizomai. Of course,</span><span>&nbsp;&ldquo;generous forgiveness&rdquo;</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;is closer to &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo; simply because charizomai is the Greek word here, which is by far more in line with that definition. It literally means &ldquo;pardon as an act of grace&rdquo;, and it not only carries the pardon aspect, but the grace aspect of it is not grace itself, but an action of grace. Grace is not the pardon, the unmerited favour, but that which supplies it. Don&rsquo;t assume they are then the same. If you are employed, your employer is not your wage, but your employer supplies your wage. Yes, I discovered the implication that it&rsquo;s the transformation process God is putting us through that supplies the pardon! It is in no way a pardon without transformation. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">15.2 Grace supplies pardon</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Is that different to what you have been taught? If so, has your previous source of education on grace delivered the easily researchable definitions as per Strong&#39;s and Thayer&#39;s work? When I cite them, I&rsquo;m citing the base for other minor supportive works that most likely used them for research anyway, like Vines. Have you even been taught this anyway? I found the need to write this, as I had not been taught these things and had to discover them myself, as mentioned, no minister seems to know them, not even some of the most reputable international ministers.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">We are just at the beginning of this section. I have as yet merely introduced these words.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>These five words manifest as </span><span>joy, gifts, and mercy with a focus on divine favour, yet even more, transcendence to a higher mental and far higher spiritual realm.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll attempt to keep this short and simple</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Charis is the central word, the hub which already contains an inner&#8209;to&#8209;outer movement: God&rsquo;s merciful kindness &rarr; inner transformation &rarr; outward Christian virtues. The other words are expansions. I&rsquo;ll treat it as the body that two legs grow down from.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Again: Charis (I&rsquo;ll simply use Thayer&#39;s </span><span>II</span><span class="c1">a description as all other meanings in some way fit into it - &ldquo;the merciful kindness by which God, exerting his holy influence upon souls, turns them to Christ, keeps, strengthens, increases them in Christian faith, knowledge, affection, and kindles them to the exercise of the Christian virtues.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You can break that into four stages:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Source: merciful kindness (God&rsquo;s gracious disposition toward sinners).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Turning: holy influence turning to Christ (conversion, new birth).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Keeping and growing: keeps, strengthens, increases (sanctification and ongoing enablement).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Outflow: kindles exercise of Christian virtues (visible fruit and ministry).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Everything else in the family shows one part of that process in focus.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">15.3 Joy born of grace</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; (chair&#333;) &ndash; the heart&rsquo;s response of joy</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; = to rejoice, be glad, &ldquo;to be calmly happy or well&#8209;off,&rdquo; also used as a greeting and even more as a salutation.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It is what happens in the affections when &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; is received: God&rsquo;s merciful kindness produces an inner rejoicing in what He has done in Christ.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Where &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; charis is the divine influence, &chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; chairo is the human response of gladness and praise flowing back to God (and often outward to others in love and generosity).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So: &ldquo;keeps, strengthens, increases them in &hellip; affection&rdquo; &rarr; that affection shows itself as &chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega;, initial rejoicing in God and salvation.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let&rsquo;s think of that like the left knee</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940; (chara) &ndash; the settled state of grace&#8209;joy</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940; = cheerfulness, calm delight; exceeding joy, gladness; the long-term contentment from God and from auspicious events.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If &chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; (chair&#333;) is the act, &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940; (chara) is the state: a Spirit&#8209;given, grace&#8209;rooted joy that abides even in suffering.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This corresponds to the continued result of &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; charis &ldquo;keeping, strengthening, increasing&rdquo; believers; the more grace works, the more joy becomes settled character rather than occasional feeling.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So: &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940; (chara) is the emotional atmosphere of a life under grace. Which is derived from the word &chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; (chair&#333;) &nbsp;and comes after it in time, so it&rsquo;s like the left foot.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; (charizomai) &ndash; grace as forgiving and giving action</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; = &ldquo;to grant as a favour; to bestow freely; to forgive, to show oneself gracious and kind.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; (charizomai) to pardon, means unmerited favour more than any of these. As &chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; (chair&#333;) comes from Charis, so think of it like the right Knee</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Then from &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; (charizomai) comes the word &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha; (charisma) &ndash; grace, becoming concrete gifts.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha; = &ldquo;a gift of grace; a favour received without merit; in Paul, especially spiritual endowments that serve the church.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This is the gift that comes because of the unmerited favour, not the unmerited favour itself</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This is &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; charis objectified and specialised: grace taking particular forms (teaching, helps, prophecy, giving, etc.). You can see the origin of the modern concept of charisma.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It sits especially in the last section of Thayer&rsquo;s line: &ldquo;kindles them to the exercise of the Christian virtues.&rdquo; God not only kindles virtues; He furnishes specific enablements to build up others.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So: &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha; (charisma) is where the &ldquo;good of God within&rdquo; becomes functional&mdash;specific capacities by which grace flows out to the body and the world. Like the right foot.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This verb is &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; in motion: God &ldquo;freely gives&rdquo; His Son (Romans 8:32), &ldquo;freely forgives&rdquo; trespasses (Colossians 2:13).</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#8203;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In believers, it is the imitation of that divine pattern: we &ldquo;freely forgive&rdquo; one another as God in Christ forgave us (Ephesians 4:32).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Here you are at the final step of Thayer&rsquo;s sentence: the virtues that grace kindles are most clearly seen in costly, undeserved forgiveness and generous giving, i.e., &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; (charizomai) lived out.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A simple way to visualise it</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you sketch it as a flow:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf; (charis) &ndash; God&rsquo;s merciful kindness and holy influence (source and inner work).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&rarr; produces &chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega; (chair&#333;) &ndash; acts of rejoicing and joyful obedience. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&rarr; becoming &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940; (chara) &ndash; a stable joy.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&rarr; and acts as &chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota; (charizomai) &ndash; gracious, forgiving, generous deeds toward others.</span><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 506.00px; height: 626.94px;"><img alt="" src="images/image1.jpg" style="width: 506.00px; height: 626.94px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&rarr; which takes form as &chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha; (charisma) &ndash; grace&#8209;gifts for service.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><ul class="c45 lst-kix_1awsl75ttfwo-0 start"><li class="c40 c2 li-bullet-0"><span>It is </span><span class="c42">God</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;acting (&ldquo;merciful kindness&hellip;holy influence&rdquo;).</span></li><li class="c2 c40 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">It is saving (&ldquo;turns them to Christ&rdquo;).</span></li><li class="c40 c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">It is ongoing (&ldquo;keeps, strengthens, increases&hellip;&rdquo;).</span></li><li class="c40 c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">It is practically fruitful (&ldquo;kindles&hellip;exercise of the Christian virtues&rdquo;).</span></li></ul><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c21" id="h.lvj2bkkwdjj"><span class="c7">Core Word Group Table</span></h2><table class="c78"><tr class="c89"><td class="c85" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c17">Strong&#39;s </span></p></td><td class="c95" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c17">Greek Lemma</span></p></td><td class="c84" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c17">Transliteration</span></p></td><td class="c94" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c17">Strong&#39;s Key Meaning</span></p></td><td class="c41" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c17">Thayer&#39;s Key Meaning</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c80"><td class="c67" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">G5463</span></p></td><td class="c47" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&#943;&rho;&omega;</span></p></td><td class="c34" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">chair&#333;</span></p></td><td class="c61" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">To be cheerful, calmly happy; rejoice, greet </span></p></td><td class="c73" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">To rejoice, be glad; thrive; hail (salutation) &#8203;</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c80"><td class="c67" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">G5479</span></p></td><td class="c47" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#940;</span></p></td><td class="c34" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">chara</span></p></td><td class="c61" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">Cheerfulness, calm delight; gladness, joy &#8203;</span></p></td><td class="c73" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">Joy, gladness (vs. sorrow); cause of joy &#8203;</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c38"><td class="c67" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">G5485</span></p></td><td class="c47" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigmaf;</span></p></td><td class="c34" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">charis</span></p></td><td class="c61" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">Graciousness; divine influence on heart/life; grace, thanks </span></p></td><td class="c73" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">That which affords joy/charm; God&#39;s merciful kindness turning souls to Christ </span></p></td></tr><tr class="c80"><td class="c67" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">G5486</span></p></td><td class="c47" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">&chi;&#940;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&mu;&alpha;</span></p></td><td class="c34" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">charisma</span></p></td><td class="c61" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">Gift of grace; spiritual endowment &#8203;</span></p></td><td class="c73" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">Free gift/favour received without merit; divine grace-gift &#8203;</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c80"><td class="c67" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">G5483</span></p></td><td class="c47" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">&chi;&alpha;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota;</span></p></td><td class="c34" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">charizomai</span></p></td><td class="c61" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">To show grace/favour; forgive, give freely &#8203;</span></p></td><td class="c73" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c24"><span class="c1">Bestow favour freely; pardon as an act of grace &#8203;</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c71 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c71"><span class="c1">These five lemmas form the heart of the family, all deriving from the Proto-Indo-European root for &quot;gleam&quot; or &quot;delight,&quot; emphasising God&#39;s beauty and goodness flowing (apparently through us) outward. </span></p><p class="c71"><span class="c1">16</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.5ne8caadtcgx"><span>{</span><span>Aspects/facets - love, joy etc? (purpose, direction, discernment, clarity) or </span><span class="c8">Grace at work</span><span>?</span><span class="c29 c26">}</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>16.1 Grace deeper than relief</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Unmerited favour is an aspect of charis, it is the first aspect, the first cut (or facet) that was made in the gem. It begins with unmerited favour for without it there is no connection or relationship with God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Grace supersedes the law, not merely the law but so much more to worship 7-days a week not &nbsp;merely 1 </span></p><p class="c0 c35"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">Act_2:46 And they, continuing daily with one accord in the temple, and breaking bread from house to house, did eat their meat with gladness and singleness of heart,</span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">Act_5:42 And daily in the temple, and in every house, they ceased not to teach and preach Jesus Christ.</span></p><p class="c0 c35"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">but to not let that cause a stumble Rom 14:5-10 20-23, as it recognises some take hold of it with ease, and others struggle to even see it, let alone take hold of it.</span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">Seeking - it seeks you, shows God to you then changes you by turning you to Christ, and becoming more Christlike</span></p><p class="c0 c35"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">It will keep you from falling away, but more, it will keep you satisfied in God.</span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span>It will strengthen you in both faith (your knowledge) and faithfulness (your walk). </span><span>It here also</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;includes epignosis. I combine those words to know God horizontally (the word - epignosis) and vertically (relationship - charis), to have charisepignosis a relationship founded in the word.</span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">It will cause Growth in your faith; being the heart-felt realisation of his reality, as well as in knowledge of him, Christianity and discernment and passion for him, the lost and the church. Also growth in those Christian virtues, the love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, patience, self-control, faith, hope, charity, prudence and fairness.</span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">It also gives Purpose, Direction, Revelation and clarity and &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gifts of the Spirit; service, exhortation, giving, leading, mercy, word of wisdom, word of knowledge, faith, gifts of healing, working of miracles, prophecy, discerning of spirits, tongues, and interpretation of tongues.</span></p><p class="c2 c35"><span class="c1">Beyond those, it compels you to walk away from sin, towards Godliness, by God&#39;s strength, not yours.</span></p><p class="c71 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>17</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.ggtm8d2kh84r"><span>Grace that grows</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">17.1 The wanderer</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The wanderer, as I will call him, is an extra-denominational friend of mine who seeks anonymity. An outdoors person who doesn&rsquo;t go to church and believes most people should get out of churches. So when I say extra-denominational, he is a Christian who is beyond the milk being taught in churches and would rather study the Bible and worship outside of organised denominational churches. His relationship with and understanding of God is also beyond the average.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>I&rsquo;ll mention a few things that have come up in our discussions, maybe a few off-subject inspirations and certainly his position in regard to charis. &nbsp;Some of these statements are derived from him, and some are what I said, while others are expanded for your clarity. He is a Christian who doesn&rsquo;t attend Church; the Bible strongly emphasises we do not neglect fellowship. Yet in the modern world, he is not out of place. He earnestly seeks fellowship with</span><span class="c44">&nbsp;sincere,</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class="c44">learned </span><span class="c1">Christians. He saw at least one of my messages and presumed that I fit the bill, which is why he reached out to me. Yet I am merely a novice (at least not a neophyte; with no knowledge).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Sure, I&rsquo;m writing this book as this seems to be knowledge I can&rsquo;t find anywhere; thus, writing it is the </span><span class="c44">foregone conclusion.</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;Though that doesn&rsquo;t make me extraordinary, merely observant enough to realise a lack, and like those messages he saw, I wrote out of inexperienced, simple revelation. I simply attempt to pen what God has revealed to me, and not me alone as it&rsquo;s straight out of the Bible. Sadly, though, we lack teachers for this important subject.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, we talk on the phone every Week. However, (and don&rsquo;t assume here before you read it all), he considers himself (and many Christians) beyond church. I understand when he insinuates this. He is certainly beyond the milk of the word and somewhat active evangelistically. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">His issue is founded on two things: the pastors never seem to get beyond the milk&hellip; I must agree. I find it rare for anyone to preach to a level that I&rsquo;d call puree soup, let alone meat. This is also why I find myself typing these words. No one teaches this, and when you look at how fundamental and foundational this is, the mind boggles as to why not. Is it too deep? Certainly not, again it&rsquo;s fundamental. Is it because those pastors and ministers themselves don&rsquo;t know this? Well, as reluctant as I am to say it&hellip; Yes! We are talking about the basics here; maybe not simple things to understand, but those that are so fundamental that they have a prime need of clear explanation. This is the Foundation of Christianity itself. Do you believe in Zischkalee? OK I just made that word up, it has no meaning, my point being we need to know the meaning of what we believe in! What we follow. How can you undertake a discipline without knowing what it is, what it leads to?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Pastors and ministers rarely go beyond the milk, as they either don&rsquo;t know more themselves, which is dangerous but true in some cases. Or they have an apprehension about doing so. Well, yes, they can see that if they &ldquo;preach it like it is&rdquo;, many will leave to seek a soft, accepting, milk-giving church. Afraid of losing their congregation. They pander to the majority, those who want to keep living an average life and not look at the reality of what God seeks from them. Why? The more people in your church, the more ears to hear at least some message of God&hellip; Yet that can&rsquo;t be the reason. That&rsquo;s like never teaching your apprentices beyond first-year skills. So why would you do that? If I kept as many apprentices as I could at first year level, I&rsquo;d be getting an extremely low-paid workforce&hellip; Hang on, could there be a financial reason? Maybe, the more bodies in pews, the more tithes and donations&hellip; If your focus is on the money, then the message only needs to be desirable.. You would certainly avoid anything even slightly contentious, let alone demanding&hellip; The milk! There may be other reasons, and many Pastors/ministers aren&rsquo;t focused on money. Again, some don&rsquo;t know much more than they were taught.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But who can survive on the milk? Only those who don&rsquo;t want to grow! I understand this. We live in a world of consumer Christianity. Most people go to church to get a little milk to 1/ Get themselves through the week (a selfish focus, which is undesirable), or 2/ to show they have done their duty to God by going to church (also missing the understanding of what the Bible says). Why? Very few have a real relationship with God; very few are anything more than churchians (people who go to church to get to heaven, but that&#39;s not how it works).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">17.2 The evidence of change</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I believe the majority of Pastors in modern churches are in crisis control, desperately trying to maintain the status quo and hoping for some growth. Two things a farmer or gardener knows about growth that seem to be unknown to pastors. 1/ If it&rsquo;s all about consumption, there is no seed left for a new crop (one reason the church is generally in decline), and 2/ When you cut most plants, it produces more growth, not less! So, in losing the old and stale, the hard and unteachable, those who won&rsquo;t be teachable, the loss is minimal, not only minimal but valuable, as now you sponsor growth.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let&#39;s look at what happens. They preach some hard, meaty truths that consumer Christians don&rsquo;t want to hear, seeking one of two options: those consumer Christians either seek to change or seek to leave. Those who change, great! Those who leave, fine, no problem, in fact, it&rsquo;s good that you have less unanointed influence on those who now seek Godliness and dual growth (personal and numerical). So half the church has left, but the other half only want to bring new people in to hear things that aren&rsquo;t being taught elsewhere. There will be a greater propensity to growth. You are merely doing what the Bible says anyway.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I like talking with the wanderer, as he certainly understands the point just made. I&rsquo;d presume he understands many Godly things more than many pastors/ministers. I find some people have a desire to teach without any desire to learn; they seem to teach from their ignorance. A shameful spread of that same ignorance. We often discuss things like this.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, even more than I, he sees churches as nurseries where the leadership seeks to keep them as babies.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I know others who also don&rsquo;t attend physical churches, but fellowship to some degree online. There are probably multiple reasons for this new trend. Though to me it seems to lack a purpose of the church, which is personal interaction for the growth of the members. Many physical churches lack this anyway, and the larger the church, the less personal connection and therefore the lack of corrective ability, as well as personal encouragement and more.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">One of the things the wanderer mentioned to me was a quote from a minister long ago, which went something like this. A boat is in the Ocean, but you don&rsquo;t want the ocean in the boat; The church is in the world, but you don&rsquo;t want the world in the church. A valid quote. Now don&rsquo;t think they need to come to church to get saved; as you would be missing the point in many ways 1/ you are supposed to go out to express God to them lead them to Christ then invite them and 2/ The Bible says to remove worldly people from associating with the church (give them a couple of chances to change first) 3/ If that&rsquo;s not happening then the Bible is either being misunderstood or you have not even read it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What&rsquo;s your church like? A bunch of people who come very early to discuss God, Godliness and encourage each other to dual growth, then get very excited in every phase of the service, and many don&rsquo;t want to leave at the end but hang around mindful of God and blessing each other, yet some rush off to&hellip; well, not play golf, but to find people to express God to?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Are the messages from your leaders (and experienced members of the congregation, hopefully), merely milk or mind-blowing, meaty revelations, strongly founded on the Bible.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are many things a vast number of churches could improve on. Yet they&rsquo;d need to let go of those fears and those who don&rsquo;t know God. They&rsquo;d need to trust God, and I doubt those who barely know God themselves, who can&rsquo;t teach that meat as they are only on the milk themselves, can step up to the mark. They&rsquo;d have to ask God to push the &ldquo;ME&rdquo; out of their hearts and fill it with God</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The wanderer keeps talking to me of the need for people to leave the church, with the implication that they would then go beyond the milk and start evangelising, etc. (though he never says that exactly, and I find it hard to interrupt). I see it differently; It&rsquo;s time to stand up and take action to discover what God really wants (it&rsquo;s blatantly obvious in the Bible&hellip; but who reads and understands the Bible? Very few), to become that person, to then discover your call, train in it, launch it and support others doing likewise.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But to remain in Churches so you have the opportunity to encourage others to reach and launch their call in a godly fashion. The wanderer suggests that because the leaders only preach milk and ignore or maybe even fight anyone who seeks more, to leave to pursue that meat alone. There is a danger in that if you have not gone far beyond the milk in the first place... If you are not strong in your relationship with and knowledge of God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">We need churches to grow, yet I see his issue; growth isn&rsquo;t really happening in many of them. But is leaving the answer? No, I think not. I think it is better to convince the leadership of the need for the people to understand their relationship with God properly, rather than just milk. Creating in them an earnest desire to grow personally and bring others to God. If the leadership can&rsquo;t see this, then they have a problem; and yes, many do. So what then?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Either keep moving on till you find a Church that has got those basics right or God willing, create one! I have met ministers in my life who had their hearts in the right place, they simply didn&rsquo;t know much of the &ldquo;how&rdquo; to do things or didn&rsquo;t know the WOW factor, mind-blowing, deep things of God, the meat. So growth in their churches was minimal&hellip; But it was constant! Any minister I&rsquo;d ever met who had the basics right presided over a growing church. Yet some of them still didn&rsquo;t have it right; they still let sin in (more so in their own lives than in the church), and what had become a relatively large church crashed.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;d like to see a theocratic church, and maybe it will become more theocratic when people learn these old forgotten things. They burst out of the Bible everywhere, yet due to poor translations or the like, they are overlooked. I mean, for example, the Greek word duolos means slave, yet is translated extremely softly into servant. I won&rsquo;t go into that now. I could write another book on it; though it really makes a highly valid difference.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I have some fellowship with the wanderer, the closest person I have to a like-minded friend. It reminds me of a circus, many who see a tent alone, and think they know all about circuses. Yet, some enter and look at the clowns alone and think they know it all, some look beyond the clowns and also see the acrobats, lion tamers, musicians and other sideshows. So like him, they have a good understanding of our figurative circus. Yet is there more? Yes. We miss things that make it wonderful. The audience builds an atmosphere, and all the work outside the tent, that keeps it running. These are crucial things in a circus, yet my point is that crucial things are all too often overlooked.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sure, there are even a few minor aspects I don&rsquo;t mention in circuses, as this book will also lack in description. All I&rsquo;m saying here is that even the best of us will miss some of the larger factors, let alone the small.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Another point along that line is: Your duty isn&#39;t in church; it is in the community, to be the selfless living sacrifice, having an earnest, prayerful mindset and stepping up to other ways to position yourself, like reading the word, and having empowering fellowship, etc.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Some points of his are, Pride will stop everything, especially you, from receiving, including from God. &nbsp;We are victorious in Christ, therefore allowing yourself to be a victim is non-Christian. When you have faith in God, He has faith in you. And righteousness requires faith, and faith needs to be tested to be proven.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Some other thoughts that came to my mind in discussion with him were: Assess your beliefs for rationality because you will believe in what you want to believe in, including lies.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&#39;s getting easier to lie and create fakery as AI easily creates your concepts without the requirement for it to support its results with truth. Therefore, it is also becoming harder to believe even what we see.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1 c46">18</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.pm3me43cnt1"><span>Grace is not license</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">18.1 What to do with it - empowerment, deep relationship, find call</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There will be many who do nothing due to these revelations, many will see no need to change, others may see it as inferior, that they already know far more than a simple dissertation. In the parable, the sower sowed multiple types of ground, yet the seed grew to fruition in only one. Be that yielding ground. So, for those willing, what to do with it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">(expand?)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1 c91">Let it - obsess you, direct and teach you, drive you to God, empower you, find your call, speak to you, ??? {expand on each}</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Make it a routine! How much do you want, Charis? No, let&#39;s try again. How much do you REALLY want, Charis? Think for a moment, then read on. What is the very thing that saves us worth? How much of your life will you give to it? Again, stop, contemplate deeply. The very thing that saves you is worth what? How much time? 100% Surely not, simply because I can&rsquo;t think of anyone who can do anything and never take a break, the sabbath came as man needed a break at least one day a week. If you thought or said 100% that simply isn&rsquo;t practical, as there will be times you will be thinking about something other than God or Godly things. So let&#39;s grant the value of a sabbath 1/7 about 15% out&hellip; 85%? That would be wonderful, yet unlikely.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;d like to say here in life it&#39;s better to shoot for a low target that stretches yourself a little and keep expanding that than shoot for a very hard target off the bat. So, for example, if you can easily jump 6 feet but 7 is getting a little difficult, then try for 7 regularly, then 8 and so on, rather than try for 12 straight away. Try something a little difficult and keep increasing the mark, as that is the way professionals expand their skills. Novices who try to reach difficult goals up front often don&rsquo;t do so and give up from failure rather than be encouraged by a little success.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Also, it&rsquo;s so much easier to expand a routine than totally upturn your life in the first place. You would be likely to break the intended routine, and &ldquo;Broken routines are usually replaced by new routines or frivolity&rdquo;. So let&#39;s look at something simple and work up from there. How about committing less than an hour a day to start? For some people, an hour is not much, for others, that&rsquo;s a lot. Less than an hour!, How much less? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">OK, that depends. Are you working 80 hours a week and have a family to attend to for the rest of the time? Some people do, for anyone like that. Let&rsquo;s just start with 15 minutes, and for you, it&rsquo;s a lot, 2-5 minutes of prayer and 10 minutes of reading the Bible daily. Then seek God as to how you can work a little less and give a little more time to him. If you have no need to do anything, for example, you&rsquo;re retired and can do whatever you like. An hour a day is nothing for you; however, an hour a day, even when you have nothing to do, can bring tedium. So consider a half hour to start, and the difference is you can work up to an hour a day or more rather quickly. Yet at your own (slightly uncomfortable) pace. Never be so comfortable that it&rsquo;s meaning less, nor pressure yourself enough to even contemplate giving up. It&rsquo;s like learning to run a marathon, if you&rsquo;re not a runner, don&rsquo;t try to run 26 miles on day one!, A quarter mile working up to a mile by the end of the week, and don&rsquo;t forget a couple of break days, yet keep adding miles week by week till one day you are confident you can enter a marathon and finish it. My point is never do anything in such a way that it&rsquo;s not at least a little challenging, nor where the challenge is so great you are likely to give up.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Charis is for you, but never forget it&rsquo;s far more; it by nature needs to flow from you to others as well. As we must deny ourselves XXX, and reach out xxx like unhiden lights xxx &nbsp;to reach the lost Mat 28:19,20</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Mat 12:30 &nbsp;He who is not with Me is against Me, and he who is not gathering with Me, scatters. There is a little implication here, yet I believe it is self-evident. The first half is fairly obvious. We must stand with him, yet the second gathering? Scattering? OK, there is a little to read into this, yet it jumps out at you. He spoke of crops and harvest often; &ldquo;gather&rdquo; is a term for harvesting. Most, if not all, of his references to harvesting were evangelism, so he is talking about the need to evangelise, and the implication is that he did.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What did he do? Every conversation he had seemed to lead to God or Godliness (every recorded one at least). Do we do that? Ouch. Yes, that makes me cringe with all the opportunities I never took. After all, look at just one case. The woman at the well xxx xxx </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Do we talk to the people at the drinking fountain about God? Or how about other places we go to acquire water&hellip; The supermarket. When was the last time you saw someone at a checkout say to the checkout person, while we&rsquo;re doing nothing, can I tell you about something wonderful&hellip; God? Or turn to the person behind in the cue and do the same? I&rsquo;ve never seen it, yet did our master do that while acquiring water? Yes! It&rsquo;s time to not only give a little time to God, but share God with everyone we can Of course, you can&rsquo;t do that with every conversation, but we should any time we can.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you&#39;re not, he says you are against him. You can now say, &ldquo;Oh, but I&rsquo;m for him.&rdquo; Sure, but are you gathering or scattering? I now understand that not helping to gather is to scatter. How? For anyone who knows your status as a &ldquo;supposed Christian&rdquo; they judge you, and straight up, yes, they do judge you. Looking for any reason they can say you&rsquo;re not really a Christian, which then gives them reason to also not be a Christian, or that shows hypocrisy in you and therefore another excuse as to why they shouldn&rsquo;t believe what you say or in your God. To them by not doing what a Christian is called to do disqualifies you as a Christian; you therefore are diminishing the value of Christianity, disempowering it and, by consequence, scattering (diminishing the harvest).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">That also fails in description, but the point still stands strong, he said, and I&rsquo;ll combine those here to give a little more emphasis. If you are not for him and gathering, you are against him and scattering. MAKE YOUR CHOICE. It is so very important to Ether be a disciple (disciplined in doing what he did and said), or understand you are not and don&rsquo;t say you are, as that would simply then be a lie.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So back to doing it. Prayer, reading the Bible, studying, and evangelism make time for them and don&rsquo;t allow excuses. The hardest part is the evangelism. It&rsquo;s far easier to set an alarm and pray, read the word, study, but is there an alarm that can remind you to turn a conversation to God? Or to create a conversation with the intent to turn it to God? All I can suggest there is to set aside time each week to express God to others, especially if you are busy working, but use public transport to and from work, set an alarm to go off (on your phone, presuming you have one, if you&rsquo;re that busy working, you probably do). Set an alarm for about the time you&rsquo;d get to the train station or bus stop, maybe write a reminder on your ticket if you can or put a note in your wallet so every time you pay for things, you begin to think I&rsquo;ll express the love of God to the recipient of that money.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h1 class="c54" id="h.1vb1zkurksar"><span class="c51 c26">Part 2: Grace in your life</span></h1><p class="c2"><span class="c17 c57">19 Grace in practice</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c7"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">19.1 Walking it out</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c44">&nbsp;I believe those gifts that come through charis: </span><span class="c1">service, exhortation, giving, leading, mercy, word of wisdom, word of knowledge, faith, gifts of healing, working of miracles, prophecy, discerning of spirits, tongues, and interpretation of tongues are commonly duplicated by human effort. <br><br>These can be reproduced by us without God&#39;s influence. For example, can an atheist Judge show mercy? Of course. Can a Buddhist believe in their faith? Of course. In fact, I&rsquo;ll go as far as to say, more often than not, these things are a performance to present a Godly image by people who don&rsquo;t know God.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Grace comes from humility, XXX. Pray for God to fill your heart and push &ldquo;you&rdquo; out. Think on God and Godly things often, as constantly as you are able. Some people are in roles that demand their total concentration; let&rsquo;s put that to the side, but while travelling to and from work, can they think on God and Godly things? Of course.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Comprehension isn&#39;t discernment, yet they are linked; the greater your ability to comprehend, usually comes with a higher ability to discern also. Yet I find geniuses who simply can&rsquo;t discern a person&#39;s feelings, let alone things on a spiritual level. Both also often come more with education, yet the uneducated can be wiser than Doctors or Masters.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Grace is also like this, sure, it&rsquo;s more likely for those who develop it, but for some, it will just click like second nature, and others will never understand at all. It has been said that God doesn&rsquo;t call the able, he calls the available. The commitment, the change and how we position ourselves all relate here and knowing a little of them should help, but of course it&rsquo;s more about the decisions we make about ourselves. What are you, who are you, where do you want to be in God, learn what God says about you and learn to read between the lines (in a Godly attitude of doing so, of course).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.fznt05jmnkar"><span>19.2 </span><span>My anxiety in writing this</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I sincerely want you to gain a complete, useful understanding and the urge to step up for God, to improve your relationship with him, and to develop a desire to reach the lost for God.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">I would really love the perfect words that bring a full, complete and compelling knowledge to everyone. Alas, they simply don&rsquo;t exist. As history has shown, whatever message you give will be interpreted in different ways by different people. We interpret through the filters of our experience and personalities. Therefore, I expect this book will have both fans and detractors. Yet that says to me more about the contention in people rather than any potential contention in wording.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">I need to pause here and make something clear. I have not sat down and written this book from start to finish in one smooth flow, as if I had a complete, perfect message in my head. Most of what you&rsquo;re reading has come in pieces&mdash;nudges, insights, corrections&mdash;over time. I&rsquo;ve simply tried to capture those moments as faithfully as I can.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Please don&rsquo;t see any of this as &ldquo;my great revelation&rdquo;. I am not the source; I am the scribe. I feel more like a secretary taking dictation than an author crafting something clever. If there is anything of value in these pages, the credit is God&rsquo;s. If there is any confusion, clumsiness or error, that part is mine.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c26">Even now I am still learning as I type. I often feel that my words fall short of what I sense God is trying to show us. But perhaps that is exactly how it should be; it keeps me aware that I am small, that God is the one who gives insight, and that grace itself is far bigger than my ability to explain it.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">All I know is that I&rsquo;m compelled to write this from my insufficient knowledge, which causes some anxiety. I also have a sense this needs to be complete and available quickly, I sense time is running out in one way or another (I won&rsquo;t go into details there)... extra anxiety.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Yeshua said in Matthew 6:25&ndash;34:</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Because of this I say to you, do not be anxious for your life, what you may eat, and what you may drink, nor for your body, what you may put on. Is not life more than nourishment, and the body than clothing?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Look to the birds of the sky, for they do not sow, nor reap, nor gather into storehouses, and your heavenly Father nourishes them; are you not much better than they?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And who of you, being anxious, is able to add to his age one cubit?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And why are you anxious about clothing? Consider well the lilies of the field; how do they grow? They do not labour, nor do they spin;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And I say to you that not even Solomon in all his glory was clothed as one of these.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">And if the herb of the field, that today is, and tomorrow is cast into the furnace, God so clothes&mdash;not much more you, O you of little faith?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Therefore, you may not be anxious, saying, What may we eat? Or, what may we drink? Or, with what may we be clothed?</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">For the nations seek for all these, for your heavenly Father knows that you have need of all these;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">but seek first the Kingdom of God and His righteousness, and all these will be added to you.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Therefore, do not be anxious for tomorrow, for tomorrow will be anxious for its own things; sufficient for the day is the evil of it.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Yet some anxiety is not bad; sure, you can&rsquo;t add a day to your life through worry. But I </span><span>didn&rsquo;t say worry</span><span class="c1">. I do have a little concern which borders on worry, but more so, my anxiety is anticipation. A balancing act of anticipation&hellip; anxiety&hellip; good anxiety. Anxiety that pushes me toward good things, at least. It is the anxiety to &ldquo;seek first the Kingdom of God and His righteousness&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So I&rsquo;ll sum here what I hope the takeaways were.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;m anxious to express the importance of knowing about Charis (your salvation), building relationships with God, and getting Godly things right. I&rsquo;m anxious to express this in a way that at least the majority understand, while recognising the lack of knowledge I still have, and the growing awe I have about Charis (our salvation). I&rsquo;m also anxious to express that some things are quick and some take time, and that all our time could benefit God in some way, or at least not be distracted from God. Some anxiety isn&rsquo;t all bad, if it drives us to do good for others and God. Lastly, I&rsquo;m also anxious to express that Charis itself is writing this, by the leading of God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, please understand, no matter what Godly thing I or anyone may seek to educate you in&hellip; we merely supply the words and Charis does the teaching. So, I&rsquo;m anxious to glorify God by this and have you do the same. Someone wrote these words for you to realise the need for growth inward and outward; in that growth, the glory therefore goes to God and no other.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">19.3 </span><span class="c7">Transition from knowing (of) to knowing (personally, relationship)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If God isn&#39;t constantly on your heart, in your mind and &quot;on your lips&quot;, so much that strangers can look at you and say &quot;there&#39;s something Godly about that person&quot;. Then chances are, if you are not a novice, a very new Christian, you haven&#39;t understood salvation yet!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There is a transition from knowing of to knowing personally. I could say I know the Pope without ever having met him. To meet with him would take knowing him to a slightly deeper level, a regular meeting on, let&#39;s say, church matters, would be a deeper knowledge, and if I were to become a friend of his that he would seek my company more often and discuss more personal things like opinions and ideas rather than his business, I&rsquo;d know him in a different way again.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sure, I know (of) the Pope, but I don&rsquo;t know the Pope (personally).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The Pope is a mere man, in all his pomp and human preference, he is certainly insignificant to Peter, Paul and James, who all called themselves &ldquo;duolos&rdquo; (slave). None of which would have sat in a &ldquo;Vatican&rdquo; or dare to wear Glorious Robes. What slave would ever present themselves that way? Sure, we all know (of) God, but it&rsquo;s the responsibility of a disciple is to learn their discipline and in our case gain charis and therefore an active personal relationship with God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">When we get to know a person, we learn more about them, mostly by personal communication on a regular basis, while gaining a deeper understanding of them and rapport with them over time.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Is it the time that matters? No, not as much as the depth of communication. We can have long-term superficial relationships, and in other relationships, we may reveal our more personal side rather quickly. It&rsquo;s no different with God; how deep you get and how quickly you get to that depth is a choice you make.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The transition from knowing of God to knowing him intimately is in the enlightenment you absorb, not how quickly you do so. Getting to know God quickly is good, but deeply is more valuable. I can only encourage you to read the Bible with an inquisitive nature, seeking to look more deeply into its real meaning (which often means to look at the correct meaning of the original language) without bias. Do not bend its words to suit what you want it to say, as the moment you attempt to inject yourself in, you are valuing your opinions above its real (reinforced by multiple scriptures) message.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Don&rsquo;t be the person who says, God loves everyone, so God will save everyone and God forgives sin, so God will forgive everyone. Then, based on those two (overly simple) thoughts (not facts), all people go to heaven, including those who intentionally sin and those who sin by chosen ignorance. Those views are assumptions and unfounded.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Chosen ignorance? Yes, by those words I mean, people can assume that, if they choose to avoid discovering what sin is, they can be held blameless simply because they didn&rsquo;t know that whatever it is they are or are not doing is sin. Yet again, sin is born from self. Any aversion to its knowledge is therefore born of personal desire and sin in itself. Not knowing a sin is one thing, yet avoiding the knowledge of sin in the hope it reduces the penalty is then sinful self-preservation, putting yourself before God (not denying yourself).</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.wuocp1rbhxjx"><span class="c29 c26">Humility</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">20.1 Different Approaches, Same Truth</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ve said &ldquo;I am nothing&rdquo;, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s not about me&rdquo;, or &ldquo;I&rsquo;m just here to serve&rdquo; many times. It wasn&#39;t till I heard it from another person, which struck me as a strange statement, that maybe the &ldquo;I am nothing&rdquo; humility speech could be a display of ego and pride within itself. There was nothing in the statement itself that gave this away, nor even any words of pride. Yet I&rsquo;d just been attacked for promoting God, which was exactly what this person was doing. But I dared to promote God in a way that their teacher had told them was a &ldquo;false gospel&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I didn&rsquo;t know it at the time, as it caused me to look deeper into my approach. But both our approaches are very Biblical. We are both describing the same &ldquo;Hypothetical&rdquo; mountain, I&rsquo;m looking at the North face and describing that, whereas he is looking at the much steeper south face. I&rsquo;ll side-track a moment. I present the purpose of salvation as a relationship with God, which is shown in the fruits of the spirit (&ldquo;You shall know them by their fruits&rdquo;), which are good fruits: love, joy, peace, patience, etc. The good things that must grow in a person&#39;s life if they are saved.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">He presents God as a Judge ready to send you to hell if you don&rsquo;t repent. By the way, I certainly don&rsquo;t avoid the repentance part, as each of these good things has an opposite sin, which you need to walk away from to gain the good. For example, you need to walk away from the sin of hate to gain the fruit of love. Same God, same action, which is acceptance of Jesus&rsquo;s sacrifice for sin and repentance. But I focus on what happens from the decision, gaining a wonderful relationship with God, and they focus on the sin God can&rsquo;t accept. So really they focus on before the commitment to God and the cost of the conversion, sin and giving it up. The steep face, steep as that&rsquo;s a hard message &ldquo;You need to give up&rdquo;. I focus on the reward after, what you get from the commitment, the good fruits of the spirit, a reason to want God, the attractive, easy slope rather than the hard, sharp face of personal sacrifice. I don&rsquo;t avoid the fact that you will walk away from sin, but my presentation being on the good as its replacement makes the commitment easier.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">20.2 The Car, The Message, and The Heart</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll use another example, then get back to the humility side. Let&#39;s look at salvation and your relationship with God as a car. He is saying, &ldquo;Pay $100 thousand dollars, and you will get this car for it, and remember this is a lot of money, so you&rsquo;d better appreciate the car!&rdquo; I&rsquo;m saying, &ldquo;Look at this wonderful car, it has this benefit and that, you&rsquo;ll enjoy driving this, which makes it valuable, and it&rsquo;s only $100k.&rdquo; Same car, same cost, which one would get more sales?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Also, in this example, they are not leaving the car sales yard; they&rsquo;re only selling to those who are looking for cars. I&rsquo;ll expand, and suggest to you that the order of: Sin, then Hell (it&rsquo;s penalty), then God and finishing there (for people to then continue living their &ldquo;hard&rdquo; lives), is promoting to those who believe in Sin, Hell and God before you even start&hellip; those in the car yard. I&rsquo;m promoting a better life even before death, so I&rsquo;m promoting to all people, even if they don&rsquo;t already believe in sin, hell and God, that there is a better life. Your circumstances may not change, but I&rsquo;ve got something that will bring happiness even within bad circumstances.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Even atheists and sceptics who are not going to listen to the sin, then hell, then God message, will be interested in the &ldquo;I have a way you can gain: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, self-control, purpose, and so much more&rdquo; message. So I&rsquo;m going out of the car yard to the footpath and saying to people (not even considering a car, or don&rsquo;t believe cars exist), &ldquo;hey, is walking everywhere difficult? Would you like to consider a better way?&rdquo; There&rsquo;s something that can save you the effort, called a car. You may have heard of them. I&rsquo;m confident you&rsquo;re walking because you haven&rsquo;t discovered the wonderful benefit of having a car, you think they cost too much, or maybe you think they are a myth. Please give me a little time to show you a car and show you the good things they do. Same mountain, same car, different approach.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">20.3 Humility, Pride, and the Heart</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Why is this even important? I had been told by them that what I promoted was &ldquo;not the gospel&rdquo;. They not only had a different hard approach, but they were so religious about their method, that they could not accept the goodness of God; they even said&hellip; and I think the words were &ldquo;Life is hard as a Christian&rdquo;. Straight out, I wonder if they have ever comprehended the awesome good side of God, the side that, by the way, is what a Christian is expected to enter into. It&rsquo;s the reason to climb the mountain, the reason to own the car, it&rsquo;s driving the car.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It seems to me, as I type this, his experience of driving the car is bad, &ldquo;hard being a Christian&quot;. He must be sitting at the lights waiting for them to change to green and getting frustrated looking at the pedestrians moving faster than him. What he doesn&rsquo;t realise is that if he simply looks at the lights instead of the pedestrians, they ARE green. God has made it wonderful even in the circumstances when the circumstances around you are bad. Or maybe he&#39;s in the snow and cold, with no entertainment (no joy, etc.). The car has a heater, even if there is snow outside, and it has a stereo, even if the noise outside is the howling wind of a blizzard. God is good; you just need to connect with God to understand the beauty within, even when trouble is all around.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Not knowing God&#39;s joy is a choice&mdash;not a choice to avoid it (for a very few it is), but more so a choice that hasn&rsquo;t been made to find it. Who finds it? The Bible says, &ldquo;seek, and you shall find&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s not just talking about salvation there, but things like joy will come to those who seek. But let me yet again qualify this, the joy of God comes from understanding and from receiving it within from that relationship, even if your external circumstances are troublesome.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I know these people can&rsquo;t know this because it is such great joy (and all the other fruits of the spirit too). It&rsquo;s internal happiness within external turmoil. These people may be saved, but they certainly lack in the relationship with God, as that side is such a blessing that you don&rsquo;t even think about the heaven and hell aspect&mdash;the wonders right now are all you want to talk about. So, before I mention the next part, I saw a hard relationship that lacks happiness in their relationship with God. When they condemned my approach, I also saw what seemed to be pride in their own approach. So, back to the beginning of all this, the attack, and then hearing &ldquo;I am nothing&rdquo; from them straight after.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">As he spoke, my first thought was that &ldquo;I say exactly the same thing&rdquo;. My second was, &ldquo;Are you saying this to reconfirm our biblical status?&rdquo; We are expected to be humble, though is that very declaration of humility in a way saying to God, &ldquo;Look at me, God and honour me for being humble&rdquo;? A declaration of humility to seek honour? Especially when we say that to people who should know of the humility God requires of us, they will likely think of you as being Godly by being humble, therefore thinking of you as being a real Christian from the humility.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Because this came from a person so superior that they had to stand solidly against my inferior (in their mind anyway) approach, it seemed somewhat egotistical to me. They did not defend their view&mdash;I was simply saying to them that their approach is good, I think mine attracts more people. Yet still I was attacked over this. I now understand they were probably attempting to defend their teacher, who is the one who says even more harshly than &ldquo;That&rsquo;s not the gospel&rdquo;, he calls it a &ldquo;false gospel&rdquo;. Now, this man they follow must have torn out half the pages of his Bible, as I found many scriptures on the goodness of God after I researched him.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Even better than finding those, the Bible is a manual of life, like a car&#39;s manual. It seems they&rsquo;ve read the manual, but have never driven the car&mdash;knowing the Bible&#39;s words, but not having the wonderful relationship with God. It&rsquo;s not about knowing the words in the book, it&rsquo;s about the relationship.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So these hardliners seem to have had their egos hurt. They may preach submission to God for the selfish reason of avoiding hell, but they seem to have no further relationship. They are probably walking away from sin, but to where, as they don&rsquo;t know the opposite good things that I&rsquo;m walking towards. Then, when it happened that one of them said, &ldquo;I am nothing&rdquo;, and I&rsquo;d already thought I&rsquo;d seen pride in him&hellip; could a proud man say that? Was it a statement to impress me and/or God, with an announcement of the humility that God seeks from us?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I now wonder about the instances where I had said things like &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not about me&rdquo;, which is very true, though is leaning toward this issue. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not important, God is.&rdquo; I was certainly thinking it when I said that. A declaration of humility could be from pride. Sure, the Bible says things like &ldquo;Do not think of yourself more highly than you ought&rdquo;. We are to be humble. My issue here is, are we showing pride by declaring how humble we are?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">20.4 Humility Before God</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let&rsquo;s look at it further. My greeting declares my service; I say &ldquo;HI, at your service in charis&rdquo;. I want you to learn from what I present; it is my service to God for your benefit. Even Peter and Paul called themselves Doulos. Doulos means slave, and in the opening sentence of a letter, they would declare it, for example, Romans 1:1, &ldquo;Paul, a slave of Jesus Christ&hellip;&rdquo; There is more implication of humility in their greetings. My declaration is of service, which may have no humility behind it at all. To call yourself a slave of Jesus is a definite stand on this.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So even as I type this, I&rsquo;m wondering if I should change my greeting. I teach not even as a teacher&mdash;it&rsquo;s not my calling, just a part of my calling&mdash;nor as a prophet, though some of this is prophetic by nature. I present this for your benefit and not for my profit, as my intent is to bless God with all profits. I hope you will use this as a springboard to launch to far greater heights than I.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I see you as my class of future mechanics, who I hope will not only graduate, but surpass what I teach. I seek to honour God by the opportunity he has given me to express these things to you. So my role is a role of service.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">That was a thought on humility and on what we say&mdash;how we can speak one message, but the opposite comes across. I do know I need to work on my humility.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Having typed that earlier, I have another thought to add. There is something within that would have me declare my name and far more; if left unchecked it would give no glory to God. It is the self that strives to be noticed. Is humility not having such thoughts? No&mdash;it is keeping them in check.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I know very little, yet God shows me things. I&rsquo;m typing statements, then researching them to find them correct&mdash;and even more profound than I realised. It can&rsquo;t be me. I&rsquo;m just the typist.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Why? He uses the humble. He can teach the humble. And humility creates a desire to go deeper.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I wonder about this: the more we submit, the more humble we become, and the more God can move and use us.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I beg you to seek God. Push yourself out of the centre, and fill it with Him. If a single word can produce a book like this, what can be found by going deeper?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.2n0ea5hc2qoi"><span class="c29 c26">The journey</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">21.1 {subheading}</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">As mentioned, it is a journey, a journey of discovery. &ldquo;Pilgrim&#39;s Progress&rdquo; is a story of the journey which is in the progression of Christianity, and it is fitting that we are pilgrims progressing in our race towards God in our relationships with him. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What can I say about the journey as a whole? Not a great deal, as I&rsquo;ll break down some aspects for revelation&#39;s sake. Yet I&rsquo;ll sum it here before showing those stages.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Please recall it&rsquo;s likened to the journey of my ancestors. Part one, Yeshua gave his life in sacrifice for your sins&mdash;an instant in time that located an afterlife for you to then be able to reach.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Secondly, the declaration of that information: people presenting the message of salvation.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Third, the value presented in the journey and destination. For them, this was to discover it would be a voyage of weeks; for us, it&rsquo;s the explanation of Christianity being presented to us, to know the cost and journey that will be required.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Fourth, the choice to take the journey and preparation (like packing and traveling to the docks), a decision to say that sinner&rsquo;s prayer and commit. It&rsquo;s far longer to prepare for a physical journey than a spiritual one, which could be as short as a few minutes. Yet as short as it can be, there is time between thinking &ldquo;yes, I&rsquo;ll do this&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Amen&rdquo; at the end of a sinner&rsquo;s prayer.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Fifth (of course it doesn&rsquo;t finish there as many would have you believe, most often because they simply don&rsquo;t know themselves), that &ldquo;Amen&rdquo; is like giving your details for the ship&#39;s passenger log, or picking up the ticket (if it&rsquo;s a ticketed journey). You haven&rsquo;t even boarded the ship yet.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sixth, if you have the benefit of new Christians classes, that is like getting on board; otherwise, initial further education of any kind, like Bible readings, is similar.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Then seventh, the journey begins. But as you can see, there is a lot just to lead up to the ship embarking. From that point, it is constant sailing&mdash;and hopefully not seeing the journey as too tough and jumping off the ship when passing some islands or the like.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are ports along the way, places where the temptation to disembark may be alluring. Don&rsquo;t, as some remote port will be worse than the European city you departed from (life as an ex-Christian isn&rsquo;t as pretty as it seems).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Lastly, the journey isn&rsquo;t over till you reach the destination, as obvious as that may be. We need to persevere till the end&mdash;death or rapture.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So let&rsquo;s look at those stages a little deeper.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.2 Stage 1/ The discovery or sacrifice</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">As Cook discovered Australia, nothing happened till the news reached England. Then its use began, first as a penal colony, then eventually as the new world. The instant Christ died, sin was forgiven, yet past sin and generational sin; the sin of Eden passed through all generations. Yet still nothing happened. Sure, sin was forgiven, but what of the sinner? Their sin is still upon them till they accept that sacrifice, and it is counted upon them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Likewise with Cook, there at that time the ability to know of the good value of Australia came into existence, yet no one had taken the journey (maybe the Apostles, yet record of any conversion event is unknown, likely upon the final removal of doubt, like Thomas). </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">We honour Cook in his discovery with statues, and Christ is Lord, no higher honour, no statues needed, nor in my mind suitable, as we don&rsquo;t really know what he looked like. But this is not about statues. We respectfully honour Christ above all and his sacrifice. Though remember it does nothing till it is accepted and acted upon. You can refuse a gift, yet it is still a gift. You can accept a gift and never open it; likewise, acceptance requires commitment.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Acceptance alone does nothing. Christ died so we could be saved, yet beyond that, Christ died so we could serve.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.3 Stage 2/ the announcement or gospel</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It was not till Cook returned to England with the news of a good, useful land that the news broke out, and it wasn&rsquo;t even considered for use till a colony was established, in which they used convicts to build. It simply meant nothing to the average person.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now we must remember the hostile, barren west coast had been discovered, but was not considered for habitation as it was harsh. Likewise, there was a harsh path to God that was beyond most, a path of dedicated work to reach a distant goal through extreme dedication. These two relate. They were both unappealing and both presented xxx</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Yet like the Law, it was known, and was almost uninhabited, as there were a minimal number of natives. The land was vast, and the inhabitants extremely few. There was a path that had been taken by a small trickle of people who accepted a highly restricted, narrow life in both cases. The Law required fulfilment by sacrifice in lifestyle and blood; so does Christianity. The difference is Christ was the ultimate sacrifice for Sin, any further sacrifice is then from sin, not for sin. To attempt to work your way to God&#39;s favour is then repulsive, as it is then in denial of what he&rsquo;d given.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It was not till he&rsquo;d risen that the real understanding and power of life over death came about. It wasn&rsquo;t till he&rsquo;d risen that the boldness which spread Christianity around the world came in.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It wasn&rsquo;t till he&rsquo;d risen that value was truly understood and the awareness of real value began.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The resurrection here is like Cook arriving back in England to tell the King, &ldquo;the land is immense and good&rdquo;. It was the resurrection that empowered the sacrifice; yet that&rsquo;s merely where it began.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.4 Stage 3/ The value presented to consider (in both cases) [urge]</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The British Knew of the harsh Land in the southern Ocean on the other side of the planet, about as far away as you could go. Which, like living a Godly life, is as about as far as you can go in opposition to the carnal life. They knew of any journey to it being the most difficult you could take, much like the path to God as it was.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What was the change? Perception of the land in its worth and knowledge of required resources. That hostile west coast has little to build with, sure It has stone, but sparse vegetation and poor soil. All housing would need to be cut from rock rather than wooden houses, and what do you grow food in? Yet like Salvation by the Law, there was a minute number of natives who lived there.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The perception of its value changed, and the knowledge of very suitable resources, such as trees for wood and fertile land to grow food. It was not barren. I guess I could say it would not be a perpetual sacrifice, merely a single sacrifice in establishing a home. Again, like the single sacrifice of Christ. Yet a difference here, as the new colonial would need to build their own home, Christ made the sacrifice for us.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The journey was still very similar, much like our journey is similar to that of those who worked for salvation before the crucifixion. We are just going to a different part of the same place. Here is a minor point that has major connotations. Can you assess a person&#39;s salvation by what they do? No. Like you can&rsquo;t look at a sailing ship entering the Indian Ocean and say that it&#39;s going to the east or west coast of Australia! Both ships would at that stage be doing exactly the same thing. It wouldn&rsquo;t be till very late in the journey that you&rsquo;d notice some differences. Late in a Christians life, there is some evidence of differences in the fruit they produce. The law and living by it doesn&rsquo;t bring the fruit of the Spirit. The Law is a System of (usually minimal) adherence, Life in the Spirit is an illumination and joy.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Both journeys have similar aspects in the natural trip to Australia and the path to Godliness. Under the law, you are to reserve a portion of your crops for the poor, probably begrudgingly.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Under grace, we give to the poor, but with gladness; we do the same thing, but the attitude is different. Under the law, we do so to work our way. In grace, we do so knowing we can&rsquo;t work our way; the payment was made, but we do so in respect instead.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Two very similar journeys in exactly the same direction to two different places, and very different results.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Though this is not where our journey begins. Again, no person began their journey at the moment Cook made the discovery, nor when he announced it to the kingdom. The Apostles were probably on that journey, though that&rsquo;s a different story. I&rsquo;m focusing here on your personal journey years later.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Our journey isn&rsquo;t even conceived till we are made aware of its existence. Some jump in at the first word, yet most require convincing. Another similarity, the great majority will never want to leave the comfort of their established, easy lifestyle in their houses in the Cities of Britain. Why go from that comfortable, civilised lifestyle to living by faith in what seems a less comfortable existence?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">God urges you. Imagine this: someone says to you, &ldquo;There&rsquo;s this place called Australia.&rdquo; Are you going to instantly decide you want to live there? Even move will you want to take that harrowing journey? It will take some convincing. Though for those predestined, sooner or later, they will submit to that call. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Before I go on, the journeys are so similar that most people simply don&rsquo;t know the difference. Most people are trying to work their way, thinking they have given their life by making the decision to work their way. It is still by their effort due to the attitude of their heart, and the fruit just doesn&rsquo;t seem to be the same (as it probably isn&rsquo;t).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.5 Stage 4/ &nbsp;The decision or choice to commit (in both cases) - not a cruise, but a costly service</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You probably didn&rsquo;t commit to God the first time you heard about God. When you did, chances are you knew about the heaven-hell message and didn&rsquo;t really understand the service as doulos. Even if you did understand that, you may not have understood the aspect of disowning yourself. If, in the extremely unlikely case that you may have even been told about that. I seriously expect you didn&rsquo;t comprehend how charis relates to that in every aspect. How it like the cardiovascular system is interwoven throughout the body and drives it all for the brain&#39;s sake. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Maybe you thought you&rsquo;d join God&rsquo;s cruise line as a passenger to be carried off to heaven in a luxurious, comfortable life catering to your benefits. Ah, No&hellip; You are the crew, a very undermanned crew of a massive cargo ship. It is a life of service and duty, and you don&rsquo;t get a break in port either. The ship is seriously undermanned (the harvest is ripe, but the workers are few). In port, you desperately need to seek more crew members; evangelise. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You may look like a Christian, but you can&rsquo;t fool God as to your commitment.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.6 Stage 5/ The packing and travel to the departure or declaration of a desire to commit</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It may not take long between the time you first hear of true Christianity and choosing to sign up as a crew member, it may be a while. If you have not committed, truly committed to living God&#39;s way like Yeshua did, seeking to turn every event and every conversation to God. Then the opportunity is now, and the time is now.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Are you prepared? Let&#39;s see if you are willing to pay the price. Not for sin, but in due service for that which he paid.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.7 Stage 5a/ The payment and ticket, or the sinners&#39; prayer and Amen</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Remember, the price is everything. We sell everything to buy the field or the pearl. More than that, it&rsquo;s not merely all your possessions and wealth. Is it your very self, Mat 16:24? &hellip; disown himself, and Paul &ldquo;bought with a price&rdquo; Is it your salvation bought with a price? No, You are. That would make you a slave, well, yes. Rom 1:1 Nothing about you counts anymore, to disown yourself is to give up everything about you, your pride, ego, ID, needs, wants, desires&hellip; Everything. The ME in life doesn&rsquo;t matter anymore; only God and others matter!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">This is the hardest thing. In fact, it is so hard I don&rsquo;t think anyone can do it! If I&rsquo;m right, we must all give that up to God. We must therefore ask God to come into our hearts and push the Me. the self, the I out, as I don&rsquo;t have the strength to do it, nor the knowledge, and maybe just maybe the desire, who really wants their will destroyed? Not my will but thine.<br><br>Before even contemplating saying a sinner&#39;s prayer, the inductee needs to be aware of what they&rsquo;re committing to. Personally, I don&rsquo;t know of anyone who emphasises this in the modern world, including the most famous evangelists. Certainly none of those using the Mr X method. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I may certainly be wrong here, and I partly hope I am, though if we need to seriously submit in self-denial to disown ourselves, the ego, will, and desires, including things we think we need, yet can live without. I don&rsquo;t see more than a few people in my life who may have done that. If I could remember them, and my memory isn&rsquo;t perfect either, I think I may be able to count them on my fingers. So very few&hellip;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I declare right now. If we see people come to that understanding of commitment in charis, even 1% of the Church, they will make major waves, and the growth factor will cause major revival.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.8 Stage 6/ The boarding or novice education</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">After the commitment, there is the process of boarding, usually in dealing with baggage and for a working ship (as again, we are not merely passengers), cargo. This is the period of discovery, learning the aspects of Christian life and grafting them into our behaviour.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Grafting, for those who don&rsquo;t know, is transplanting a different thing into the body or one plant type into a similar other plant; some orange trees also grow lemons in the same tree.<br></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The grafting process in Christianity is to be a total graft. We are not only to take on Christianity but also to prune away all of the original sinful life, as you&rsquo;ll see in the next part (departure)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.9 Stage 7/ the departure or early Christian life [the change]</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Rom 12:3 &nbsp;mentions the unique personalised aspect of grace &ldquo;For by the grace given to me&hellip;&rdquo; But in starting a sentence with &ldquo;For&hellip;&rdquo; it is building on the previous thought or statement Romans 12:1&amp;2. Romans 12:3 then seeks humility. So let&#39;s depart that path a moment and look outside the grace scripture to see what brought it</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Romans 12:1,2 is a discussion of transformation and a plea towards it. Like a ship departing on its journey, we are to depart our old lives. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The LSV says; I therefore urge you, brothers, in view of God&#39;s mercies, to offer your bodies as living sacrifices that are holy and pleasing to God, for this is the reasonable way for you to worship. Do not be conformed to this world, but continually be transformed by the renewing of your minds so that you may be able to determine what God&#39;s will is; what is proper, pleasing, and perfect. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Offer your bodies&rdquo; The implication here is to give up the fleshy desires; preceding chapters mention this, but I&rsquo;ll not go back that far. I really am trying to keep this book short. &nbsp;And this is merely &ldquo;the reasonable&rdquo; thing to do.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Followed by the warning &ldquo;Do not be conformed to this world&rdquo;. Don&rsquo;t be worldly, or act like the unsaved in any way. And &ldquo;continually be transformed by the renewing of your minds&rdquo;. Grab on to that constant change in growth toward Godliness that charis brings.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, what happens when you do? &ldquo;You may be able to determine what God&#39;s will is; what is proper, pleasing, and perfect&rdquo; You will see the heart of God, what God wants, especially in that fruit of the Spirit.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">When we depart the worldly life in both thought and deed, we are making room in our hearts for God, especially in thought, as sin begins in the mind and so does Godliness.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Thought brings me to Philippians 4:8 (4:4-9 is all quite relevant here, especially as 4:5 mentions having a gracious attitude. But 4:8 what to think on &ldquo;Finally, brothers, whatever is true, whatever is honourable, whatever is fair, whatever is pure, whatever is acceptable, whatever is commendable, if there is anything of excellence and if there is anything praiseworthy&mdash;keep thinking about these things.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The Christian life embarks in a sinner&#39;s prayer, but is a journey of discovery with careful guidance of thought and deed. Here, as mentioned before, is where we graft those thoughts into our lives and prune away any unGodly thought. Another thought before the next phase, &ldquo;anything of excellence&rdquo;; these are things of excellence in God, not in the world, and the same applies to all of those thoughts</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.10 Stage 8/ the chances to disembark or backslide</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, once underway, there will be ports along the journey, times where the journey will stop for a moment to take on new cargo (thoughts, etc.) and take off old cargo. This is often a good thing for the learning process, yet we may at times wonder why the ship has stopped. It will not be what you&rsquo;re used to, as the majority of the time we are &ldquo;at sea&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If things aren&rsquo;t moving along, you may be in port, and of course, as we are discussing sailing ships, the wind may have died down, and we are merely adrift at sea. Now, if things have stopped for a moment, make sure you are not taking on bad cargo! Avoid sin, temptation in thought and deed. Also, beware of unscriptural teaching (more so antiscriptural). The message &ldquo;be good&rdquo; may not be directly from the Bible, but it aligns with it, so I don&#39;t consider it unscriptural. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Ok, when in port, some sailors take shore leave and don&rsquo;t reboard the ship. In our journey, this is backsliding. Avoid this, as the purpose for the journey is to reach the new land, not to stay in some grubby port along the way.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Get rid of the rotting worldly cargo and take on the fresh Godly cargo at every chance, but never stay in port!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.11 Stage 9/ The arrival or death/rapture</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Finally, we have the arrival. This is a life-long journey, so arrival at the final destination here is death in the physical body and beginning the afterlife, or God-willing rapture, having never seen death in the natural. I&rsquo;d love that!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I don&rsquo;t have to say much about this, just make sure you get there with a full, healthy, Godly cargo.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">20 (expand??)</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.61cta79iluhh"><span>21.12 </span><span class="c29 c26">The urge - god starting the journey</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The journey began before time; it was always God&#39;s plan, there is a predestined factor. Yet God does not work on predestination alone. There is also free will; our lives are like swimming in a river with multiple tributaries (sources in) and multiple distributaries (flows out). This river has a moderate current. So, sure, you can swim against the current, but not forever. The choices of life will determine which distributary you come out in. However, swimming against the call of God is like swimming against that current; sooner or later, you will end up downstream to the place God has called you. Swim with the flow; it&rsquo;s easier, and you get to where you will inevitably end up quicker.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A river&#39;s current was there before you entered (predestination). It&rsquo;s up to you to choose when to stop fighting and swim with it (freewill). God urges you before you even know, and when you know of God&#39;s call, you may still fight it a while. Sooner or later, for those select, the point of running will turn from running away to running to God, or walking at least. Please, if you&rsquo;re in that flow, no longer resisting, don&rsquo;t let &ldquo;the self&rdquo; slow the process down. Don&rsquo;t slow things down with a half-hearted loose commitment, as you&rsquo;re still swimming away, just with less effort. Again, swim with the flow, have a passion to seek every Godly thing in your life, to become what God wants you to be as soon as you can.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">21 {current partial sectioning, so reassess}</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.k6wrekq80e0n"><span>21.13 </span><span class="c29 c26">The commitment</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll revisit the commitment for a moment due to its importance.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, you&rsquo;ve committed to God&hellip; Or have you? I&rsquo;m going to declare right now that I believe the commitment is more than you think. I don&rsquo;t know your level of commitment, but I&rsquo;ll be right in more than 99% of cases. I think at least 99% of people don&lsquo;t understand commitment and discipleship. It has been lost through the ages. Worldliness has come into the Church. Most people seem to think that going to Church once a week or even a couple of times a year makes them a Christian. Others think that as long as you have said a sinner&#39;s prayer, you are saved, no matter how you live afterwards. Far fewer think you need to do those things and also be kind and show mercy, love and the like, yet that is more true.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Still, even that last statement was not correct. Not by a long way! Sure, you can add to care for the widows and the hungry and not show favour and more. But we still miss the point. As I type this (and this is an early stage, again I haven&#39;t started at the first word and typed till the last, it&rsquo;s a bit here and a bit there as I&rsquo;m inspired in various parts at various times). I realise my understanding of what a disciple is has just gone through a large paradigm shift. Sure, a Christian is to do all of those, yet doing those doesn&rsquo;t make you a Christian.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;d also like to introduce a new term here, as what I&rsquo;ve just described is what more than 90% of people think. In fact, I think at least 99%. But who am I to assess this? I have only surveyed a very few people. If almost everyone thinks or says that is what a Christian is, then I accept their concept. I&rsquo;ll simply not use the word &ldquo;Christian&rdquo; to describe what the Bible shows a disciple, follower of Yeshua, is. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.14. What a disciple really is</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Before I explain what the Bible actually says, I&rsquo;ll explain the new term for a person who follows in the way of Christ, who is discipled in the way of the messiah.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">As mentioned earlier, Jesus is a recent name that was impossible 1000 years ago, as the letter &quot; J didn&rsquo;t even exist in any text. We also know that Josephus, the only reliable historian of his day, from his region called him Yeshua. So in that respect, I do the same. Can you see where I&rsquo;m leading? I call a follower of Yeshua a Yeshuan (you may have heard of this term before).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But here&rsquo;s the difference. A Yeshuan not only does those things mentioned. But they also:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1/ Recognise that doing those things can&rsquo;t save them. That It is Grace that saves them by faith (in the sacrifice of Yeshua). Ironically, they then do those things anyway as they follow by doing what Jesus did. The difference is in their soul (heart and mind); they are not doing anything to achieve salvation, merely to show the correct respect. There is nothing to earn, but everything to show thanks for.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2/ They earnestly seek to produce the good fruits of the spirit, to become that shining light, to show the love of God in those virtues (the fruits of the spirit).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">3/They value relationship (with God) above all those other acts anyway. Having a mind on God and Godly things almost constantly. As obedient children of God..</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">4/.And most importantly, they recognise the missing factor of following in the way of Yeshua. They know that following in his way means they are to do what he did. What did he do? Sure, He cast out demons, healed the sick, fed thousands, gave whatever was expected, and prayed constantly. I may have missed one or two things that &ldquo;Christians&rdquo; may do. He did something else that very few of us ever do. Something that he did constantly at every single chance.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">He taught, and more so, he promoted God and Godliness. He urged everyone he met in one way or another to repent, turn to God, live a Godly life and to spread that to everyone.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">To live like him, we are to cast out demons (if we can), to heal (if we have the faith) and more importantly as there is no &lsquo;if&rsquo; here... Express God to everyone who is in our presence or range of influence at every chance with a compassion for them in a desire that we can help them understand their need to repent and also gain that wonderful relationship. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Sure, there are a very small handful of people who go into the main streets of cities on weekend nights and preach the gospel (their version at least), or maybe hand out tracts. But even those people will just sit by themselves and maybe read the Bible on the public transport home. At a picnic in the local park on the weekend, at lunch, they will hang with their families or fellow church members and eat and talk about social things. Maybe talk about Godly things, which is far less likely. But do they ever promote God at&hellip; every chance? No. Even for those who go out regularly, it seems confined to just a few hours a week.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I can know that I&rsquo;m safe with that &lsquo;no&rsquo;, as if they did, then I would have had people tell me about God at the shops, on a park bench, while waiting at the doctors, everywhere. That simply has never happened. Maybe I may have been approached on a bench once or twice in my life, but I can&rsquo;t even remember an occasion where that actually happened. Certainly never in shops or at the doctors or the like.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, even those less than 1% of Christians who go out to specifically evangelise on weekend nights, don&rsquo;t do so constantly. Yes, I say less than 1%. My city alone has nearly one million people, and I&rsquo;ve seen regularly 5-6 people handing out tracts, which, by the way, is a poor method, but at least they are doing something. Preaching in the busy streets is also somewhat common by a similar minuscule number. However, I&rsquo;d recommend that even less. Well, the messages they preach don&rsquo;t reach the mark at least, and what are they trying to do by that method?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In ancient times, that was the only method to spread a message, as there was no media except for a very few handwritten messages. So someone shouting in the marketplace was the mass media of their day, like TV of the times. People would go to listen to them as it was the prime form of entertainment in most places. Excluding Gladiators and the like, but that was far more rare. Every town of basically every culture would have public speaking of one form or another. It was the best thing to do back then&hellip; It was the only thing, basically.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Does shouting in the marketplace (busy city streets) stand up today? Just as much as Gladiators do as well. There is no place&hellip; unless&hellip; yes, I&rsquo;ll add a condition. If you present a very new kind of message or something that really grabs their attention, and I&rsquo;m not saying to do magic tricks to build a crowd. Then hit them with the same old despised messages.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I also have an issue with &ldquo;tricks&rdquo; anyway, as they are based on deception. Should we use deception in any way? This is just a personal thought, but no.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I would like to broadcast in public areas, yet not till I have a very different message, and I do, it&rsquo;s just not polished as it should be yet. So, I&rsquo;ll wait</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.15 Lifestyle, not lip-service</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you are committed to God, you are committed to these things:</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Discovering what God wants: earnest repentance, real understanding of his word, real growth in spiritual fruits, a desire to find your call, and a heart that desperately wants to reach the lost.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Imagine being in an ocean boat race, and a wave sinks a boat with a lot of people who were rowing. What&rsquo;s your first thought? Great, now we can&rsquo;t lose and row on, or stop, we need to turn back and rescue them? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If we see people in physical turmoil, we are concerned enough to seek their rescue, yet when we see everyone around us in major spiritual jeopardy, on a highway to hell, we are happy to &lsquo;run our race&rsquo; and ignore them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">OK, this may seem harsh, but I really mean this. You have just read what true commitment is. How many people do you really see who have a mind constantly to God, who want to chase Godliness, who want to act like Yeshua, who are constantly focusing on promoting God to every person they ever meet (not just on a Saturday night)?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Less than 1%? I&rsquo;d certainly say less than 1%. In my city, I&rsquo;ll round the population up to 1 million, as it&rsquo;s quite close. I&rsquo;d say 10 to 20, maybe 30 thousand go to Church. I&rsquo;ll be generous and say 30 thousand. I won&rsquo;t count those who never go to Church, who are Christmas and easter Christians, those who are likely to be found in the bars and strip clubs rather than a Church.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So of that 30 thousand, how many do I ever see promoting Gog or even working in Christian charities or acting in ministry&hellip; acting as Christians in at least some way? Remember this, as I&rsquo;ll use this &lsquo;LS&rsquo; to show the difference&hellip; It&rsquo;s a Life-Style not a Lip-Service! How many give some kind of Christian Service (role), including evangelism? I&rsquo;ll be generous again and say 10%, I&rsquo;m down to 3 thousand. Of those 3 thousand, how many are doing so from the wrong perspective, the wrong attitude in their heart? Those who think they need to do it to work their way to heaven? I&rsquo;d say most of them, yet again I&rsquo;ll keep the figure light, say 1 thousand, leaving 2 thousand. Now I personally think it&rsquo;s only a few hundred, yet I&rsquo;ll still look on the generous side and ask one last question.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Of those 2 thousand, how many are still missing the mark because they have not crucified the self? That still want to be seen as important, or have their name remembered, have ego, have pride or in some other way value their desires above God&#39;s? Matthew 10:38. Here I will yet again look on the light side as I have met very few in my life who aren&rsquo;t holding on to ego, pride, selfish desires or anything else where their &lsquo;self&rsquo; rules their heart rather than God. I&rsquo;ll reduce it to 1 thousand. 1 thousand Christians out of 1 million 0.1% and I really think the self issue is the major flaw to just about everyone, I know many of even those dedicated ones who cry about their (social/emotional) needs not being met and do they really act like Jesus, forget the miracles, what about their conversations (usually about social things rather than about God), and their attitude to evangelism when someone starts a conversation with them over some non-Christian thing? Do they try to turn the conversation to God? A couple of them may, but I only ever really see that when they are talking to other Christians or it that Time of the week when they are out to evangelise. Do they not realise that person may have wanted to know about something, yet are going to hell, and they could have changed the conversation and changed that person&#39;s life?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Personally, I think only .01% want to turn every conversation (or at least most conversations) to God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>There is also a commitment to maintenance; </span><span class="c58">The NT is filled with commands (&quot;be holy,&quot; &quot;love one another,&quot; &quot;put to death the misdeeds of the body&quot;). God&#39;s grace (</span><span class="c42 c58">charis</span><span class="c58">) is the empowering influence that makes obedience possible, but the choice to obey remains a real, responsible human act.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Obedience is all-important, but not under your own strength and not at the cost of relationship, as obedience (of the covenant) is for the purpose of gaining that relationship, therefore it is in itself in submission to the relationship. Sure, we are to obey, but what do we obey? The words our master commissioned thousands of years ago through mere scribes or those which He directly spoke in red letters in the New Testament, and even more those he speaks in charis?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Obey, but make sure it is primarily The Direct words and that of charis over that of old. They are called Old and New Testaments for a reason. And I can&rsquo;t find the Scripture that says &ldquo;We are saved by upholding the Law&rdquo;. Especially as it is literally impossible, what was the last animal you offered in sacrifice in the temple? You must do that to be saved under the Law!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;m so glad we are under the law of the Spirit, rather than the law of sin and death. We are saved by charis, not by legalism. Yet is that an excuse to do whatever you wish? No, as in the New Testament, everything you do for yourself is sin! It is not denying or disowning yourself, and therefore, you would be unworthy of him. Walk a Godly righteous life, but don&rsquo;t go rebuilding temples to reinitiate sacrifices. It is in my heart that fell and was not rebuilt for a reason. Those sacrifices don&rsquo;t count now the ultimate sacrifice was made. We are to live a selfless, Godly life, doing what he did, saying what he said and so on and not giving homage to an intentionally defunct legal system that you simply can&rsquo;t uphold.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So remember we need to be totally committed, but to God and not the law as if was more than an insufficient temporal candlelight in the darkness, when now we have the Sun (Son).</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Our commitment is to produce the fruit and fulfil the purpose God put in our heart upon or after we commit (truthfully and earnestly) to him.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&#39;charis&#39;, the relationship that legalists hope you never find? </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.8s5pa4e0n24u"><span class="c33 c26 c46">21.16 The change, the transformation, also deserves expansion.</span></h3><p class="c4"><span class="c1">God&#39;s unmerited call and ongoing (somewhat empowering) influence requires human choice and cooperation. As predestined as it is, the merge with free will is evident. As the old saying goes, &ldquo;You can run, &nbsp;but you can&rsquo;t hide&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span>It is primarily an inescapable force, yet again, it&rsquo;s a great wind that will sooner or later blow those chosen into that rushing stream. We have free will and can fight against it, but sooner or later, the force of God, like the force of nature, will win. </span><span class="c58">The dynamic, personal relationship portrayed throughout the NT; that God calls and enables humans to trust and follow. This is the pattern of discipleship.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span>So I hope I have reconciled those seemingly opposing factors of destiny (ABC) and free will (XYZ). I hope in your mind it </span><span class="c31 c26">successfully holds together two major New Testament strands: the absolute priority of God&#39;s grace (unmerited, initiating, enabling) and the necessity of human response (faith, obedience, perseverance). Avoid the error of &quot;cheap grace&quot; and submit to the pervasive call to &quot;continue in the faith&quot; (Col. 1:23), &quot;work out your salvation&quot; (Phil. 2:12), and &quot;run the race&quot; (Heb. 12:1).</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span>Thayer repeatedly stresses that </span><span class="c42">charis</span><span>&nbsp;is not just forgiveness that leaves the person unchanged; it is the power that </span><span class="c17">elevates</span><span>&nbsp;the believer out of the dominion of sin into the realm of righteousness, life, and the Spirit (Rom 5:17, 21; 6:14; 2 Cor 5:17; Titus 3:5&ndash;7, etc.). </span><span class="c17">Rising above</span><span>&nbsp;the old sphere of sin/flesh/death into the new sphere of righteousness/life/Spirit is extremely common in Paul and in Thayer&rsquo;s exposition of Pauline grace. </span><span class="c17">The upward movement out of sin into a higher order of goodness and life</span><span>&nbsp;is an elevating, sphere-shifting character of </span><span class="c42">charis</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;that Thayer constantly highlights.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c11"><span class="c31 c26">Grace accomplishes what rules alone could not: the real change of a person&#39;s heart. This is shown as both a divine act and a human cooperation. Paul describes it as &quot;putting away the old person&quot; and &quot;putting on the new person&quot; (Ephesians 4:22-24, NLV). This change follows a clear pattern&mdash;rising above sin to live by the fruit of the Spirit: &quot;But the fruit of the Spirit is love, joy, peace, not giving up, being kind, being good, having faith, being gentle, and being the boss over our own desires&quot; (Galatians 5:22-23, NLV). Each good quality replaces a bad one: love pushes out hatred, joy pushes out bitterness, and peace overcomes worry. This rising above is grace in action&mdash;unmerited divine power lifting us from sin&#39;s weight to spiritual freedom.</span></p><p class="c4 c11 c10"><span class="c31 c26"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c44">Change as fast as you can comprehend what God is teaching, &nbsp;as fast as you can learn where and what you need to be in God. Long for the change, too many want the salvation but have no desire for the crucial change. If you give God the choice between salvation and change, he would change you rather than save you. His intent is for that relationship to abound. For this, he needs that change, as sin in our lives is keeping his presence away. He can&rsquo;t share a relationship with sin, it is his enemy.</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.m2vjtl6mjlbl"><span>21.17 </span><span>Expect the unexpected</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I can tell you of some things to expect, yet I can&rsquo;t know the journey you will take. It&rsquo;s like telling you what it&rsquo;s like to be on board a ship, yet many ships made that journey, and each was different due to size, crews and the like. Then there were many other factors like storms and other individual attributes to each person&#39;s voyage, such as their likelihood of seasickness, or if they spent more time on deck or below, etc. All our voyages are different, so expect the unexpected, yet there are a few things that will be similar. They are all voyages on water, so all ships roll to varying degrees, the journeys take time, so there will be unpleasant weather at times, and all journeys have ports along the way, where you may be tempted to get off. So, as I&rsquo;ve mentioned, the expected lets look at the unexpected.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are things I can&rsquo;t explain, that which I simply don&rsquo;t have words for, or that any words fall short of describing. Such as the exact way charis comes about, how you know it&rsquo;s god or how it feels physically or emotionally. All I can do is give a very vague picture. Like trying to look at the world outside through a stained glass window, some light will come through, and you may be able to notice some shapes through the most clear parts, but what you will mostly see is the picture in the window itself. You may get an idea of God and Godliness from what I say, but you need to go outside and look for yourself to gain a clear picture. As even the most brilliant wordsmith will fall short.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Expect to see the world and life in a different way, to see the value God offers. Expect to learn regularly, and I hope, constantly if you get your mindset right and relationship right.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Expect to learn only what you want to learn if you don&rsquo;t. Yet if you do actually submit rather than simply act like you have, then expect revelation and change. Whatever you do or don&rsquo;t do, expect challenges, sometimes even trouble or temptation, as no matter how deep you get in relationship with God, they will exist and be likely to encounter.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Expect that which I can not explain, and as I can&rsquo;t know your individual journey, expect what I haven&rsquo;t even considered. I know there will be unexpected things; everyone who gets even close to walking a Godly life seems to have encountered things they didn&rsquo;t expect.</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.lkvgh8j5l6ra"><span>21.18 </span><span>The Wow factor (Boom)</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There may be some who have an understanding of this, who have a deep relationship with God and know much of what I&rsquo;ve said. Yet, I&rsquo;ve spoken to many people about this, including ministers who all explained Grace as &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;, as that&rsquo;s all they knew. I even saw a very famous TV Pastor who is among the most popular in the world (maybe even the foremost in teaching the Greek words)... yet he, too, explained it merely as &ldquo;unmerited favour&rdquo;. So I earnestly expect this is news to most of you.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">On the other hand. I suppose that for many people, this book won&rsquo;t change their understanding of God, Godliness, who they are in God, or who they need to become. They may never come to the understanding that they may be perceiving &ldquo;relationship with God&rdquo; as something other than their current relationship (which may in no way be what God seeks). There will be some others who will have a Wow moment somewhere in this revelation, yet they will not endeavour to implement much change due to it. They will simply think Wow, that&rsquo;s interesting, and continue to live as they were. Others will also discover something new here (an old fact, but now they can understand it). They will seek to make changes, but for some reason, life will get in the way, and they will fall back to their old habits. There will also be a few, like the parable of the sower, where this falls on good ground. They will also have a Wow moment and seek to implement change. When an opportunity arises to distract them from their new Godly attitude and lifestyle, they will quickly notice and seek to restore the relationship with God and their neighbour (the unsaved world, etc.).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How do I know this? Why am I saying this? I have experienced it. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.19 My discovery</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">When I started to research Charis, I had a Wow moment. At that stage, I&rsquo;d only read Strong&#39;s description. I began to live and act a little differently. God then pushed me on to discover more (probably due to the respect I&rsquo;d given to his lead and the education he was giving me). I was led to Thayer&rsquo;s description, WOW! I thought Strong had a massive point and Christianity could be prestructured back upon it (prestructured, my word for returning to the original structure of Christianity *a backwards restructure). There have been many times I&rsquo;ve had my mind blown by these descriptions upon my contemplation of them. By the way, most things in life to me are &ldquo;yeah, yeah, same old, same old.&rdquo;. It takes an extreme amount to blow my mind. Those were the 2 biggest brain meltdowns I&rsquo;d had in a very long time. Yet I&rsquo;ve had quite a few minor wow moments in this whole process of learning.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, I pray my few insufficient words have helped you to see what I&rsquo;ve seen. No matter how I word what my mind seeks to express, the words and images I read, after I&rsquo;ve written them, seem so very insufficient.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.20 Total surrender</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Christianity isn&rsquo;t just the part of your life that you give to God, not a day on the weekend and a few hours of prayer and Bible reading through the week. It&#39;s not even giving a lot of time to the pursuit of Godliness. In fact, it&rsquo;s not pursuing Godliness at all. It&rsquo;s merely having a relationship with God that lets him have control of your life and full place in your heart. No, you at all&hellip; No ego, no pride, no need for things, or entertainment or friends (yes, I said friends). No need for anything but God and the desires he puts in your heart. If you desire things of this world, they are not the desires he has placed there. I know that all I want from life is 1/ to know him better (have him advance my relationship with him) 2/ Do what he asks to see the world gain a wonderful relationship with him, 3/ for you to know God better 4/ For you to have similar desires for God and Gods work and 5/ for the unsaved to discover all these wonderful things from a life in God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I can see as I type this, I won&rsquo;t be satisfied with the meagre words I use to persuade you, and yes, I seek to have you screaming &ldquo;I want this too&rdquo;. I want you to understand what I am not qualified to present. I&rsquo;m writing books on this, as I conceive a need, as I have never been told these things. Yet when I think of them, my mind is overwhelmed, so I apologise for my lack of delivery ability. I&rsquo;ll just put it this way for now: if you understand, God becomes all you want and all you want to express, you want to turn every conversation to God.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">21.21 Letting go of self</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I took a break recently and didn&rsquo;t have my mind on God the majority of the time as I focused on entertainment. One week feels like I&rsquo;ve gone backward many months in my relationship with God. I wonder if it was God&#39;s plan so I could see how difficult it is to get into a mindset where God is on your mind more than not. Where you just want more time every day to spend in prayer, in reading the word, in teaching others to improve their relations with God and to share the wonders of God with the unsaved who have no concept at all. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">God will move you to that position where your focus is on almost nothing but him&hellip; if you let him! You must want that. God will not do anything against your will; He will encourage you toward that change of mindset, but not force you. It&rsquo;s up to you to be willing, to want God to put you in that place. He calls an elect, but coaxes them and doesn&rsquo;t force them, yet at the same time, it&rsquo;s an irresistible coaxing. Resisting God when he calls is like swimming upriver; you&rsquo;re swimming against the flow. It&rsquo;s not impossible, and he will let you do that, but sooner or later, you&rsquo;ll give in to his call. This is not a bad thing, though, as the other end is his ocean of love. All those who never enter the water will never know the wonders of God. I hope these verbal images help. It&rsquo;s simply an amazing thing to understand the relationship with God, its compelling power and beauty. You won&rsquo;t understand the underlying current of that river and the enormity of the ocean of God&#39;s love till you take that step of faith and step in. Till you give up on your ego, pride, desires, wants, and your self. As I often say, there&rsquo;s only enough room in your heart for you or God; you choose which one.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">God calls us to let go of self, to glorify him, and when you let go, nothing about YOU matters; there is no longer room for pride, etc. It&rsquo;s the reason I don&rsquo;t want to use my name on this book. That is not giving 100% glory to God. It&rsquo;s reserving 1% glory for yourself (Your ego, your pride, you). If these are my words, then I give them away for nothing (no fame, no money *no proceeds go to me **if the books are not free!). I&rsquo;m putting my time and effort in this to glorify God alone. I can only share this comprehension he gave me. It&rsquo;s a Wow moment when it clicks into place (and I hope it has for you). There are a few wow moments in my experience with this, as there seems to be more revealed to me all the time.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So let go (of your self, your power, your needs, your ego, your whatever). If you haven&rsquo;t asked God into your life, do so. But I hope you have already. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">21.22 Insufficient words</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Though I expect not, there is also the chance that this may not be new to you. That you were aware of all these factors and may even know things about charis, metanoeo and rhema that would also blow my mind. After all, I just watched someone preach about something, and I don&rsquo;t recall their exact words, like &ldquo;this will be amazing&rdquo; or something that indicated to me that they thought people would receive it as a major new revelation. As I watched, my scepticism grew, with every overexaggerated word and highly sanguine expression delivering no more than a rather average message, along the lines of many I&rsquo;ve heard.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Firstly, I sincerely hope I have not been doing that; considering it superior from who it&rsquo;s coming from and how I&rsquo;m delivering it. To me, it has been a real discovery that I believe is rare (and precious). Secondly, it may also be something new, yet no more than novel and not of the value I see, yet I expect this is not the case, that there is real enlightenment to be had here. I just hope I&rsquo;ve put these things in ways that bring clarity to you, and you also &ldquo;think differently&rdquo; because of them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">A person mentioned &ldquo;... bilingual&hellip;&rdquo; in the middle of a sentence today, and I instantly thought, I&rsquo;m not bilingual, I&rsquo;m TRYlingual, I try to put concepts into language. I try to explain what I find rather difficult to put into words; I ask you, as your part, to try to see beyond my simple words.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you see what I&rsquo;m poorly wording, you will see the vast nature of it. It&rsquo;s like looking into the night sky; it goes far beyond what we see, and we all see different parts of it depending on where we are on the planet and which direction we are looking from that point. Yet I know there is far more in the distance that can&rsquo;t even be seen by the naked eye, and can be revealed by telescopes; it is more than we see.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Thousands of words to describe just one, and yet this book is metaphorically merely looking up at one part of the immense night sky. Here&rsquo;s the wow factor, one other way; all these words can&rsquo;t describe a day in living it, certainly not when deep into that voyage.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I keep coming back to this section, wishing to find better ways to express the feeling of insufficiency in my words. At best, all I can say is I, too, am learning as I type. Things that may easily be fobbed off as nothing intrigue me as to the cause of that fobbing? I know this will happen for multiple reasons, a desire by opponents for this information to not carry truth is a major one. Yet I see my insufficient attempt to build an understanding of the relationship, the way God expresses things to us, and the emotions included that are somewhat beyond words. I am blown away and hope I have shared the awe a little.</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.3bvsrrv84is3"><span>22 </span><span class="c29 c26">That nudge inside</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c17">22.1 Discernment</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Though we can expect the unexpected, there is a common vain which runs through those who have submitted and grown in understanding from that submission and commitment to learn and grow. Again, can I say exactly how it feels, no, nor may you feel it in the same way, but in knowing God, you come to learn when God is moving you to something. I will not say, telling you something as some people say &ldquo;God told me&hellip;.&rdquo; I am more suspicious that the more confident they are, and the closer they seem to define it as actual words rather than a sense or feeling. I&rsquo;m rather suspicious of anyone who implies the heard the audible voice of God, yet it has happened in history and is not beyond possibility, merely rather improbable.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If someone makes a bold declaration that God told them in an audible voice of even in a message in their heart that was so clear it may have well have been in exact words, or that they relay it as exact words, my suspicion rings alarms. Fake prophets usually declare a direct communication on a level where they hear God in specific words. I don&rsquo;t know of all circumstances, yet I have come across the &ldquo;God told me&hellip;&rdquo; types of people and what they then say is often ungodly, or there are other indications of potential issues like blatant sin in their lives.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Yet, for those who describe it as a nudge inside, we are more likely, in my experience, to find a person who is heading in a Godly direction. Note: I didn&rsquo;t say walking a Godly life, as it seems to me that even the best of us have so much further to go. It&rsquo;s more of a peace about things that God wants, or a disturbance with things that are out of God&#39;s will.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">22.2 Learning to hear</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">They certainly have a sense; however, they describe it. Can I explain the feeling of wind, or being wet? No, but if you have felt those, you know what I mean. It&rsquo;s like explaining colour to someone born totally blind. We can only give a vague idea of shading. We cannot explain the difference between red and blue, no, but can we explain that some colours are brighter and more vibrant than others, a little bit, as we can relate vibrance to other things, like when looking at colour, bright colours often bring happiness, and the more dull or colourless (grey) ones can bring your mood down more. Not that colour is emotion, but as they can&rsquo;t see, we can only describe what they do know; emotion. So a long way to a short point (sorry for those who &ldquo;got it&rdquo; straight away).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Most people describe an internal feeling, and often in or upon the heart. We may not know exactly what god wants, but we get an idea that where we&rsquo;re heading is right or wrong.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you sense it&rsquo;s wrong don&rsquo;t be afraid to change direction, if that change may disrupt others 1/ explain and 2/ help them in transition or 3/ find a replacement for yourself if that thing is Godly (like you have been evangelising with another and now it&rsquo;s time to train up a third or move to another region) find someone else to go with them, as it&rsquo;s a Godly venture.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>There may be a hint in learning to know it. I can&rsquo;t say this will work, but if your heart is in the right place, you have sought God fill your heart and </span><span class="c46">push you out to &ldquo;disown&rdquo; yourself</span><span class="c1">. When things happen, in actions or what people say, notice what is happening or being said. And if you have been learning to discern, which isn&rsquo;t hard if you are not ignorant to it. Assess what you feel when the action or words are not Godly and what you feel when they are. In doing so, you will likely notice those feelings more often and upon further investigation, you should be able to confirm if it was from God or not.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I have known some people who had a good idea of what God wanted, and one who was spot on, a prophet whose words always seemed to come true. I can&rsquo;t say I recall this exactly, as it was nearly 30 years ago. But by recollection, I think he mentioned waiting on God as practising hearing from God. In my experience, I have come to believe there is a developmental side. What I suggest due to that is in the early stages of learning to hear from God, use a fleece (XXXX scripture)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&rsquo;s Ok to seek confirmation in the early days, though I&rsquo;d expect you grow beyond that need too. Lastly here, that nudge starts even before the commitment, nudging you towards that commitment to start with.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.mq44ob5sdkgb"><span>22.3 The holding factor </span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c1">(Mr X falls if there is no heaven, it&rsquo;s not relevant to me)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In the words of John Lennon</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Imagine there&rsquo;s no heaven, it&rsquo;s easy if you try&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The evangelist &nbsp;Mr X&rsquo;s argument falls apart. He needs a heaven and hell for any value to his point, as they are his foundation.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Like I said about the cross early in this book. &ldquo;We are not saved by the cross, we are saved by Grace because of it.&rdquo; Again, I&rsquo;m going to make a potentially controversial statement. I don&rsquo;t like to soften these statements, as the controversial sound to them also makes them memorable. Again, I&rsquo;ll state, to read it carefully, as you&rsquo;ll find it both true and valuable.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">22.4 Why the wager still helps</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let&#39;s do what John Lennon suggested. Imagine there&#39;s no Heaven or Hell. Mr X has no case at all. My case and the whole premise of this/these book/s gains strength, as now people who believe in these but have no real relationship with God must think again. In which case, Mr X may as well be walking around saying to people, &ldquo;Hi, can I introduce you to Santa Claus?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What happens with my case? Those who believed in an afterlife are now just lost. No direction, no hope, nothing. That includes those who say their Chrisians but have no real relationship with God and people of other religions who believe in an afterlife or those who believe in an afterlife but don&rsquo;t believe in God, just in being good.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">They are all then lost in direction and personal value; they would probably lose morals as well. It would be far more troublesome than it is now. Yet I still have a strong case, in fact, even stronger. Now, instead of living to work your way to heaven (as most believe it is themselves being good that works their way there). By choosing to have faith in God. Again, as per Ephesians 2:8, &ldquo;We are saved by grace through faith&hellip;&rdquo; Not evidence, not fact, not anything else but faith (a choice to believe). Then I promote by making this choice to first believe and then by acting in accordance with that belief, you will grow to discover the reality of God (after the choice to believe), and you will gain those wonderful traits; the fruits of the spirit, wisdom, discernment, as well as family and importantly for many people, purpose.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You gain all those good things growing within. Of course, I&rsquo;m not saying your external environment will change. Not at least till you change and affect that environment. In many cases that affect won&rsquo;t help anyway. But, if you have taken on those qualities and Spiritual fruits, who cares about the external! You will be learning to cope from the internal strength gained and so on.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Everything to gain and nothing to lose&hellip; Yes. Now let&#39;s look at Pascal&#39;s wager, as there is a small potential loss there, that I&rsquo;ll show isn&rsquo;t really a loss either.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Pascal&#39;s Wager is a pragmatic argument from 17th-century philosopher Blaise Pascal, suggesting belief in God is the rational choice due to the potential outcomes. It frames life as a gamble where reason can&#39;t prove God&#39;s existence, so one weighs infinite rewards against finite costs</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h2 class="c25" id="h.j5wkbwuhu0xs"><span class="c44 c17 c77">22.5 Holding and perseverance</span></h2><p class="c71"><span class="c1">Pascal argues you must &quot;wager&quot; on God&#39;s existence or non-existence, as neutrality isn&#39;t possible&mdash;you live as if one or the other is true. Believing costs little (e.g., forgoing some pleasures) but gains eternity in heaven if God exists; disbelieving risks eternal hell if wrong, with minimal upside if God doesn&#39;t exist.</span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.klbyrojwx4h6"><span class="c33 c26">Decision Matrix</span></h3><p class="c71"><span class="c1">Pascal&#39;s idea is often shown in a payoff table:</span></p><table class="c78"><tr class="c79"><td class="c90" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c17">Choice</span></p></td><td class="c49" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c17">God Exists</span></p></td><td class="c53" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c17">God Does Not Exist</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c79"><td class="c87" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c1">Believe</span></p></td><td class="c70" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c1">+&infin; (heaven)</span></p></td><td class="c27" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c1">-c (finite loss)</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c72"><td class="c60" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c1">Disbelieve</span></p></td><td class="c76" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c1">-&infin; (hell)</span></p></td><td class="c64" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c43"><span class="c1">+c (finite gain)</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">22.6 Pascal&rsquo;s wager explained</span></p><p class="c2"><span>Expected value favours belief, as even a tiny chance of God existing yields infinite upside.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Pascal implies that if there is no God and you believe there is, you lose minor pleasures, and if there is no God and you don&rsquo;t believe, then you maintain those minor pleasures. Firstly, you don&rsquo;t gain more of those minor pleasures by not believing; you just maintain what you have.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But those minor pleasures come with their own costs and trouble that make them more unappealing than they seem at first glance. Sure, the non-Christian can have the pleasure to be a drunkard&hellip; But the penalty for that is a hangover in the morning, and it can become an addiction that costs money for the alcohol, when you may want to give up, it&rsquo;s problematic. Then the costs can run far higher. Get drunk, drive a car, smash it, and you&rsquo;ll be up for a ton of money (sorrow). That&rsquo;s just alcohol. Other drugs are the same, costs, addictions, and danger from a lack of control. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What about other pleasures&hellip; for example, sex? Christians believe in the sanctity of marriage, one partner. Non-Christians have sex with many and spread sexual diseases&hellip; more trouble, and potentially a shortened life </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">22.7 The real cost of unbelief</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What about other non-Christian pleasures, like driving fast vehicles? OK, I&rsquo;ve done that, I&rsquo;ve ridden a bike at about 300kph, about 186mph (when backsliding). I say &ldquo;about&rdquo;, as the speedo got to about 280kph but was incorrect by about 10% under the actual speed due to the use of incorrect sprockets (the cogs the drive chain is on), So I would have proably exceeded 300kph (308? At one stage it was checked with cellphones speed app, and was 110 on the app, when showing 100 on the speedo). A real thrill, the thrill of power and speed, and yet, subconsciously, there is also a slight thrill of dicing with death and surviving. Yes, the chance of death is a very real thing, so as a Christian, you should not take that risk. We are not to take our lives that loosely for pleasure&#39;s sake, even on a race track where it&rsquo;s legal (unless you are a well-trained professional, and then I still have my doubts).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You name the pleasure. I can probably think of a downfall for it!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So Pascal&#39;s wager in reality 2 possibilities if there is a God: believe and commit honestly, there is a great reward, or don&rsquo;t believe or commit honestly, and the cost is devastating. Then the 2 possibilities if there is no God: believe and commit honestly, there are still rewards in those fruits (which also can make your life and relationships better, etc.), or don&rsquo;t believe or commit honestly and gain a few temporal pleasures that have major downfalls and the cost is usually worse than the pleasure and can also be devastating.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In fact Pascals wager can be brought down to Heaven (Paradise) and Hell. If they do or do not exist, I still win, by the constant joy and other bonuses I have. By the way, I can lose that joy (temporarily), I can spend a lot of time in selfish entertainment or the like, and walk away from that feeling somewhat down, like I&rsquo;d lost something&hellip; yes, I had, the focus on myself (MY entertainment, especially over a prolonged period), brings a dissatisfaction, the dissatisfaction of having wasted time.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The solution? Get into God, honestly, not kidding yourself by holding onto your own desires, what you think are your needs, etc. Discover that real charis and don&rsquo;t let go!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Even &nbsp;Pascal </span><span class="c1">addressed unbelief by advising those who lack genuine faith to take practical steps toward belief, as habit and action shape the heart over time. In human nature, repeated actions persuade the mind. Pascal considered that custom bends our inclinations permanently -belief follows behaviour. Renouncing passions that block faith, practising Christian virtues, and trusting God to grant true faith eventually.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">22.8 Grace as the holding factor</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How can what I&rsquo;ve just delivered be a holding factor? It&rsquo;s &ldquo;keeps&rdquo; in Thayer&#39;s description.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">My relationship with God keeps me, it holds me and stops me from straying, as if there were no other factor to maintain my stance, my faith, such as heaven and hell. Then I am unmoved, kept by God and gain continuously through my growth with him.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let&rsquo;s look at Php_2:12 &nbsp;&ldquo;Wherefore, my beloved, as ye have always obeyed, not as in my presence only, but now much more in my absence, work out your own salvation with fear and trembling.&rdquo; Obedience when alone is valid, yet here I want to focus on the finish. Of the verse and of your journey. &ldquo;Work out your own salvation&hellip;&rdquo; means to assess it, though in the modern world, a &ldquo;Work out&rdquo; also means to exercise, which is appropriate in itself. Don&rsquo;t just assess it, exercise it, live it. Do so &ldquo;with fear and trembling.&rdquo; That has diminished in meaning over time. Do will still understand its tone?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">When we apply the deep thought and concern which that part of the verse seeks, we are not being afraid of a tenuous, fragile salvation or tremble due to an indecisive God. Not at all. We treat our salvation like a power outlet in a wall. It&rsquo;s a good thing that will produce an indescribable, wonderful result when you plug into it. Yet remember it&rsquo;s not a powerless point, the power it gives needs care as well. Don&rsquo;t plug in frayed cords or wet plugs, as that power is to be treated with great respect. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Let God &ldquo;keep&ldquo; you till the end, don&rsquo;t be satisfied with where you&rsquo;re at and stagnate, always move on towards that &ldquo;finish line&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17 c46 c52">23</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.sdw2rq2xhtot"><span class="c46">How we position ourselves.</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">23.1 Minute men and readiness</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">In the continental war (the US war of independence). There were guerrilla combatants known as the militia. A group of them were known as The Minute Men, as they could get ready for battle at a minute&#39;s notice (grab their gun and run to battle).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The Bible mentions warfare and in the New Testament, spiritual warfare, though I&rsquo;d like to take the concept further, as the idea of guerrilla, partisans or militia didn&rsquo;t exist in biblical times, as often a soldier was identified merely as one with a weapon or armour or the like, excepting formal armies like the Romans.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;m not going to focus on the spiritual warfare, but on action as a civilian. I certainly do not suggest any form of actual physical conflict either. But the desire, preparation, and readiness of the Christian militia. I&rsquo;m now talking about you and me, rather than official ministers (the regulars, as it were). I am not, at least as I type this in an official ordained role. I am, however, organising a militia of Christian civilians in illustrative terms.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The fight is not against flesh and blood&hellip; OK, sure, but we are leaning into spiritual warfare upon this thought. I&rsquo;m not talking of that either. More a battle of wits and no, I&rsquo;m not presenting the idea of winning an argument either, but winning souls. We certainly don&rsquo;t want to &ldquo;win the battle but lose the war&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">23.2</span><span class="c32 c17">&nbsp;What a Yeshuan is</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">First, we are all subject to this fight. Every Yeshuan is called to show their light, bare thier cross, make disciples, and this one relates to &ldquo;fight the good fight&rdquo;. It is not optional; it is a core element of what a Yeshuan is. The pumping heart, without which the body is dead! Without which we are not emulating Christ and therefore not a real disciple.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There is more to Yeshuan life than this, though this is like a soldier putting their uniform on. It is one thing all soldiers do and a crucial part of their identification, as we are known by our fruit. People are called to differing gifts and differing roles, just like an army, in which they are identified by different insignia, but all have the same base uniform. Our uniform is evangelical, sure, there may be some variations to that too, but everyone is called to spread God in both word and deed.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Even minute men are trained in regular techniques, weaponry and battle formation, etc. We need to be ready to give an answer for the hope&hellip;Everyone should have basic training. Biblically, it&rsquo;s called discipleship, how to be a Christian, not just a churchian, not just knowing the basics, the need to have love, joy, etc., but skills of evangelism, not just ready to give an answer, but how to answer (what answer). More than answer, however, our Lord initiated many conversations and seemed to turn every conversation to God and or Godliness.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So what is the training? I&rsquo;ll be blunt. I&rsquo;m not sure! Do I have an efficient teachable method? No, not yet anyway, not as I type this. Though, as mentioned earlier, 1/ this book is written a bit here, and a bit there, this part is after the part where I said I&rsquo;d just discovered a week ago the 100% constant evangelism Yeshua seemed to display. (as this part should come later, and that part was earlier, many pages away, but the same day).</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Still, I have led maybe a couple of dozen people to God in my life, not many, though, as I have mentioned, I have also only just come back a year ago after 23 years of backsliding. Still, does that disqualify me from delivering this? Remember, God will use a donkey if need be. I know people seeking to develop standardised evangelistic formats and training.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Why standardised? Isn&rsquo;t the Holy Spirit&#39;s lead better and certainly more Godly? Yes, sure, however, what happens then is we send people out without experience, and they fear going out, they lack confidence, and most people aren&rsquo;t very good at listening to God&hellip; shooting off their gun in any direction isn&rsquo;t likely to get good results and more likely to hurt your forces. Yes, you can hurt your side. Poor evangelism can turn people off and tar all other &ldquo;Christians&rdquo; with the same brush. Please don&rsquo;t enter battle till you have been trained.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">23.3 Trained to fish</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So we get trained and are ready for battle. Now it&rsquo;s no longer a battle but a fishing trip. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Before I explain this, it&rsquo;s back to the base point momentarily. What is the result of charis? Christian virtues, fruit of the spirit, and as Dr Strong put it, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s reflection in the life&rdquo; God in you so much that 1/ it&rsquo;s wonderful and 2/ it&rsquo;s those wonderful things coming out! OK, got that.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So how do you fish? The ancient method was to throw a spear into the water, which still happens in some remote tribal areas of this world. But what is most common, due to the probability of better results? Angleing, putting a worm on a hook on a line on a fishing rod!</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Why? Attracting a fish with what they see as desirable is far better and easier than trying to kill them instantly and painfully with a spear. In most cases, a spear thrown into the water scares most fish away. The worm attracts the fish; it&rsquo;s the food they need, so let&#39;s find and show how God meets their needs. That&rsquo;s another book entirely, but as we approach the end of this book, I expect I&rsquo;ve covered a lot of that here.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What do you do once you&rsquo;ve caught that fish? There is a lot of hobby fishing in this world. People do so on TV shows, purely about the thrill of the catch. They just throw the fish back in the water. Here&rsquo;s a major issue with the church. The great majority of evangelists are hobby fishers. Let&rsquo;s get you to a sinner&#39;s prayer and toss you back. Oh no. Not on my watch!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How dare you glory in (oh yes, another issue is that many evangelists glory in what they do), catching fish and dare to toss them back. &ldquo;Oh, you&rsquo;ve said a sinner&#39;s prayer, I&rsquo;ve done my job, now go find yourself a church&hellip;&rdquo; Many won&rsquo;t even go as far as to suggest the convert find a church, merely &ldquo;goodbye&rdquo;. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">23.4 The gospels&rsquo; angles</span></p><p class="c2"><span>Now, I&rsquo;m going into the gospels for a moment. John never mentioned the great commission; the other three did, but from their own perspectives. Luke was a doctor in </span><span class="c32 c26">Colossians 4:14. Paul calls him &quot;the beloved physician.&quot; Mark, a scribe who could translate multiple languages, so he was also highly educated, and Matthew was a humble tax collector. Yes, humble as to his reference, Yeshua calling a tax collector, not even elevating himself to &ldquo;Jesus called me&rdquo;<br></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">Let&rsquo;s look at those Mark focused on; preach to EVERY creature, salvation Vs damnation, and wondrous signs; powers in expression like a writer would</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">Luke, as a doctor, focused on the physical evidence, then simplicity of directives, like a doctor writing a script, minimalistic</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">Now Matthew, a tax collector, who needs to get it right a man of duty and structured focus, emphasising disciple-making, baptism, and obedience.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">Should we focus on the wonders that make the story impressive? Or doing nothing more than the basic job? Or I&rsquo;d like to suggest getting it right! Like a government official. I too will focus on an important aspect he too could not forget, being the man of duty among them.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">Mat 28:19 &nbsp;having gone, then, disciple all the nations, immersing them into the Name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit, </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">Mat 28:20 &nbsp;teaching them to observe all, whatever I commanded you, and behold, I am with you all the days&mdash;until the full end of the age.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">&ldquo;Disciple all the nations&rdquo; and &ldquo;Teaching them&rdquo; - the job isn&rsquo;t over with amen at the end of a sinner&#39;s prayer, it has really just begun. Teach them or make sure they are being taught. If you or they are not local, find them a church and check up on occasion.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">We are fishers of men and shepherds in one; there is a symbol of a hook on a crook that I like, implying this and a few other things, though there is also a saying &ldquo;by hook or by crook&rdquo; which came from legal means of collecting firewood in medieval England. There was a law that you could collect any dead wood in the king&#39;s forest that you could drag down from a tree by a billhook (a pruning hook) or a shepherd&#39;s crook, as cutting the trees was illegal. So originally by any legal means.<br><br>There is a standard to be had there. Reach the lost by all effort at any ethical means. Yeshua said in Mark 1:38 &quot;Let&#39;s go to the neighbouring town,&quot; he replied, &quot;so I can preach there, too, because that&#39;s why I came.&quot; (ISV). He was not just a sacrifice; he had a greater purpose and some supplementary actions. His purpose, even before sacrifice, was to express the gospel, to preach the good news&hellip; To EVERYONE. I don&rsquo;t know of anywhere he didn&rsquo;t turn the message to God or Godliness.<br></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c26">There are times when doing so would be inappropriate, for example, let&#39;s keep air traffic control messages to direction and safety. Yet when pouring a drink in the kitchen of the control tower, can we discuss God? Sure, any time you are not required to focus on a particular thing, turn the message to God!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c32 c26"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c32 c17">23.5 Ready for battle</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&nbsp;Are you ready to sign up for God&#39;s army, to be well prepared and ready at a minute&#39;s notice? To open a conversation at that acquisition point (no longer a well, but a checkout in our modern world)? I&rsquo;m not asking if you are prepared; it&rsquo;s too early at this stage. Are you ready to enlist for that training? At the end of this book, I&rsquo;ll add some contact information for a training organisation, ready to teach you for free. God&#39;s work is a duty, not a business.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Seek to be self-aware, know your intentions and dedicate to prayer. preparation, getting your life right and stepping out into your call. OK, so you like everyone know who you are, you&rsquo;re self-aware&hellip; Please think again, we think we know ourselves, and we often think we know ourselves better than anyone. Yet many people are fooling themselves with a distorted self-image. Have you ever met a person who everyone says is nasty, and when you meet them, yes, you find them trashing others or the like? Ask that person how they see themselves, chances are they will say things like, &ldquo;kind and loving&rdquo;. Do people with issues see themselves as the issue or others who cause all their issues? The great majority will blame others for things they have a large part of the fault in, if not totally caused by themselves.<br><br>It is very rare that a person can see their faults; most of us see ourselves as wonderful. Stop right there. You may be OK, but that&rsquo;s not the point. The point is, chances are you are not quite how you see yourself, and it can even work the other way. There are even the rare few who think they are worse than what they really are. Or even our trait perception can be off, we can think we are people-oriented when we are task-oriented and so on.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Get to know the real you and prepare for God to move, by time in prayer, the Bible, Godly thought and action. Be ready to change and more so, eager to change and not into what you think is Godly, but what Biblically is. Again, here is where you need more than charis, but charisepignosis.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You may find it an interesting study to find out more about self-awareness. Think of this: find someone that seems to have some negative traits, ask people what that person is like and then ask them, it&rsquo;s highly likely they will paint themselves in nice words, where others won&rsquo;t. Now, I won&rsquo;t say Try that, as it would be gossip (sin). But to ask others what you could improve in your life may help.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There would be a few other tips that would help, but as I don&rsquo;t know of many, no one has even taught me of these things, so I wouldn&rsquo;t know where to look for more. I pray we all learn to apply charisepignosis and help each other, develop these early initial urges (thoughts from God), into a working ministry and growth system.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">However, I propose here a big asset in this is the ability and choice to walk in Godly thought and action. Keep God, Godliness and Godly things on your mind as often as you are able. Be willing to look a little deeper as well, especially into scripture XXX &ldquo;rightly dividing the word&rdquo;. How? Simple; do what I did, don&rsquo;t just look at a word and go on unless it&#39;s a simple word. Go to the reference books, Strongs, Thayers and even dare I say it, don&rsquo;t trash me on this till you hear me out&hellip; use AI.<br><br>I guess a lot of people have read the last sentence and not this one, as they&rsquo;ve just thrown this book out. I&rsquo;ve said a few things that are controversial, and each time, more will have stopped reading. I admit, as demonic as many present it as I use AI to simplify things, I will ask it to find verses on one subject or another that I suspect may not be found by a particular word. If I thought I&rsquo;d find verses by a word, I&rsquo;d do a lexicon search. But can you find verses on, let&#39;s say, &ldquo;badmouthing a person&rdquo; if you can&rsquo;t think of the Biblical term (slander)? AI will.<br><br>That&rsquo;s one way I use it, but this helps too. I will present my ideas on a Christian subject like free will and predestination, and ask it to review and rate my stance. By the way, initially it was my position on free will, because I hadn&rsquo;t thought about the scriptures on predestination, and it was AI that alerted me to them&hellip; useful!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Why not have AI challenge your beliefs? It has helped from some of this book. Also, I will feed this draft into AI once finished and ask it to notify me on any repetition, poor wording or unclear ideas etc. to help me revise the draft before completion.<br><br>OK, so if AI is of the devil, and yes, I see AI video and forgery as such, etc., then what is of the devil, the tool AI or the person who wanted to create a fallacy? Personally, I think it&rsquo;s who uses it and how, as it is a tool, is alcohol a sin or the action of going beyond one drink and getting drunk? After all, Paul even told Timothy - 1Tim 5:23 &nbsp;Stop drinking only water, but use a little wine for your stomach because of your frequent illnesses.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">People are sinners (sin is of the devil), so should I not leave my room ever, as there are sinners out there? I should show them God&#39;s glory! I should use AI for God as well, just maybe limiting it to the research and refinement side. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1 c46"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c29 c17 c46">24</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.qqyu35qmsxeg"><span class="c29 c26">The power and importance of prayer </span></h2><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c7 c11">24.1</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">A regular prayer is good, develop what you want to say to God and ask of him [ask not for yourself but for him and for others, etc.].</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">I include inspire me with a [] waking dream [for growth, both mine and others]</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Why do I want those things I pray for?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c7 c11">24.2 Prayer, trust, and obedience</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Are you trustworthy? Wait, I mean beyond circumstance? This is a valuable thing to understand. Trustworthy isn&rsquo;t saying I&rsquo;ll do X, and when Y gets in the way, you say I couldn&rsquo;t do X because of Y and expect it to be treated as not your fault. It doesn&rsquo;t work that way. The fact that you didn&rsquo;t do what you promised is a lie and shows you are also unreliable and untrustworthy. These are sins. Never make a promise unless you know for a fact 100% that you not only can but will keep it. 99.9999% sure doesn&rsquo;t count!</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">I personally experience this, Christians making promises based on a rather expectant future result. For example, from their next pay&hellip; What of the minimal chance that the business goes bankrupt and you have no next pay? Or the store you work in is burnt down, and there&rsquo;s no work to go to. Unforeseen things are causing rather Christian people, and I mean those who do display a more Godly nature than the average, to fall in this regard.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Am I much better? No!, I do not claim to have it all together; I have issues, not as you are likely to first perceive them, with faithfulness and self-control. I have no wife to be faithful to, so don&rsquo;t assume I&rsquo;m &ldquo;unfaithful&rdquo;, that&rsquo;s not the faithfulness here. It&rsquo;s faithful to God and your word (trustworthy), and those you commit faithfulness to in any way.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">I have said I&rsquo;ll go evangelise, yet when the time came around, I wrote more pages of this book. They are also important in God, and maybe that&rsquo;s what God actually wanted me to do, as some things were on my mind which I justified as a Godly reason, that I could sense that was what God wanted&hellip; yet was it?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Is it possible I used a godly activity as an excuse to not do the stressful thing God calls us all to do? I think we can seek ways to get out of what God calls us to do, and the best excuse is another godly urgent act. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Evangelism is not what I&rsquo;m called to, though 1/ we are all called to it to varying degrees and 2/it is also somewhat within the call I have; a sub ministry of my call.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c7 c11">24.3 Commitment and foundations</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">This book is of a higher need within my call, yet can I spend a few fewer hours on it and go out to spread God? I don&rsquo;t have many hours for this either, as there are many other ministry things being neglected as I write. But this is my highest focus for the time being (over the next month, a few months? While I write this).<br><br>There is an urgency to this. But can I use that as an excuse? I&rsquo;ll say right now, there is certainly that chance, as I get nervous about evangelism like most Christians do. I&rsquo;m not 100% sure, though, as there is also that chance God wanted me to write that day. The same applies to self-control here as it is also a self-control issue. I don&rsquo;t have a self-control issue with things most people see as obvious self-control issues, but what of those extra chocolate biscuits? I find the extra one too difficult to resist. Sure, it&rsquo;s only a chocolate biscuit, and I&rsquo;m not massively overweight; I am a little overweight, so it is proper to resist. OK, it is a self-control issue.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">I&rsquo;m not perfect, I&rsquo;m forgiven&hellip; There, I said it, yes, that old excuse I&rsquo;ve heard so many times in my youth. Fail! That is an excuse, and we are to avoid excuses! So I say instead &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not perfect, I&rsquo;m committed!&rdquo; Now, what do I mean? I&rsquo;m committed to God and Godliness, I&rsquo;m committed to that change and realise it&rsquo;s a process which won&rsquo;t happen overnight, but if I&rsquo;m committed, it&rsquo;s not just some excuse, but a change to enact quickly. I&rsquo;ve given up a few things before, none happened instantly, and Chocolate biscuts won&rsquo;t either; I have a fridge full of them. Nor am I seeking to quit entirely, just the over-indulgence. One a day, not the six a day I was eating a month ago or the two or three I&rsquo;m eating now (as I continue reducing to one a day).</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Am I better than you? No. Am I seeking improvement? Absolutely. Does that in any way disqualify me from writing this book? It may qualify me more, as I&rsquo;ll at least be honest about my status, and I can also present this to you from experience. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">I have come to realise the multiple foundations. Some cities that have ancient history, like Rome for example, have buildings that are not built on foundation rock, but on top of previous buildings. They are founded on something that has its own foundation.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c7 c11">24.4 Foundations and spiritual location</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c11">I have come to realise there are multiple foundations. Some cities with ancient history, like Rome, have buildings that are not built straight onto bedrock but on top of previous buildings. They are founded on something that already has its own foundation. In the same way, there are things I&rsquo;m only just beginning to understand now that I couldn&rsquo;t have seen without the earlier foundations God laid in me &ndash; charis, doulos, metanoeo, </span><span class="c11">epistrepho</span><span class="c1 c11">, and so on. These recent revelations wouldn&rsquo;t jump out at me on their own; they sit on older structures. It really is an upward spiral.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Today, my new perception is that we can be &ldquo;located&rdquo; spiritually by three points, like triangulation on a map. We are located by 1/ our knowledge of the word, 2/ our relationship with God and 3/ our Christlike actions. Our Christlike actions are built on that relationship with God, and they are the higher goal, but they become counterfeit if they are not built on a real relationship. It&rsquo;s what we do, but the &ldquo;why&rdquo; matters&mdash;are we doing it to work our way to heaven or out of love for God (to oversimplify)? That relationship itself needs a foundation in the word.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Some people hit bedrock quickly; they know a little of the word and get their lives right early in their walk. Others just keep digging and digging and never reach the rock. Just because someone claims to be a Christian means very little; do they really have a proper relationship with God? Upon a reasonable working knowledge of the word we can understand God, gain that relationship, and from that relationship we serve in our &ldquo;reasonable service&rdquo;.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">From my recent dealings with legalists, I see how easily a person&rsquo;s focus can drift to the law instead of sharing God. They may know the word very well, but like Pharisees, they cling to law and ignore charis. Are we saved to uphold the Mosaic law, or to live true religion&mdash;caring for the widow and the vulnerable&mdash;and to share the good news, rather than forcing people into our very small box?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c7 c11">24.5 Reality check</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Before I finish with this section, I ask you to earnestly and honestly take a reality check with yourself. </span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Why are there so few on the narrow path? Because we all assume we are on it without checking our obedience and our relationship. If I ask 100 people (professing Christianity), which path are they on? I expect 100 will say &quot;the narrow path&quot;. Yet as there are tares among the wheat, goats among the sheep, etc. This can&#39;t be right. Most people who profess Christianity don&rsquo;t really understand it. After all, both paths are paths of those who believe they are following God. As we also know, the majority are on the wrong path... Then my question is... Are you fooling yourself by assuming you are on the narrow path? (Here&#39;s a hint - the great majority are!).</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Did you just say to yourself, &ldquo;No, I&rsquo;m good, I&rsquo;m living a Godly life&hellip;&rdquo; or something like that? Almost every person will, yet there are still those tares and goats. Remember, these references are to those in the Church, not those outside. So let me ask another way, after all, comprehending grace is important, but having that relationship with God is more important. So if I may ask a few questions&hellip;</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Is your relationship with God constantly growing (you are closer each day)?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Are you learning more about God, Godliness and what&rsquo;s needed to grow as a Christian daily?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Are you constantly walking away from sin (even simple sins like swearing less)?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Are you growing in compulsion to do Godly things (less likely to act on your own desires and more desire to tell everyone you meet about God etc.)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Are you seeking opportunities to turn every conversation to a Godly one (if Yeshua came to spread the gospel, Mark 1:38, are you following in his footsteps)?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">When you are alone, would you rather read your Bible or watch a movie?</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Are there people you speak negatively about (if so, could you simply not mention any issues you have with them, excluding the need to warn others who have some kind of connection with them)?</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">Sure, I spend time on things that are outside Godliness, like watching science documentaries or the news on TV. I only do so when I have finished my day&#39;s work and need to relax and get my mind off that work, so a distraction for an hour or two helps me get to sleep. Also, the less educational the program, the less interesting it is to me, as they not only distract the mind but also distract your walk with God. News and education are not as ungodly as many things on TV; in fact, they are somewhat beneficial, as when discussing God with the lost or even the Church, it is helpful to show a knowledge of the world and that you are not ignorant. They will be able to relate to you more.</span></p><p class="c4 c10"><span class="c1 c11"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1 c11">25</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.lgiz76oe0nvs"><span class="c29 c26">No Disruption </span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c1">(don&rsquo;t allow it *broken routines by distraction or disturbance)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">25.1 Disruption and ripples</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Other than disruption through broken routines, as mentioned in xxx other things can and will cause disturbances. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Any disturbance in your natural life will flow on somewhat to your spiritual life. The degree of flow is not in proportion to the natural disturbance. Some minor disturbance may cause large waves, and sometimes bigger life events may cause only small ripples in your current relationship with God. I say current there as these are temporal ripples or waves. Throw a rock in water, and the waves or ripples it causes will die down. Yet also remember two things here: Is your faith and life in God, a very small paper boat that almost any ripple could sink? Or is it an Ocean liner that even a tidal wave would have trouble sinking?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">25.2 Balance and routines</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The other is, how do we look at those ripples? Do we blow things out of proportion and consider minor issues to be major problems? And we can even go the other way, and choose not to deal with a sin, thinking it&rsquo;s nothing, it&rsquo;s not a sin, just a habit, or just a (whatever). We can minimise issues that should be dealt with and let them go, thinking they are too small to matter. If it&rsquo;s not Godly, chances are it matters&hellip; but don&rsquo;t blow it out of proportion either. Learn the balanced attitude God seeks.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Don&rsquo;t let small ripples sink your ship, or even let massive tidal waves sink your little paper boat. The easiest way is to build strong, regular routines. Also, here on routines, there is an old saying - &nbsp;&ldquo;</span><span>An idle mind is the devil&#39;s workshop.&rdquo;</span><span>&nbsp;Where 2 Thessalonians 3:11 says, &ldquo;We hear that some of you are living in idleness. You are not busy working - you are busy interfering in other people&#39;s lives!&rdquo; If you have little to do, fill your time with Godly training, then with evangelism. Above all, overcome disruptions; they are destructive.</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.t001kq2xtht"><span>25.3 </span><span class="c29 c26">Don&rsquo;t fall</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">There are many NT warnings against apostasy, falling away, and shipwrecking one&#39;s faith (e.g., Heb. 6:4-6, 1 Cor. 10:12). These show that grace isn&rsquo;t fully coercive or guarantees final perseverance irrespective of human choice; otherwise, such warnings would be meaningless. They would not exist.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The need to keep responding is stressed throughout Scripture. Jesus warned about being ready, like the wise bridesmaids who kept oil in their lamps (Matthew 25:1-13). Paul cautioned: &quot;Be careful! If you think you are standing strong, you could fall&quot; (1 Corinthians 10:12, NLV). Yet this warning stands next to a deep promise for those who continue in faith: &quot;I am sure that God, who began the good work in you, will keep on working in you until the day Jesus Christ comes again&quot; (Philippians 1:6, NLV). The God who starts salvation through His unmerited influence will complete it in those who keep walking in that influence.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Many things can cause a fall: disruptions, sin, apathy, and others. Don&rsquo;t jump ship at the slightest disturbance; seek God all the more.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">26 (expand?)</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.fagf781bbwc4"><span class="c29 c26">Prayer - constant *requirements, opportunity for God&#39;s glory *massive, etc</span></h2><p class="c2"><span class="c7">26.1 Prayer practice and challenge</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, be honest with yourself, again, you don&rsquo;t have to tell me, but how often do you pray and in what style?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll first look at the styles of prayer. I guess there are 6. Yes, I said, I guess! Do you think I&rsquo;m an expert on everything? NO! I&rsquo;d expect many people to have studied prayer far more than I have. But I can talk about personal experience and what I know of the Bible here. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Now, before I get into this, what am I an expert in? I have not found a person that I don&rsquo;t have to explain aspects of grace/charis to, even Pastors fall short. But does that make me an expert? Well, I&rsquo;m writing this/these book/s and have looked into it a lot and given many messages on it. Though I seem to be in the early learning stages myself, as there is so much more I seem to keep learning. Of course, that qualifies me to write what I have learned from both my research and my personal experience (how God &ldquo;turns me to Christ&rdquo;). I don&rsquo;t know anyone more qualified. But I don&rsquo;t see myself as an expert. I feel like the first person to ever build a wooden chair, considering myself not an expert carpenter, as I know there will be people who learn from this effort and create better works. Please, I&rsquo;d like to inspire you to step up to that mark. It&rsquo;s not hard, and you can find many people willing to help you step up to whatever call you have (or find it if you don&rsquo;t know yet). If you have had people in ministry say no for some reason or another, consider that they are human and may be trying to protect themselves by saying no.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I didn&rsquo;t even have anyone to ask, as every minister I spoke to had very little idea about this subject, and it is not wise to ask advice or permission from anyone you find yourself teaching. I did, however, ask them for permission to speak to their membership (one-on-one, or however they like) about evangelism, as they are responsible for their church. Alas, no, good responses there either. They seem to want to stick to the two methods of either &ldquo;pray them in&rdquo; or go out to the streets and preach &ldquo;hellfire&rdquo;. Those good old methods, those sort of good very old methods&hellip; Those everyone knows, and are tired of, used up, overused, not very effective ancient methods that they are too afraid or too ignorant to update.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">You know what I&rsquo;ve said, forget the hellfire messages, people want to know how to stop their lives being hell now. We have little idea of how to express that because we (the church as a whole) are only trained up in the ineffective Hellfire messages. It&rsquo;s time to consider modernising and appealing to the modern mindset with modern issues that no one is helping with, but god has the answer, if only people would give real change a chance.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">26.2 Prayer forms and spiritual sensitivity</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Anyway, back to prayer. 6 types, right? 3 audible, 2 in your known language, 1/ formal, e.g., the Lord&#39;s prayer, 2/ informal, e.g., whatever comes to mind and 3/ in tongues. Then we have inaudible prayer in your mind, 4/ formal again, the Lord&#39;s prayer as an example and 5/ informal or random (but rational) words mentally. 6/ I&rsquo;m considering this as an option, in tongues silently. But then, finally, I can think of 7/ Can you guess, or do you know? I can think of one other, another silent prayer&hellip; A prayerful attitude. Here&rsquo;s where God gets a chance to do the talking. It can be conversational and very informal. Like OK God, what do I do about X? And I&rsquo;ll wait for an answer, with, you guessed it, a prayerful attitude while waiting.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I find myself simply thinking of ministry, and things that God puts in my heart, especially after offering a thought like God lead me today. Tell me what you want me to know. A prayerful attitude.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I feel like there is much to be said here, on this subject, yet as I type this, I&rsquo;m approaching the 12-hour mark for today, and I&rsquo;m starting to get tired and making more typos. It&rsquo;s becoming hard to think clearly, and I&rsquo;m likely to shut down now. Yet it&rsquo;s often times like this I go to watch TV, maybe the news for inspiration as news can do that, or maybe something on the Christian channel. However, I find I may have been sitting there an hour or so, regain some energy, and God puts some inspiration in me. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">What am I saying here? God, with me anyway, will wait till I&rsquo;m too tired to concentrate on other tasks like this, before he moves in my heart, producing something in my mind. Does this happen to you? I mean that again, as I said, I certainly am no expert on prayer. God doesn&rsquo;t wait till it&rsquo;s convenient with you, he waits till you&rsquo;ve stopped everything else (tired). </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Here&rsquo;s another: If things go bad, it may or may not be related to your prayer life or how your Christian journey along that narrow path is progressing. If you are making steps, though, be aware of potential trouble. The enemy has no need to attack the weak. They will fall away by their own lack of effort. I just got a phone call minutes ago. It wasn&rsquo;t very bad, but I could see the potential for it to trap me. I could see a con, not because I&rsquo;m an expert in cons, but because alarm bells started ringing inside. &nbsp;I had been trapped before and lost some money.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So, just as a note, the better you are going, the more likely you may be facing distractions, deception and other trouble. Don&rsquo;t shut down because of it, and don&rsquo;t &ldquo;crawl back into your hole&rdquo;, that&#39;s exactly what the enemy wants. Use it to be wiser and bolder.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I contemplated praying for signs and wonders to bring others to God. Yet, my heart was not in it, the desire was there, but I know the conflict with what that desire was and a sufficiency in my heart, that God was saying to me, &ldquo;My grace is sufficient for you&rdquo;. God is saying to me to promote to others to seek the faith that will produce those signs and wonders, yet what I have given you is a wonder in itself. It is a wonder that these words come to me, and it is their due appearance, that is a sign in itself. The weight and pressure of the coming revival is about to overcome the barriers that hold it back. Comprehension of grace is one of the keys. We don&rsquo;t need a revival of legalism, of liberalism, of churchiness, of Pentecostalism. This Revival will start in hearts and be a revival of grace. People will begin to understand what has been forgotten and grow through those charisepignosis changes, thus removing the bushel (of sin) from the lamp (of Godliness). </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>So prayer should be constant </span><span class="c7">xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx add</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I shall finish this book with 3 prayers, sinners, grace and daily</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">27</span></p><h2 class="c30" id="h.w6mli845p5zo"><span class="c29 c26">Sell all to buy the field - what you value is in your heart</span></h2><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c17">27.1 Learning by discovery</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll lead into this last morsel with a thought: some people say they know a lot, others, like me, know so very little, yet I can learn more from a person who also knows almost nothing than I can from those who know it all. How little do I know? As mentioned a couple of times, I have been learning personally by writing this book. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I have started writing parts with a minor thought in mind, and in the explanation, have gone to spheres I hadn&rsquo;t thought of. God has been teaching me this by revealing it to me all the way through writing it. I know this is just a drop in the ocean, as it seems every page holds far more than the sentence or paragraph I had in mind to start with.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">My point from those two paragraphs. If I know so little as to be learning so much, then grab hold of charisepignosis with all three hands (clocks have three hands, so I&rsquo;ll let myself off with that one), yes, three hands, grab hold of those three survey points to triangulate where you&rsquo;re at and where you need to go. The word, relationship and service.</span></p><h3 class="c13" id="h.bqc8qwfg9e9y"><span>27.2 </span><span class="c33 c26">Are you spiritually and emotionally healthy?</span></h3><p class="c2"><span class="c1">How healthy is your relationship with God and your neighbour (all people). It&rsquo;s a spiritual journey, sure, but your relationships will assess it. Who&#39;s first in your life? God? And second? Here, I think Yeshua could have gone one step further: instead of &lsquo;love your neighbour as yourself&rsquo;, I think he could have rephrased it as &lsquo;love your neighbour above yourself&rsquo;. However, his explanation had similar implications.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The Parable of the Good Samaritan: Luke 10:25-37 (ISV)</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Just then, an expert in the Law stood up to test Jesus. He asked, &quot;Teacher, what must I do to inherit eternal life?&quot; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Jesus answered him, &quot;What is written in the Law? What do you read there?&quot; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">He answered, &quot;You must love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, with all your strength, and with all your mind. And you must love your neighbour as yourself.&quot; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Jesus told him, &quot;You have answered correctly. &#39;Do this, and you will live.&#39;&quot; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But the man wanted to justify himself, so he asked Jesus, &quot;And who is my neighbour?&quot; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">After careful consideration, Jesus replied, &quot;A man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho when he fell into the hands of bandits. They stripped him, beat him, and went away, leaving him half dead. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">By chance, a priest was travelling along that road. When he saw the man, he went by on the other side. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Similarly, a descendant of Levi came to that place. When he saw the man, he also went by on the other side. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">But as he was travelling along, a Samaritan came across the man. When the Samaritan saw him, he was moved with compassion. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">He went to him and bandaged his wounds, pouring oil and wine on them. Then he put him on his own animal, brought him to an inn, and took care of him. </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The next day, he took out two denarii and gave them to the innkeeper, saying, &#39;Take good care of him. If you spend more than that, I&#39;ll repay you when I come back.&#39; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">&quot;Of these three men, who do you think was a neighbour to the man who fell into the hands of the bandits?&quot; </span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">He said, &quot;The one who showed mercy to him.&quot; Jesus told him, &quot;Go and do what he did.&quot;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So Yeshua expressed in my words. Treat everyone as your neighbour and do all you can to take care of them at your expense. If we do that, in many cases, we will treat them better than we treat ourselves.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Your relationships directly affect your emotional and spiritual health; disrupt one, and the other will suffer along with it. A strong spiritual life will always sponsor emotional understanding and strength, yet our emotions can be strong without a spiritual life at all.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">So what do these look like? A strong spiritual health is a life with God on your mind, almost constantly. Of course, there are things that at times will take all of your concentration, such as doing difficult mathematical calculations. At other times, we can think quite easily about God and what God wants to express to us while doing something like riding a bike (as the riding becomes second nature and therefore the second thought), our primary thoughts can then be on Godly things. When we find ourselves thinking about God more every day, praying more, and seeking to read the Bible more. When we want to divert every conversation to God, if we can. Then there&rsquo;s evidence that this is a strong spiritual life. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">That strong spiritual life will affect your emotions, you will love more, be angered less, happier and more balanced overall when you are putting others first. On the other hand, we can have people who have learned emotional discipline that don&rsquo;t know God, so it can exist independent of Spiritual strength.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">27.3 Truth, not hype</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Are you spiritually and emotionally strong? Constantly thinking of God, Godly things and loving both God and people in your words and actions? Or is it all about you, your emotions, your desires, your needs, etc.? Do you want to be active for God or just a consumer Christian?</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I&rsquo;ll finish with the parable of a treasure. Beforehand, I&rsquo;ll mention people who in the past have presented messages by first building up their impact, using exaggerated expressions of how amazing or life-changing their message will be. Yet followed with a rather mediocre message along the lines of those preached many times previously. The promise of wonder if not followed by something to wonder about, to me is presenting it outside of the truth&hellip; a lie.</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">It&rsquo;s like offering &ldquo;fresh fruit&rdquo; and delivering stinking, rotting mush. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I seriously hope the message here did not carry a similar vein. That I&rsquo;d not built it up beyond its presentation, and it did deliver an expansion of understanding. If it does deserve some acclaim, that belongs to God after all, who is Joe Average beyond the average Joe? I am but doulos. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">27.4 The treasure in the field</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Yeshua told a parable of a treasure in a field. Matthew 13:44 &nbsp;&quot;The kingdom from heaven is like treasure hidden in a field that a man found and hid. In his excitement, he went and sold everything he had and bought that field.&quot; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">The implication is that its value is far more than the cost, and as mentioned, there certainly is an immense cost. The greatest cost a person can pay outside their physical life as you need to give your soul. You must give all you value most; not things, not money, but your life. Yet your life includes all you own. Nothing is yours anymore, but as a slave, all that is yours belongs to your master. In the natural world, a master owns a slave&#39;s life but doesn&rsquo;t own the slave&#39;s soul. In the service of God, you give him everything, starting with your soul, submitting your desires, thoughts, and everything about you. Few understand this and give no more than some attention and a little time. Part payments don&rsquo;t buy anything!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">27.5 Pride and surrender</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1Peter 5:5 &nbsp;In like manner, you young ones, be subject to elders, and all subjecting yourselves to one another; clothe yourselves with humble-mindedness, because God resists the proud, but He gives grace to the humble; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If I may expand, He resists even the slightest pride, and this may seem odd, but he resists the pride a person may have in their humility, &ldquo;OH I&rsquo;M nothing&rdquo; as said by some, displaying a sense that the statement is an honourable one.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span>After typing that last sentence, I remembered a person who said they were nothing, yet they seemed to have little understanding of grace and certainly stood against its presentation to people, as it was their belief that people need to be scared into heaven through the fear of hell. A lack of the very compassion and comprehension grace itself delivers. I now think of the &ldquo;</span><span class="c17">I&rsquo;M</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;right&rdquo; attitude, offering a sense of pride they had and still thought they were humble. Please understand that &ldquo;I&hellip; &ldquo; (anything) comes from pride, and so can the &ldquo;You&hellip;&rdquo; (anything hurtful). As in the sense I&rsquo;m trying to convey, the &ldquo;You (whatever)&rdquo; has likely come from being hurt, and you can&rsquo;t hurt an ego that doesn&rsquo;t exist.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">If you have not yet done so, sell your unfounded beliefs, sell all you hold dear (your ego, your pride, your needs, wants, selfish desires), give it all up to purchase that field (the rhema through metanoeo). Beyond a loose commitment, it is an explosion of comprehension that only comes with a real earnest sale of your soul to purchase life as a mere slave, yet serving the Lord of All. In such, the paradigm shifts keep coming like a volcano, starting with small explosions growing to a crescendo mass explosion, yet in God it never ends, as soon as you think you have a good comprehension of an aspect of God, he shows you more. Sure, you&rsquo;re committing to a life of mere service, but the fruit, the wisdom, the new purpose and so many other things are all worth it.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c7">27.6 Final challenge and prayers</span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">I hope you are challenged by this book. We need to be challenged, on the knifes edge, as that is where growth starts. If you&#39;re ready to take the next step, whatever that step may be, consider joining one of our upcoming events designed to support and inspire you on your path. Our events are crafted to provide guidance, build community, and deepen your understanding of ministry. Check out our events page to find the perfect opportunity to connect with others and gain the insight you need to move forward with clarity and confidence.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">Lastly, those prayers, as mentioned, are merely guides, as even prayer should not be so refined that it&rsquo;s religious (the exact same words every day). Treat these as examples; how to pray, not what to pray!</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">1. Holy Father, I come to you in Yeshua&#39;s name. I admit I&rsquo;m a sinner and can&rsquo;t pay for that sin, I ask you to forgive my sin, and I accept the sacrifice of Yeshua for my sin, and commit to him as lord and master of my life. I recognise my part being to stimulate your grace to change me and walk a Godly life, no longer for me, but for you. Amen</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">2. (This requires minimal words), &ldquo;Bring me grace, Lord,&rdquo; or &nbsp;&ldquo;Please increase Grace in my life, Lord, Amen&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c1">3. Father in heaven, you are holy, use me to spread your kingdom. Bring me knowledge, wisdom, fruit of the Spirit, courage, GRACE, revelation and the words to reveal that to others. Forgive me and teach me to forgive. Show me the path you have for me, keep me on it, push me along it, your will not mine. Supply the needs for this and intercept and disrupt any disturbances or evil, all for your glory, in Yeshua&#39;s name. Amen</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><h1 class="c54" id="h.a3q4jpn7ivji"><span class="c1">33 &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</span></h1><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1"></span></p></body></html>
